{"title_page": "Phidippus femoratus", "text_new": "{{taxobox\n|image= \n|image_caption= \n|regnum=[[Animal]]ia\n|phylum=[[Arthropod]]a\n|classis=[[Arachnid]]a\n|ordo=[[Spider|Araneae]]\n|familia=[[Jumping spider|Salticidae]]\n|genus=''[[Phidippus]]''\n|species='''''P. femoratus'''''\n|binomial=''Phidippus femoratus''\n|binomial_authority=[[George and Elizabeth Peckham]], 1901}}\n\n'''''Phidippus femoratus''''' is a species of [[spider]] in the family [[jumping spider|Salticidae]], found in the US states of [[New Mexico]], [[Arizona]] and [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://salticidae.org/salticid/diagnost/phidippu/femorat.htm|title=Phidippus femoratus|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=3671143|title=The Courtship Behavior of Phidippus femoratus (Araneae, Salticidae)|first=Robert R.|last=Jackson|date=1 January 1982|publisher=|journal=The Southwestern Naturalist|volume=27|issue=2|pages=187\u2013195|doi=10.2307/3671143}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7181619}}\n\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of the United States]]\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1901]]\n\n\n{{Salticidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{taxobox\n|image= \n|image_caption= \n|regnum=[[Animal]]ia\n|phylum=[[Arthropod]]a\n|classis=[[Arachnid]]a\n|ordo=[[Spider|Araneae]]\n|familia=[[Jumping spider|Salticidae]]\n|genus=''[[Phidippus]]''\n|species='''''P. femoratus'''''\n|binomial=''Phidippus femoratus''\n|binomial_authority=[[George and Elizabeth Peckham]], 1901}}\n\n'''''Phidippus femoratus''''' is a species of [[spider]] in the [[jumping spider|Salticidae]] family, that can be found in the US states of [[New Mexico]], [[Arizona]] and [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://salticidae.org/salticid/diagnost/phidippu/femorat.htm|title=Phidippus femoratus|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=3671143|title=The Courtship Behavior of Phidippus femoratus (Araneae, Salticidae)|first=Robert R.|last=Jackson|date=1 January 1982|publisher=|journal=The Southwestern Naturalist|volume=27|issue=2|pages=187\u2013195|doi=10.2307/3671143}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7181619}}\n\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of the United States]]\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1901]]\n\n\n{{Salticidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phidippus_femoratus"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 2003", "text_new": "{{short description|2003 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|title = MLS Cup 2003\n|year  = [[MLS Cup]]\n|image = MLS Cup 2003 logo.gif\n|team1 = [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|team1score = 2\n|team2 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|team2score = 4\n|date = November 23, 2003\n|stadium = [[Home Depot Center]]\n|city = [[Carson, California]], US\n|man_of_the_match1a = [[Landon Donovan]]<br />(San Jose Earthquakes) \n|weather = Sunny, {{convert|71|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n|attendance = 27,000 \n|referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n|previous = [[MLS Cup 2002|2002]]\n|next = [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2003''' was the eighth edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on November 23, 2003. It was hosted at the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], and was contested by the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] and the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] to decide the champion of the [[2003 Major League Soccer season|2003 season]]. Both teams had previously won the MLS Cup and were looking for their second championship.\n\nSan Jose defeated Chicago 4\u20132, clinching their second championship in three years; [[Landon Donovan]] scored two goals and was named the match's [[most valuable player]]. The match included a sequence of three goals scored within a five-minute period early in the second half and had the earliest goal scored in MLS Cup history, the competition's first [[own goal]], and the first [[penalty kick]] awarded in a final. It was also the highest-scoring final, with six goals in total.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:LA Galaxy vs Houston Dynamo- Western Conference Finals panorama.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Home Depot Center]], host of MLS Cup 2003 and home of the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]]]\n\nThe under construction [[Home Depot Center]] was announced as the venue of MLS Cup 2003 on February 27, 2002, a week after [[CMGI Field]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], was awarded the [[MLS Cup 2002|2002 final]].<ref name=\"MLS-2002\">{{cite press release |date=February 27, 2002 |title=Galaxy Awarded MLS Cup 2003 |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/la0227cup03.html |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020812053936/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/la0227cup03.html |archivedate=August 12, 2002 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The 27,000-seat stadium opened on June 7, 2003, as the centerpiece of a $140 million multi-sport complex in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Carson, California|Carson]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ortega |first=John |date=June 1, 2003 |title=Carson Hopes to Start on Right Track |page=B1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/01/sports/sp-track1 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The Home Depot Center is a [[soccer-specific stadium]] that was built to primarily serve as the home of the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=June 7, 2003 |title=Absolutely No Place Like Home for Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/07/sports/sp-galaxy7 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> It also hosted several matches during the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup]] in September and October, including the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|final match]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 13, 2003 |title=Germany Hoists Cup With Last Call |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/oct/13/sports/sp-wwc13 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 2003 edition was the second MLS Cup to be hosted in the Los Angeles area, following the [[MLS Cup '98|1998 cup]] at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California]], attended by 51,530 spectators.<ref name=\"MLS-2002\"/> The 2003 cup was attended by a sellout crowd of 27,000, including 500 [[San Jose Earthquakes]] supporters in the designated away section.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Donovan's Goals Lead San Jose to Second M.L.S. Title |page=D7 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/24/sports/soccer-donovan-s-goals-lead-san-jose-to-second-mls-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news |last=D'Hippolito |first=Joseph |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Donovan's double gives San Jose second MLS title |page=C12 |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2003-11-23-mls-cup_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Home Depot Center was selected to host later MLS Cups in [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]], [[MLS Cup 2008|2008]], and [[MLS Cup 2011|2011]] before neutral venues for the final were abolished.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=November 13, 2011 |title=Playoff system changes coming |page=C9 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/nov/12/sports/la-sp-baxter-soccer-20111113 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Almond |first=Elliott |date=October 4, 2012 |title=San Jose Earthquakes mull stadium options for MLS Cup |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/10/04/san-jose-earthquakes-mull-stadium-options-for-mls-cup/ |work=[[The Mercury News]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The stadium, later renamed the [[StubHub Center]], would go on to host the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2012|2012]] and [[MLS Cup 2014|2014]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Celani |first=Andrew |date=December 3, 2014 |title=9 Things To Know Ahead Of Revolution-Galaxy MLS Cup |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2014/12/03/9-things-to-know-ahead-of-revolution-galaxy-mls-cup/ |publisher=[[WBZ-TV|CBS Boston]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{main|2003 Major League Soccer season}}\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2003 Major League Soccer season|2003 season]] was the eighth in the league's history and was contested by ten teams in two conferences. Each team played a total of 30 matches in the regular season from April to October, facing teams within their conference four times, outside of their conference two times, and playing an additional set of games against a non-conference team.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031202192517/http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |archivedate=December 2, 2003 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref> The playoffs ran entirely within November and was contested by the top four teams in each conference, a change from the [[MLS Cup 2002|2002 playoffs]].<ref>{{cite news |date=November 20, 2002 |title=MLS to have longer season in 2003 |url=https://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2002/11/20/MLS-to-have-longer-season-in-2003/UPI-92071037845939/ |publisher=[[United Press International]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> It was organized into three rounds: a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away series]] in the Conference Semifinals with a winner determined by [[aggregate score]], followed by an [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] period and a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] if necessary; a single-match Conference Final; and the MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=October 2009 |title=MLS Cup 2009 Playoffs Guide |page=3 |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/pdf/mls/2009/playoffs/2009POguide.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119212135/http://web.mlsnet.com/pdf/mls/2009/playoffs/2009POguide.pdf |archivedate=January 19, 2010 |ref={{SfnRef|MLS Cup 2009 Playoffs Guide|2009}} |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 2003 was contested by the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], who also won the regular season's [[Supporters' Shield]] and the [[U.S. Open Cup]], and the [[San Jose Earthquakes]]. Both teams had previously won the MLS Cup and finished at the top of their respective conferences in regular season play, separated by a single point.<ref name=\"Munster-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Knapp |first=Kathryn L. |date=November 21, 2003 |title=Best championship yet? |page=C8 |work=[[The Times of Northwest Indiana|The Times]] |location=Munster, Indiana |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25422802/mls_cup_2003_best_championship_yet/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The two teams had not previously met in the playoffs.<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\">{{cite web |title=MLS Cup 2003 Preview: San Jose v. Chicago |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=preview&lang= |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031222094832/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=preview&lang= |archivedate=December 22, 2003 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Chicago and San Jose played three matches in the regular season, which ended in two scoreless draws and a 4\u20131 victory in May for the Fire at San Jose's [[Spartan Stadium (San Jose)|Spartan Stadium]].<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\"/><ref name=\"AP-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Armour |first=Nancy |date=November 21, 2003 |title=Despite big changes, Fire keeps winning |page=B5 |work=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|The Daily Chronicle]] |location=DeKalb, Illinois |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25423131/despite_big_changes_fire_keeps_winning/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Fire===\n\nThe Chicago Fire entered as one of the league's first two [[expansion team]]s in 1998, winning the [[MLS Cup 1998|MLS Cup]] and [[1998 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] in their inaugural season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ziehm |first=Len |date=October 31, 1998 |title=Fire adds title: MLS champ wins U.S. Open Cup |page=96 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Trecker |first=Jerry |date=October 25, 1998 |title=MLS' 3rd Year: It's A Good News, Bad News Thing |page=E8 |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1998-10-25-9810250312-story.html |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The team returned to the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2000|2000]], losing to the [[Kansas City Wizards]], and won the [[2000 U.S. Open Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 22, 2000 |title=Chicago's win vs. Miami makes up for MLS loss |page=B10 |work=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25463490/chicagos_win_vs_miami_makes_up_for/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The team finished the 2002 season as the third-placed seed in the Eastern Conference, its worst-ever performance,<ref name=\"Naperville\">{{cite news |last=Engel |first=Brad |date=November 21, 2003 |title=Blazing comeback; The Fire rises from last year's ashes to compete with San Jose for MLS Cup |page=62 |work=[[The Naperville Sun]]}}</ref> and were eliminated by the [[New England Revolution]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 3, 2002 |title=Extinguished |page=C1 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349160/extinguished/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Sarachan]] was hired to replace [[Bob Bradley]] as head coach and drafted several rookie players, including forwards [[Nate Jaqua]] and [[Damani Ralph]], and new acquisitions to bolster the team's existing lineup while offloading expensive veteran players.<ref name=\"SI-Fire\">{{cite news |date=November 20, 2003 |title=Chasing a triple |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/soccer/11/20/fire.mlscup.ap/index.html |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031207051654/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/soccer/11/20/fire.mlscup.ap/index.html |archivedate=December 7, 2003 |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Fire struggled with injuries to several starting players that led to several draws and losses early in the season, but scored key victories and won a Supporters' Shield title and the 2003 U.S. Open Cup.<ref name=\"Naperville\"/><ref name=\"SI-Fire\"/> Sarachan was named [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]] prior to the MLS Cup final, where a win would clinch a [[treble (association football)|treble]] for the first time in American soccer history.<ref name=\"Naperville\"/><ref name=\"CHI-2003\">{{cite web |title=MLS History: Chicago Fire, 2003 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/club/chicago/2003 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nChicago entered the playoffs as top seed and faced [[D.C. United]] in the Conference Semifinals. The team won 4\u20130 on aggregate with back-to-back 2\u20130 wins and advanced to face New England in the Conference Finals.<ref name=\"Tribune-Preview\">{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 23, 2003 |title=It's simple: The best against the best |page=1 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25408131/fire_1_win_from_mls_cup/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The match, played at [[Soldier Field]] in Chicago, was scoreless after regulation time and advanced to [[overtime (association football)|overtime]], where captain [[Chris Armas]] scored the [[golden goal]] in the 101st minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 15, 2003 |title=Armas scorches winner |page=1 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-11-15-0311150223-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Fire became the first team to reach an MLS Cup final without conceding a goal in the playoffs, earning three straight [[shutout]]s.<ref name=\"SA\">{{cite news |date=November 21, 2003 |title=MLS CUP: San Jose and Chicago meet Sunday in final |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/5287/mls-cup-san-jose-and-chicago-meet-sunday-in-final.html |work=[[Soccer America]] |url-access=subscription |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===San Jose Earthquakes===\n{{main|2003 San Jose Earthquakes season}}\n\nThe San Jose Earthquakes (originally the [[San Jose Clash]]) participated in the [[1996 MLS Cup Playoffs|inaugural edition]] of the playoffs in 1996, but failed to qualify for four subsequent seasons.<ref name=\"NYT-SJ2001\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Agoos Leads San Jose Into M.L.S. Title Game |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/21/sports/soccer-agoos-leads-san-jose-into-mls-title-game.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SJ-History\">{{cite web |title=Club History |url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/club/history |publisher=[[San Jose Earthquakes]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> After finishing the 2000 season in last place, [[Frank Yallop]] was hired as the club's fifth head coach in 2001, taking the retiring [[Dominic Kinnear]] as his assistant. The team was bolstered by the acquisition of veteran defender [[Jeff Agoos]], striker [[Dwayne De Rosario]], and teenage forward [[Landon Donovan]].<ref name=\"SJ-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Trecker |first=Jerry |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Galaxy's Time With Donovan, Agoos? |page=E16 |work=Hartford Courant}}</ref> The Earthquakes went on a 12-match unbeaten streak and won their [[MLS Cup 2001|first MLS Cup]] over the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], their in-state rivals.<ref name=\"NYT-SJ2001\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 22, 2001 |title=San Jose Breaks Down Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/22/sports/sp-60149 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> San Jose finished the 2002 season in second place, behind the Galaxy, but were eliminated by the [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref name=\"SJ-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=September 29, 2002 |title=McBride's goal boosts Crew |page=D1 |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes acquired several rookie players in the [[2003 MLS SuperDraft|2003 SuperDraft]], including midfielder [[Todd Dunivant]], forward [[Jamil Walker]], and goalkeeper [[Josh Saunders]], capping a busy off-season that saw the departure of several veteran players. San Jose began the season with a six-match unbeaten streak and continued to stay atop the Western Conference standings despite injuries to several key players and absences due to national team call-ups.<ref>{{cite web |date=November 18, 2003 |title=MLS Cup 2003 Preview: San Jose Earthquakes |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1118sj.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031204204522/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1118sj.html |archivedate=December 4, 2003 |accessdate=November 16, 2003}}</ref> The team held on to finish second overall behind the Chicago Fire with 51 points, with Landon Donovan leading the team's scoring with 12 goals and [[Pat Onstad]] setting new goalkeeping records for the club.<ref name=\"SJ-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 22, 2003 |title=In a pinch, Donovan delivers |page=6 |work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\nSan Jose were paired with rivals Los Angeles in the Conference Semifinals and lost the away leg 2\u20130, conceding goals to [[Sasha Victorine]] and [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]] after a halftime skirmish.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=November 2, 2003 |title=Galaxy Shows It Has Plenty of Playoff Fight |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/02/sports/sp-galaxy2 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy's extended their aggregate lead to 4\u20130 during the first 13 minutes of the second leg at [[Spartan Stadium (San Jose)|Spartan Stadium]] on November 9, but the Earthquakes responded by scoring four unanswered goals to tie the match 4\u20134 on aggregate, including a last-minute header from defender [[Chris Roner]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=November 10, 2003 |title=Galaxy Really at a Loss |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/10/sports/sp-galaxy10 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> San Jose clinched their series victory with a golden goal scored by substitute forward [[Rodrigo Faria]] in the 96th minute,<ref>{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |date=November 10, 2003 |title=Down by 2, 4, then...; 5 goals push Quakes onward |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> capping a comeback in what was called one of the greatest matches in MLS history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |authorlink=Grant Wahl |date=November 11, 2003 |title=\u00a1\u00a1\u00a1Es un cl\u00e1sico!!! |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/writers/grant_wahl/11/10/mls.classic/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040218234623/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/writers/grant_wahl/11/10/mls.classic/index.html |archivedate=February 18, 2004 |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carlisle |first=Jeff |date=November 25, 2015 |title=San Jose, New England top list of all-time greatest MLS playoff comebacks |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/19/blog/post/2726933/san-jose-new-england-top-list-of-greatest-mls-comebacks |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> In the Conference Final against the [[Kansas City Wizards]] on November 15, San Jose conceded the first goal and rallied to equalize before trailing 2\u20131. Earthquakes midfielder [[Brian Mullan]] then equalized again and sent the match to overtime, where Landon Donovan scored a golden goal in the 117th minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=Killion |first=Ann |date=November 16, 2003 |title=Donovan's OT goal puts cup in reach |page=C1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]'''||'''30'''||'''15'''||'''7'''||'''8'''||'''53'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[New England Revolution]]||30||12||9||9||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|MetroStars]]||30||11||10||9||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|4||align=left|[[D.C. United]]||30||10||11||9||'''39'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]]||30||10||12||8||38\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2003 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2003 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[San Jose Earthquakes]]'''||'''30'''||'''14'''||'''7'''||'''9'''||'''51'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||30||11||10||9||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||30||11||12||7||'''40'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|4||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||30||9||12||9||'''36'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||30||6||19||5||23\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2003 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|[[2003 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|4\u20130\n|2\u20130 (A)\n|2\u20130 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|5\u20134\n|0\u20132 (A)\n|5\u20132 {{aet}} (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[New England Revolution]]\n|colspan=3|1\u20130 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Final\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|colspan=3|3\u20132 (H)\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Broadcasting and entertainment==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]]. English play-by-play commentary was provided by [[JP Dellacamera]] with color analysis by [[Ty Keough]], reprising their roles at [[MLS Cup 2002]]. Play-by-play commentator [[Ernesto Motta]] returned from the previous cup's Spanish-language broadcast, working alongside color analyst Robert Sierra. ABC/ESPN provided a total of 20 cameras, including aerial coverage from a [[Goodyear Blimp]]. The match was also broadcast live on radio within the U.S. on [[Sports Byline USA]] in English and [[Radio Unica]] in Spanish, and on the [[American Forces Radio Network]] internationally.<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 19, 2003 |title=MLS Cup 2003 Broadcast Set |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1119broadcast.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031122084651/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1119broadcast.html |archivedate=November 22, 2003 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref> The ABC broadcast earned a [[Nielsen rating]] of 0.6, the lowest figure recorded for an MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=December 4, 2012 |title=MLS Cup television ratings dip |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/49487/mls-cup-television-ratings-dip.html |work=Soccer America |url-access=subscription |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe match's halftime show featured singer [[Michelle Branch]], who performed her hit single \"[[Breathe (Michelle Branch song)|Breathe]]\".<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 12, 2003 |title=Michelle Branch to Perform at 2003 MLS Cup Halftime Show |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1110branch.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031119031007/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1110branch.html |archivedate=November 19, 2003 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Castillo |first=Arielle |date=December 5, 2013 |title=MLS Cup 2015: a #TBT look at musical performers of Cups past |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/12/03/mls-cup-2015-tbt-look-musical-performers-cups-past-sideline |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:LandonDonovan1.jpg|thumb|right|San Jose forward [[Landon Donovan]] scored two goals and was named match [[most valuable player|MVP]] at MLS Cup 2003|x260px]]\n\nReferee of the Year [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]] was chosen to officiate the match and was previously the head referee at [[MLS Cup 1997]].<ref name=\"SA\"/> At kickoff, set for 12:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]], the weather in Carson was sunny with a temperature of {{convert|71|F|C}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=December 10, 2016 |title=Will Toronto FC vs. Seattle Sounders be the coldest MLS Cup on record? |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/12/10/will-toronto-fc-vs-seattle-sounders-be-coldest-mls-cup-record |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Both teams fielded their regular lineups arranged in a 4\u20134\u20132 [[Formation (association football)|formation]].<ref name=\"Mercury-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |date=November 23, 2003 |title=After a baffling journey, Quakes at the doorstep |page=C1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes kicked off the match and made a series of attacks that won them a [[direct free kick|free kick]] outside of the penalty box. After a faked shot by [[Jeff Agoos]], Danish midfielder [[Ronnie Ekelund]] drove the ball past the defensive wall and scored the first goal of the final, tying the record for fastest MLS Cup goal.<ref name=\"Tribune-Thunder\">{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Quakes steal Fire's thunder |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-11-24-0311240165-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Chicago had the majority of possession and chances in the first half, including two shots that were missed by striker [[Ante Razov]] and a poor touch by [[Damani Ralph]], but eventually conceded a second goal to San Jose.<ref name=\"Post\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Donovan Fills Up San Jose's Cup |page=D4 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A8624-2003Nov23.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Summary\">{{cite news |date=November 23, 2003 |title=San Jose Earns MLS Cup 2003 Title |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=recap&lang= |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031208163435/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=recap&lang= |archivedate=December 8, 2003 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> An Earthquakes counter-attack in the 38th minute sprung [[Jamil Walker]], who sent a through-pass to [[Landon Donovan]], who sprinted pass several defenders and shot the ball past goalkeeper [[Zach Thornton]].<ref name=\"SunTimes\">{{cite news |last=Padilla |first=Doug |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Leaky Fire falls in MLS Cup |work=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref>\n\nThe second half opened with a sequence of three goals by both teams within five minutes, beginning with a short pass by [[Andy Williams (Jamaican footballer)|Andy Williams]] to [[DaMarcus Beasley]] that was shot into the near side of the goal, cutting San Jose's lead to 2\u20131.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Earthquakes Win MLS Cup |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/24/sports/sp-mls24 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Shortly after kickoff, a long overhead pass by [[Brian Mullan]] found Earthquakes midfielder [[Richard Mulrooney]], who scored and restored the Earthquakes' two-goal lead.<ref name=\"SF-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=November 24, 2003 |title=MLS Cup: Earthquakes rumble; Donovan, Onstad secure S.J.'s 2nd title |page=C1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/MLS-CUP-Earthquakes-rumble-Donovan-Onstad-2548067.php |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The Fire continued to press for a second goal and earned a throw-in near San Jose's goal that led to a cross into the box by [[Evan Whitfield]]. The cross was deflected into the goal by Earthquakes defender [[Chris Roner]], who had been substituted three minutes earlier, narrowing the team's lead to 3\u20132 in the 54th minute.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> Roner then conceded a [[penalty kick]] to the Earthquakes two minutes later after a tackle from behind on Damani Ralph in the penalty area.<ref name=\"Post\"/> Ante Razov took the penalty kick, the first in MLS Cup history,<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> but it was saved by goalkeeper Pat Onstad with a dive to his right side to catch the ball.<ref name=\"SF-Summary\"/>\n\nRazov attempted to score an equalizing goal in the 58th minute, taking a shot in front of Onstad that grazed the corner of the net. San Jose forward Jamil Walker suffered an injury and was replaced in the 60th minute by [[Dwayne DeRosario]], who sized on a mis-cleared ball from Chicago ten minutes later and sent a cross into the box that was finished by Landon Donovan, giving the Earthquakes a 4\u20132 lead in the 71st minute.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> With the goal, Donovan became the first player to score two goals in an MLS Cup.<ref name=\"SF-Summary\"/> A chance for Chicago to reduce San Jose's lead came from a cross by Ralph in the 82nd minute that rolled across the six-yard box, but the tap-in for Razov was missed and the ball continued out of bounds.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> Ralph also had a chance to score a consolation goal in the third minute of [[stoppage time]], a cross by [[Nate Jaqua]] that he headed wide in front of the goal.<ref name=\"Post\"/> Despite having fewer shots and corner kicks, the San Jose Earthquakes won the match 4\u20132 and earned their second championship in three years.<ref name=\"Post\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n|date=November 23, 2003\n|time=12:30 [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|team1=[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|score=2\u20134\n|report=https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2003\n|team2=[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|goals1=\n*[[DaMarcus Beasley|Beasley]] {{goal|49}}\n*[[Chris Roner|Roner]] {{goal|54|o.g.}}\n|goals2=\n*[[Ronnie Ekelund|Ekelund]] {{goal|5}}\n*[[Landon Donovan|Donovan]] {{goal|38||71}}\n*[[Richard Mulrooney|Mulrooney]] {{goal|50}}\n|stadium=[[Home Depot Center]]\n|location=[[Carson, California]]\n|attendance=27,000\n|referee=[[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''CHICAGO FIRE:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Zach Thornton]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Evan Whitfield]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jim Curtin]] || || {{suboff|81}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Carlos Bocanegra]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Orlando Perez]] || || {{suboff|45}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Andy Williams (Jamaican footballer)|Andy Williams]] || || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jesse Marsch]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Armas]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[DaMarcus Beasley]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Damani Ralph]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ante Razov]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Curtis Spiteri]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[C. J. Brown]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kelly Gray]] || || {{subon|45}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Logan Pause]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Justin Mapp]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|CRC}} [[Jonathan Bola\u00f1os]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ryan Futagaki]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Nate Jaqua]] || || {{subon|81}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|BOT}} [[Dipsy Selolwane]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Dave Sarachan]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''SAN JOSE EARTHQUAKES:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Pat Onstad]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Craig Waibel]] || {{yel|15}} || {{suboff|51}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Troy Dayak]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Robinson (soccer)|Eddie Robinson]] || {{yel|54}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''9'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Mullan]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richard Mulrooney]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Ronnie Ekelund]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Manny Lagos]] || || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Landon Donovan]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jamil Walker]] || || {{suboff|60}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jon Conway]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''30'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Josh Saunders]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ramiro Corrales]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Todd Dunivant]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Roner]] || || {{subon|51}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]] || || {{subon|60}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Roger Levesque]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Rodrigo Faria]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Frank Yallop]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Landon Donovan]] (San Jose Earthquakes)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Craig Lowry\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Darren Engers\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Noel Kenny]]\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still tied.\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+Statistics<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px;\"|\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px;\"| {{nowrap|Chicago Fire}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px;\"| {{nowrap|San Jose}}<br />Earthquakes\n|-\n|scope=row|Goals scored\n| 2\n| 4\n|-\n|scope=row|Total shots\n| 22\n| 11\n|-\n|scope=row|Shots on target\n| 10\n| 7\n|-\n|scope=row|Saves\n| 4\n| 8\n|-\n|scope=row|Corner kicks\n| 13\n| 3\n|-\n|scope=row|Fouls committed\n| 17\n| 14\n|-\n|scope=row|Offsides\n| 4\n| 3\n|-\n|scope=row|Yellow cards\n| 0\n| 2\n|-\n|scope=row|Red cards\n| 0\n| 0\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe San Jose Earthquakes became the second team in league history to win multiple MLS Cups, following [[D.C. United]]'s three titles in the 1990s.<ref name=\"NYT\"/> The six-goal 2003 final was the highest-scoring in MLS Cup history, beating the five-goal [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural edition]], and featured its earliest goal, its first [[own goal]], and its first awarded [[penalty kick]].<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Summary\"/> The own goal and penalty kick were both caused by Earthquakes defender [[Chris Roner]], who would undergo ankle surgery at the end of the season that ultimately led to the end of his playing career.<ref>{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=February 13, 2012 |title=What Ever Happened To ... Chris Roner |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2012/02/13/what-ever-happened-chris-roner |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref> [[Landon Donovan]] became the first player to score multiple goals in an MLS Cup final and was named the match's [[most valuable player]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Peters |first=Ken |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Earthquakes win MLS Cup |page=D6 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/540034901/Earthquakes-win-MLS-Cup.html |work=[[Deseret News]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> San Jose captain Jeff Agoos won his fifth MLS Cup, having played in six previous finals for the Earthquakes and D.C. United.<ref name=\"LAT-Summary\"/>\n\nSan Jose qualified for the [[2004 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] as MLS Cup champions, while Chicago also qualified as Supporters' Shield champion.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 30, 2003 |title=Champions Cup |page=D8 |work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The Earthquakes were eliminated in the quarterfinals by eventual champions [[Liga Deportiva Alajuelense|Alajuelense]], while the Fire were defeated by [[Deportivo Saprissa]] in the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 19, 2004 |title=Costa Rica impone su ley en la Concacaf |language=Spanish |trans-title=Costa Rica imposes its law in CONCACAF |url=https://es.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2004/m=4/news=costa-rica-impone-ley-concacaf-91312.html |publisher=[[FIFA.com]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> Both teams have yet to make an appearance at the MLS Cup final since 2003;<ref>{{cite news |last=Reineking |first=Jim |date=December 7, 2017 |title=MLS Cup: Ranking every championship game |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2017/12/06/mls-cup-ranking-every-game/926051001/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> two years after the cup, the Earthquakes were placed on hiatus and replaced by the [[Houston Dynamo]], who would win back-to-back MLS Cups in their first two seasons before San Jose was reinstated in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 17, 2007 |title=Garber paints a bright picture |page=E7 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25463830/garber_paints_a_bright_picture/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=November 19, 2007 |title=Houston parties after second MLS title |page=B1 |work=[[Santa Maria Times]]}}</ref> The first domestic treble in MLS history was ultimately won in [[2017 Major League Soccer season|2017]] by [[Toronto FC]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Boisvert |first=Nick |date=February 16, 2018 |title=After a record-setting season, TFC sets its sights on a Champions League title |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tfc-champions-league-1.4539194 |work=CBC News |accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{San Jose Earthquakes matches}}\n{{Chicago Fire FC matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2003 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:2003 Major League Soccer season|*MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes matches|MLS Cup 2003]]\n[[Category:Chicago Fire FC matches|MLS Cup 2003]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Carson, California]]\n[[Category:November 2003 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2003 in sports in California]]\n[[Category:21st century in Carson, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2003 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|title = MLS Cup 2003\n|year  = [[MLS Cup]]\n|image = MLS Cup 2003 logo.gif\n|team1 = [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|team1score = 2\n|team2 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|team2score = 4\n|date = November 23, 2003\n|stadium = [[Home Depot Center]]\n|city = [[Carson, California]], US\n|man_of_the_match1a = [[Landon Donovan]]<br />(San Jose Earthquakes) \n|weather = Sunny, {{convert|71|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n|attendance = 27,000 \n|referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n|previous = [[MLS Cup 2002|2002]]\n|next = [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2003''' was the eighth edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on November 23, 2003. It was hosted at the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], and was contested by the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] and the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] to decide the champion of the [[2003 Major League Soccer season|2003 season]]. Both teams had previously won the MLS Cup and were looking for their second championship.\n\nSan Jose defeated Chicago 4\u20132, clinching their second championship in three years; [[Landon Donovan]] scored two goals and was named the match's [[most valuable player]]. The match included a sequence of three goals scored within a five-minute period early in the second half and had the earliest goal scored in MLS Cup history, the competition's first [[own goal]], and the first [[penalty kick]] awarded in a final. It was also the highest-scoring final, with six goals in total.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:LA Galaxy vs Houston Dynamo- Western Conference Finals panorama.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Home Depot Center]], host of MLS Cup 2003 and home of the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]]]\n\nThe under construction [[Home Depot Center]] was announced as the venue of MLS Cup 2003 on February 27, 2002, a week after [[CMGI Field]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], was awarded the [[MLS Cup 2002|2002 final]].<ref name=\"MLS-2002\">{{cite press release |date=February 27, 2002 |title=Galaxy Awarded MLS Cup 2003 |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/la0227cup03.html |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020812053936/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/la0227cup03.html |archivedate=August 12, 2002 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The 27,000-seat stadium opened on June 7, 2003, as the centerpiece of a $140 million multi-sport complex in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Carson, California|Carson]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ortega |first=John |date=June 1, 2003 |title=Carson Hopes to Start on Right Track |page=B1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/01/sports/sp-track1 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The Home Depot Center is a [[soccer-specific stadium]] that was built to primarily serve as the home of the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=June 7, 2003 |title=Absolutely No Place Like Home for Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/07/sports/sp-galaxy7 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> It also hosted several matches during the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup]] in September and October, including the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|final match]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 13, 2003 |title=Germany Hoists Cup With Last Call |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/oct/13/sports/sp-wwc13 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 2003 edition was the second MLS Cup to be hosted in the Los Angeles area, following the [[MLS Cup '98|1998 cup]] at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California]], attended by 51,530 spectators.<ref name=\"MLS-2002\"/> The 2003 cup was attended by a sellout crowd of 27,000, including 500 [[San Jose Earthquakes]] supporters in the designated away section.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Donovan's Goals Lead San Jose to Second M.L.S. Title |page=D7 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/24/sports/soccer-donovan-s-goals-lead-san-jose-to-second-mls-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news |last=D'Hippolito |first=Joseph |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Donovan's double gives San Jose second MLS title |page=C12 |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2003-11-23-mls-cup_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Home Depot Center was selected to host later MLS Cups in [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]], [[MLS Cup 2008|2008]], and [[MLS Cup 2011|2011]] before neutral venues for the final were abolished.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=November 13, 2011 |title=Playoff system changes coming |page=C9 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/nov/12/sports/la-sp-baxter-soccer-20111113 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Almond |first=Elliott |date=October 4, 2012 |title=San Jose Earthquakes mull stadium options for MLS Cup |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/10/04/san-jose-earthquakes-mull-stadium-options-for-mls-cup/ |work=[[The Mercury News]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The stadium, later renamed the [[StubHub Center]], would go on to host the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2012|2012]] and [[MLS Cup 2014|2014]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Celani |first=Andrew |date=December 3, 2014 |title=9 Things To Know Ahead Of Revolution-Galaxy MLS Cup |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2014/12/03/9-things-to-know-ahead-of-revolution-galaxy-mls-cup/ |publisher=[[WBZ-TV|CBS Boston]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{main|2003 Major League Soccer season}}\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2003 Major League Soccer season|2003 season]] was the eighth in the league's history and was contested by ten teams in two conferences. Each team played a total of 30 matches in the regular season from April to October, facing teams within their conference four times, outside of their conference two times, and playing an additional set of games against a non-conference team.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031202192517/http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |archivedate=December 2, 2003 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref> The playoffs ran entirely within November and was contested by the top four teams in each conference, a change from the [[MLS Cup 2002|2002 playoffs]].<ref>{{cite news |date=November 20, 2002 |title=MLS to have longer season in 2003 |url=https://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2002/11/20/MLS-to-have-longer-season-in-2003/UPI-92071037845939/ |publisher=[[United Press International]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> It was organized into three rounds: a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away series]] in the Conference Semifinals with a winner determined by [[aggregate score]], followed by an [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] period and a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] if necessary; a single-match Conference Final; and the MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=October 2009 |title=MLS Cup 2009 Playoffs Guide |page=3 |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/pdf/mls/2009/playoffs/2009POguide.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119212135/http://web.mlsnet.com/pdf/mls/2009/playoffs/2009POguide.pdf |archivedate=January 19, 2010 |ref={{SfnRef|MLS Cup 2009 Playoffs Guide|2009}} |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 2003 was contested by the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], who also won the regular season's [[Supporters' Shield]] and the [[U.S. Open Cup]], and the [[San Jose Earthquakes]]. Both teams had previously won the MLS Cup and finished at the top of their respective conferences in regular season play, separated by a single point.<ref name=\"Munster-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Knapp |first=Kathryn L. |date=November 21, 2003 |title=Best championship yet? |page=C8 |work=[[The Times of Northwest Indiana|The Times]] |location=Munster, Indiana |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25422802/mls_cup_2003_best_championship_yet/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The two teams had not previously met in the playoffs.<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\">{{cite web |title=MLS Cup 2003 Preview: San Jose v. Chicago |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=preview&lang= |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031222094832/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=preview&lang= |archivedate=December 22, 2003 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Chicago and San Jose played three matches in the regular season, which ended in two scoreless draws and a 4\u20131 victory in May for the Fire at San Jose's [[Spartan Stadium (San Jose)|Spartan Stadium]].<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\"/><ref name=\"AP-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Armour |first=Nancy |date=November 21, 2003 |title=Despite big changes, Fire keeps winning |page=B5 |work=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|The Daily Chronicle]] |location=DeKalb, Illinois |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25423131/despite_big_changes_fire_keeps_winning/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Fire===\n\nThe Chicago Fire entered as one of the league's first two [[expansion team]]s in 1998, winning the [[MLS Cup 1998|MLS Cup]] and [[1998 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] in their inaugural season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ziehm |first=Len |date=October 31, 1998 |title=Fire adds title: MLS champ wins U.S. Open Cup |page=96 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Trecker |first=Jerry |date=October 25, 1998 |title=MLS' 3rd Year: It's A Good News, Bad News Thing |page=E8 |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1998-10-25-9810250312-story.html |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The team returned to the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2000|2000]], losing to the [[Kansas City Wizards]], and won the [[2000 U.S. Open Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |date=October 22, 2000 |title=Chicago's win vs. Miami makes up for MLS loss |page=B10 |work=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25463490/chicagos_win_vs_miami_makes_up_for/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The team finished the 2002 season as the third-placed seed in the Eastern Conference, its worst-ever performance,<ref name=\"Naperville\">{{cite news |last=Engel |first=Brad |date=November 21, 2003 |title=Blazing comeback; The Fire rises from last year's ashes to compete with San Jose for MLS Cup |page=62 |work=[[The Naperville Sun]]}}</ref> and were eliminated by the [[New England Revolution]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 3, 2002 |title=Extinguished |page=C1 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349160/extinguished/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Sarachan]] was hired to replace [[Bob Bradley]] as head coach and drafted several rookie players, including forwards [[Nate Jaqua]] and [[Damani Ralph]], and new acquisitions to bolster the team's existing lineup while offloading expensive veteran players.<ref name=\"SI-Fire\">{{cite news |date=November 20, 2003 |title=Chasing a triple |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/soccer/11/20/fire.mlscup.ap/index.html |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031207051654/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/soccer/11/20/fire.mlscup.ap/index.html |archivedate=December 7, 2003 |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Fire struggled with injuries to several starting players that led to several draws and losses early in the season, but scored key victories and won a Supporters' Shield title and the 2003 U.S. Open Cup.<ref name=\"Naperville\"/><ref name=\"SI-Fire\"/> Sarachan was named [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]] prior to the MLS Cup final, where a win would clinch a [[treble (association football)|treble]] for the first time in American soccer history.<ref name=\"Naperville\"/><ref name=\"CHI-2003\">{{cite web |title=MLS History: Chicago Fire, 2003 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/club/chicago/2003 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nChicago entered the playoffs as top seed and faced [[D.C. United]] in the Conference Semifinals. The team won 4\u20130 on aggregate with back-to-back 2\u20130 wins and advanced to face New England in the Conference Finals.<ref name=\"Tribune-Preview\">{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 23, 2003 |title=It's simple: The best against the best |page=1 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25408131/fire_1_win_from_mls_cup/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The match, played at [[Soldier Field]] in Chicago, was scoreless after regulation time and advanced to [[overtime (association football)|overtime]], where captain [[Chris Armas]] scored the [[golden goal]] in the 101st minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 15, 2003 |title=Armas scorches winner |page=1 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-11-15-0311150223-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Fire became the first team to reach an MLS Cup final without conceding a goal in the playoffs, earning three straight [[shutout]]s.<ref name=\"SA\">{{cite news |date=November 21, 2003 |title=MLS CUP: San Jose and Chicago meet Sunday in final |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/5287/mls-cup-san-jose-and-chicago-meet-sunday-in-final.html |work=[[Soccer America]] |url-access=subscription |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===San Jose Earthquakes===\n{{main|2003 San Jose Earthquakes season}}\n\nThe San Jose Earthquakes (originally the [[San Jose Clash]]) participated in the [[1996 MLS Cup Playoffs|inaugural edition]] of the playoffs in 1996, but failed to qualify for four subsequent seasons.<ref name=\"NYT-SJ2001\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Agoos Leads San Jose Into M.L.S. Title Game |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/21/sports/soccer-agoos-leads-san-jose-into-mls-title-game.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SJ-History\">{{cite web |title=Club History |url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/club/history |publisher=[[San Jose Earthquakes]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> After finishing the 2000 season in last place, [[Frank Yallop]] was hired as the club's fifth head coach in 2001, taking the retiring [[Dominic Kinnear]] as his assistant. The team was bolstered by the acquisition of veteran defender [[Jeff Agoos]], striker [[Dwayne De Rosario]], and teenage forward [[Landon Donovan]].<ref name=\"SJ-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Trecker |first=Jerry |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Galaxy's Time With Donovan, Agoos? |page=E16 |work=Hartford Courant}}</ref> The Earthquakes went on a 12-match unbeaten streak and won their [[MLS Cup 2001|first MLS Cup]] over the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], their in-state rivals.<ref name=\"NYT-SJ2001\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 22, 2001 |title=San Jose Breaks Down Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/22/sports/sp-60149 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> San Jose finished the 2002 season in second place, behind the Galaxy, but were eliminated by the [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref name=\"SJ-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=September 29, 2002 |title=McBride's goal boosts Crew |page=D1 |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes acquired several rookie players in the [[2003 MLS SuperDraft|2003 SuperDraft]], including midfielder [[Todd Dunivant]], forward [[Jamil Walker]], and goalkeeper [[Josh Saunders]], capping a busy off-season that saw the departure of several veteran players. San Jose began the season with a six-match unbeaten streak and continued to stay atop the Western Conference standings despite injuries to several key players and absences due to national team call-ups.<ref>{{cite web |date=November 18, 2003 |title=MLS Cup 2003 Preview: San Jose Earthquakes |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1118sj.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031204204522/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1118sj.html |archivedate=December 4, 2003 |accessdate=November 16, 2003}}</ref> The team held on to finish second overall behind the Chicago Fire with 51 points, with Landon Donovan leading the team's scoring with 12 goals and [[Pat Onstad]] setting new goalkeeping records for the club.<ref name=\"SJ-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 22, 2003 |title=In a pinch, Donovan delivers |page=6 |work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\nSan Jose were paired with rivals Los Angeles in the Conference Semifinals and lost the away leg 2\u20130, conceding goals to [[Sasha Victorine]] and [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]] after a halftime skirmish.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=November 2, 2003 |title=Galaxy Shows It Has Plenty of Playoff Fight |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/02/sports/sp-galaxy2 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy's extended their aggregate lead to 4\u20130 during the first 13 minutes of the second leg at [[Spartan Stadium (San Jose)|Spartan Stadium]] on November 9, but the Earthquakes responded by scoring four unanswered goals to tie the match 4\u20134 on aggregate, including a last-minute header from defender [[Chris Roner]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=November 10, 2003 |title=Galaxy Really at a Loss |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/10/sports/sp-galaxy10 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> San Jose clinched their series victory with a golden goal scored by substitute forward [[Rodrigo Faria]] in the 96th minute,<ref>{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |date=November 10, 2003 |title=Down by 2, 4, then...; 5 goals push Quakes onward |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> capping a comeback in what was called one of the greatest matches in MLS history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |authorlink=Grant Wahl |date=November 11, 2003 |title=\u00a1\u00a1\u00a1Es un cl\u00e1sico!!! |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/writers/grant_wahl/11/10/mls.classic/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040218234623/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2003/writers/grant_wahl/11/10/mls.classic/index.html |archivedate=February 18, 2004 |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carlisle |first=Jeff |date=November 25, 2015 |title=San Jose, New England top list of all-time greatest MLS playoff comebacks |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/19/blog/post/2726933/san-jose-new-england-top-list-of-greatest-mls-comebacks |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> In the Conference Final against the [[Kansas City Wizards]] on November 15, San Jose conceded the first goal and rallied to equalize before trailing 2\u20131. Earthquakes midfielder [[Brian Mullan]] then equalized again and sent the match to overtime, where Landon Donovan scored a golden goal in the 117th minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=Killion |first=Ann |date=November 16, 2003 |title=Donovan's OT goal puts cup in reach |page=C1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]'''||'''30'''||'''15'''||'''7'''||'''8'''||'''53'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[New England Revolution]]||30||12||9||9||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|MetroStars]]||30||11||10||9||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|4||align=left|[[D.C. United]]||30||10||11||9||'''39'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]]||30||10||12||8||38\n|}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2003 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[San Jose Earthquakes]]'''||'''30'''||'''14'''||'''7'''||'''9'''||'''51'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||30||11||10||9||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||30||11||12||7||'''40'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|4||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||30||9||12||9||'''36'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||30||6||19||5||23\n|}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|[[2003 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|4\u20130\n|2\u20130 (A)\n|2\u20130 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|5\u20134\n|0\u20132 (A)\n|5\u20132 {{aet}} (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[New England Revolution]]\n|colspan=3|1\u20130 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Final\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|colspan=3|3\u20132 (H)\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Broadcasting and entertainment==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]]. English play-by-play commentary was provided by [[JP Dellacamera]] with color analysis by [[Ty Keough]], reprising their roles at [[MLS Cup 2002]]. Play-by-play commentator [[Ernesto Motta]] returned from the previous cup's Spanish-language broadcast, working alongside color analyst Robert Sierra. ABC/ESPN provided a total of 20 cameras, including aerial coverage from a [[Goodyear Blimp]]. The match was also broadcast live on radio within the U.S. on [[Sports Byline USA]] in English and [[Radio Unica]] in Spanish, and on the [[American Forces Radio Network]] internationally.<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 19, 2003 |title=MLS Cup 2003 Broadcast Set |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1119broadcast.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031122084651/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1119broadcast.html |archivedate=November 22, 2003 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref> The ABC broadcast earned a [[Nielsen rating]] of 0.6, the lowest figure recorded for an MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=December 4, 2012 |title=MLS Cup television ratings dip |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/49487/mls-cup-television-ratings-dip.html |work=Soccer America |url-access=subscription |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe match's halftime show featured singer [[Michelle Branch]], who performed her hit single \"[[Breathe (Michelle Branch song)|Breathe]]\".<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 12, 2003 |title=Michelle Branch to Perform at 2003 MLS Cup Halftime Show |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1110branch.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031119031007/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/2003/mlscup1110branch.html |archivedate=November 19, 2003 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Castillo |first=Arielle |date=December 5, 2013 |title=MLS Cup 2015: a #TBT look at musical performers of Cups past |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/12/03/mls-cup-2015-tbt-look-musical-performers-cups-past-sideline |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:LandonDonovan1.jpg|thumb|right|San Jose forward [[Landon Donovan]] scored two goals and was named match [[most valuable player|MVP]] at MLS Cup 2003|x260px]]\n\nReferee of the Year [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]] was chosen to officiate the match and was previously the head referee at [[MLS Cup 1997]].<ref name=\"SA\"/> At kickoff, set for 12:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]], the weather in Carson was sunny with a temperature of {{convert|71|F|C}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=December 10, 2016 |title=Will Toronto FC vs. Seattle Sounders be the coldest MLS Cup on record? |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/12/10/will-toronto-fc-vs-seattle-sounders-be-coldest-mls-cup-record |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Both teams fielded their regular lineups arranged in a 4\u20134\u20132 [[Formation (association football)|formation]].<ref name=\"Mercury-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |date=November 23, 2003 |title=After a baffling journey, Quakes at the doorstep |page=C1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes kicked off the match and made a series of attacks that won them a [[direct free kick|free kick]] outside of the penalty box. After a faked shot by [[Jeff Agoos]], Danish midfielder [[Ronnie Ekelund]] drove the ball past the defensive wall and scored the first goal of the final, tying the record for fastest MLS Cup goal.<ref name=\"Tribune-Thunder\">{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Jack |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Quakes steal Fire's thunder |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-11-24-0311240165-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Chicago had the majority of possession and chances in the first half, including two shots that were missed by striker [[Ante Razov]] and a poor touch by [[Damani Ralph]], but eventually conceded a second goal to San Jose.<ref name=\"Post\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Donovan Fills Up San Jose's Cup |page=D4 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A8624-2003Nov23.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Summary\">{{cite news |date=November 23, 2003 |title=San Jose Earns MLS Cup 2003 Title |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=recap&lang= |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031208163435/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/03/tracker.php?gamename=11232003_SJCHI&version=recap&lang= |archivedate=December 8, 2003 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> An Earthquakes counter-attack in the 38th minute sprung [[Jamil Walker]], who sent a through-pass to [[Landon Donovan]], who sprinted pass several defenders and shot the ball past goalkeeper [[Zach Thornton]].<ref name=\"SunTimes\">{{cite news |last=Padilla |first=Doug |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Leaky Fire falls in MLS Cup |work=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref>\n\nThe second half opened with a sequence of three goals by both teams within five minutes, beginning with a short pass by [[Andy Williams (Jamaican footballer)|Andy Williams]] to [[DaMarcus Beasley]] that was shot into the near side of the goal, cutting San Jose's lead to 2\u20131.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Earthquakes Win MLS Cup |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/24/sports/sp-mls24 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Shortly after kickoff, a long overhead pass by [[Brian Mullan]] found Earthquakes midfielder [[Richard Mulrooney]], who scored and restored the Earthquakes' two-goal lead.<ref name=\"SF-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=November 24, 2003 |title=MLS Cup: Earthquakes rumble; Donovan, Onstad secure S.J.'s 2nd title |page=C1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/MLS-CUP-Earthquakes-rumble-Donovan-Onstad-2548067.php |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The Fire continued to press for a second goal and earned a throw-in near San Jose's goal that led to a cross into the box by [[Evan Whitfield]]. The cross was deflected into the goal by Earthquakes defender [[Chris Roner]], who had been substituted three minutes earlier, narrowing the team's lead to 3\u20132 in the 54th minute.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> Roner then conceded a [[penalty kick]] to the Earthquakes two minutes later after a tackle from behind on Damani Ralph in the penalty area.<ref name=\"Post\"/> Ante Razov took the penalty kick, the first in MLS Cup history,<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> but it was saved by goalkeeper Pat Onstad with a dive to his right side to catch the ball.<ref name=\"SF-Summary\"/>\n\nRazov attempted to score an equalizing goal in the 58th minute, taking a shot in front of Onstad that grazed the corner of the net. San Jose forward Jamil Walker suffered an injury and was replaced in the 60th minute by [[Dwayne DeRosario]], who sized on a mis-cleared ball from Chicago ten minutes later and sent a cross into the box that was finished by Landon Donovan, giving the Earthquakes a 4\u20132 lead in the 71st minute.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> With the goal, Donovan became the first player to score two goals in an MLS Cup.<ref name=\"SF-Summary\"/> A chance for Chicago to reduce San Jose's lead came from a cross by Ralph in the 82nd minute that rolled across the six-yard box, but the tap-in for Razov was missed and the ball continued out of bounds.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> Ralph also had a chance to score a consolation goal in the third minute of [[stoppage time]], a cross by [[Nate Jaqua]] that he headed wide in front of the goal.<ref name=\"Post\"/> Despite having fewer shots and corner kicks, the San Jose Earthquakes won the match 4\u20132 and earned their second championship in three years.<ref name=\"Post\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n|date=November 23, 2003\n|time=12:30 [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|team1=[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|score=2\u20134\n|report=https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2003\n|team2=[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|goals1=\n*[[DaMarcus Beasley|Beasley]] {{goal|49}}\n*[[Chris Roner|Roner]] {{goal|54|o.g.}}\n|goals2=\n*[[Ronnie Ekelund|Ekelund]] {{goal|5}}\n*[[Landon Donovan|Donovan]] {{goal|38||71}}\n*[[Richard Mulrooney|Mulrooney]] {{goal|50}}\n|stadium=[[Home Depot Center]]\n|location=[[Carson, California]]\n|attendance=27,000\n|referee=[[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''CHICAGO FIRE:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Zach Thornton]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Evan Whitfield]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jim Curtin]] || || {{suboff|81}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Carlos Bocanegra]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Orlando Perez]] || || {{suboff|45}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Andy Williams (Jamaican footballer)|Andy Williams]] || || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jesse Marsch]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Armas]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[DaMarcus Beasley]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Damani Ralph]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ante Razov]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Curtis Spiteri]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[C. J. Brown]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kelly Gray]] || || {{subon|45}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Logan Pause]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Justin Mapp]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|CRC}} [[Jonathan Bola\u00f1os]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ryan Futagaki]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Nate Jaqua]] || || {{subon|81}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|BOT}} [[Dipsy Selolwane]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Dave Sarachan]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''SAN JOSE EARTHQUAKES:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Pat Onstad]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Craig Waibel]] || {{yel|15}} || {{suboff|51}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Troy Dayak]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Robinson (soccer)|Eddie Robinson]] || {{yel|54}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''9'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Mullan]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richard Mulrooney]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Ronnie Ekelund]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Manny Lagos]] || || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Landon Donovan]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jamil Walker]] || || {{suboff|60}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jon Conway]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''30'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Josh Saunders]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ramiro Corrales]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Todd Dunivant]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Roner]] || || {{subon|51}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]] || || {{subon|60}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Roger Levesque]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Rodrigo Faria]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Frank Yallop]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Landon Donovan]] (San Jose Earthquakes)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Craig Lowry\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Darren Engers\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Noel Kenny]]\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still tied.\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+Statistics<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px;\"|\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px;\"| {{nowrap|Chicago Fire}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px;\"| {{nowrap|San Jose}}<br />Earthquakes\n|-\n|scope=row|Goals scored\n| 2\n| 4\n|-\n|scope=row|Total shots\n| 22\n| 11\n|-\n|scope=row|Shots on target\n| 10\n| 7\n|-\n|scope=row|Saves\n| 4\n| 8\n|-\n|scope=row|Corner kicks\n| 13\n| 3\n|-\n|scope=row|Fouls committed\n| 17\n| 14\n|-\n|scope=row|Offsides\n| 4\n| 3\n|-\n|scope=row|Yellow cards\n| 0\n| 2\n|-\n|scope=row|Red cards\n| 0\n| 0\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe San Jose Earthquakes became the second team in league history to win multiple MLS Cups, following [[D.C. United]]'s three titles in the 1990s.<ref name=\"NYT\"/> The six-goal 2003 final was the highest-scoring in MLS Cup history, beating the five-goal [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural edition]], and featured its earliest goal, its first [[own goal]], and its first awarded [[penalty kick]].<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Summary\"/> The own goal and penalty kick were both caused by Earthquakes defender [[Chris Roner]], who would undergo ankle surgery at the end of the season that ultimately led to the end of his playing career.<ref>{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=February 13, 2012 |title=What Ever Happened To ... Chris Roner |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2012/02/13/what-ever-happened-chris-roner |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref> [[Landon Donovan]] became the first player to score multiple goals in an MLS Cup final and was named the match's [[most valuable player]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Peters |first=Ken |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Earthquakes win MLS Cup |page=D6 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/540034901/Earthquakes-win-MLS-Cup.html |work=[[Deseret News]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> San Jose captain Jeff Agoos won his fifth MLS Cup, having played in six previous finals for the Earthquakes and D.C. United.<ref name=\"LAT-Summary\"/>\n\nSan Jose qualified for the [[2004 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] as MLS Cup champions, while Chicago also qualified as Supporters' Shield champion.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 30, 2003 |title=Champions Cup |page=D8 |work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The Earthquakes were eliminated in the quarterfinals by eventual champions [[Liga Deportiva Alajuelense|Alajuelense]], while the Fire were defeated by [[Deportivo Saprissa]] in the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 19, 2004 |title=Costa Rica impone su ley en la Concacaf |language=Spanish |trans-title=Costa Rica imposes its law in CONCACAF |url=https://es.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2004/m=4/news=costa-rica-impone-ley-concacaf-91312.html |publisher=[[FIFA.com]] |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> Both teams have yet to make an appearance at the MLS Cup final since 2003;<ref>{{cite news |last=Reineking |first=Jim |date=December 7, 2017 |title=MLS Cup: Ranking every championship game |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2017/12/06/mls-cup-ranking-every-game/926051001/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> two years after the cup, the Earthquakes were placed on hiatus and replaced by the [[Houston Dynamo]], who would win back-to-back MLS Cups in their first two seasons before San Jose was reinstated in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 17, 2007 |title=Garber paints a bright picture |page=E7 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25463830/garber_paints_a_bright_picture/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 16, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=November 19, 2007 |title=Houston parties after second MLS title |page=B1 |work=[[Santa Maria Times]]}}</ref> The first domestic treble in MLS history was ultimately won in [[2017 Major League Soccer season|2017]] by [[Toronto FC]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Boisvert |first=Nick |date=February 16, 2018 |title=After a record-setting season, TFC sets its sights on a Champions League title |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tfc-champions-league-1.4539194 |work=CBC News |accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{San Jose Earthquakes matches}}\n{{Chicago Fire FC matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2003 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:2003 Major League Soccer season|*MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes matches|MLS Cup 2003]]\n[[Category:Chicago Fire FC matches|MLS Cup 2003]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Carson, California]]\n[[Category:November 2003 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2003 in sports in California]]\n[[Category:21st century in Carson, California]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary of results:adding source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Cup_2003"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Bowles", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian football player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Daniel Bowles\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Bowles speaking about Club Captain [[Matt McKay|McKay]]\n| fullname = Daniel James Bowles\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|10|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toowoomba]], Australia<ref>[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/adelaideunited/news-display/Excited-Bowles-one-to-watch/48128 'Excited' Bowles one to watch]. ''footballaustralia.com.au''. 13 July 2012. Retrieved 13 July 2012.</ref>\n| height = {{height|m=1.89}}\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Centre-back]] / [[Defender (football)|Right-back]]\n| currentclub = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[St Albans]]\n| youthyears2 = 2007\u20132008\n| youthclubs2 = [[Queensland Academy of Sport|QAS]]\n| youthyears3 = 2008\u20132009\n| youthclubs3 = [[Australian Institute of Sport|AIS]]\n| youthyears4 = 2008\u20132011\n| youthclubs4 = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| youthyears5 = 2011\u20132012\n| youthclubs5 = [[Gold Coast United FC|Gold Coast United]]\n| years1 = 2007\n| clubs1 = [[Toowoomba Raiders]]\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = 2008\n| clubs2 = [[Australian Institute of Sport Football Program|AIS]]\n| caps2 = 8\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2011\n| clubs3 = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| caps3 = 0\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs4 = [[Gold Coast United FC|Gold Coast United]]\n| caps4 = 12\n| goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2012\u20132014\n| clubs5 = [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]]\n| caps5 = 21\n| goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2014\u2013\n| clubs6 = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| caps6 = 70\n| goals6 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132009\n| nationalteam1 = [[Australia national under-17 football team|Australia U-17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 0\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2009\u20132011\n| nationalteam2 = [[Australia national under-20 football team|Australia U-20]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 14\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| pcupdate = 8 March 2019\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Bowles''' (born 19 October 1991) is an Australian [[association football|football (soccer)]] player who currently plays for [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nBowles played all of his junior football in [[Toowoomba]], initially with St Albans Football Club followed by the South Toowoomba Hawks and made his senior debut at 15 with the [[Toowoomba Raiders]] who play in the [[Brisbane Premier League]] (BPL).\n\n===Brisbane Roar===\nIn 2008, Daniel Bowles signed with [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]], participating in the club's inaugural [[A-League National Youth League|National Youth League]] season, where the Roar would finish third, just missing out on a spot in the final. The following season, Bowles would feature heavily, being a sturdy defender in what was a dismal season for the team. On 7 February 2011, Bowles was called up to the senior team following the departure of former player of the season, [[Luke DeVere]]. He signed a one-year contract that took him through to the end of that season.<ref>[http://www.brisbaneroar.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=38749 Brisbane \u2013 Daniel Bowles profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219190242/http://www.brisbaneroar.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=38749 |date=19 February 2011 }}. ''brisbaneroar.com.au''. Retrieved March 2011.</ref>\n\n===Gold Coast United===\nIn 9 September's edition of the ''[[The Courier-Mail|Courier Mail]]'', it was reported that Bowles would trial at [[right back]] for [[Gold Coast United]] in a pre-season match later in the month.\n\nOn 16 December 2011 he made his debut for [[A-League]] club [[Gold Coast United]].<ref>[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/aleague/matchcentre/Adelaide-United-FC-v-Gold-Coast-United-FC-Hyundai-A-League/2139 Match report- Adelaide United \u2013 Gold Coast United]. ''footballaustralia.com.au''. Retrieved 16 December 2011.</ref> On 9 March 2012 Bowles scored his first senior career goal against Newcastle Jets.\n\n===Adelaide United===\nOn 22 March 2012 it was announced Bowles had signed a two-year undisclosed contract with [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]] in the [[A-League]].<ref>[http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/news/1098541/Gold-Coast-loses-another-young-star Gold Coast United loses another young star]. ''theworldgame.sbs.com.au''. Retrieved 22 March 2012.</ref> On 2 May 2014, it was announced that Bowles, as well as colleague [[Jake Barker-Daish]] were released from the club.<ref>[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/adelaideunited/news-display/Adelaide-United-confirms-departures-of-BarkerDaish-and-Bowles/90262 Adelaide United confirms departures of Barker-Daish and Bowles]. ''footballaustralia.com.au''. Retrieved 2 May 2014.</ref>\n\n===Return to Brisbane Roar===\nOn 8 July 2014, 3.5 months after being released by Adelaide United, Bowles signed with Brisbane Roar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brisbaneroar.com.au/article/young-and-bowles-return-to-queensland/g6d08v6xjcnv1k4f57xwnkt7n|title=Young and Bowles return to Queensland|date=8 July 2014|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]}}</ref> Bowles made his debut for the Roar in the 4\u20130 plundering of the [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]] at [[Hunter Stadium]]. Bowles was awarded his first red card of the season in the Roar's 3\u20132 away win against [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]]. He received the red card after holding back defender [[Nigel Boogaard]], who was later found out to be offside, and Adelaide were apportioned a penalty. Despite this, Bowles featured in the Round 25 Team of the Week. He featured in three of the Roar's ACL fixtures, being part of the defensive team that kept a clean sheet against [[Beijing Guoan F.C.|Beijing Guoan]].\n\nBowles obtained a serious knee injury in January 2017, ruling him out for the remainder of the season. He returned to play the beginning of the next season.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.is/20130410013746/http://m.footballaustralia.com.au/clubplayers-profile/Daniel-Bowles/4905/6 Adelaide United profile]\n\n{{Brisbane Roar FC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowles, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Roar FC players]]\n[[Category:Gold Coast United FC players]]\n[[Category:Adelaide United FC players]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Australian Institute of Sport soccer players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian football player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Daniel Bowles\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Bowles speaking about Club Captain [[Matt McKay|McKay]]\n| fullname = Daniel James Bowles\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|10|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Toowoomba]], Australia<ref>[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/adelaideunited/news-display/Excited-Bowles-one-to-watch/48128 'Excited' Bowles one to watch]. ''footballaustralia.com.au''. 13 July 2012. Retrieved 13 July 2012.</ref>\n| height = {{height|m=1.89}}\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Centre-back]] / [[Defender (football)|Right-back]]\n| currentclub = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[St Albans]]\n| youthyears2 = 2007\u20132008\n| youthclubs2 = [[Queensland Academy of Sport|QAS]]\n| youthyears3 = 2008\u20132009\n| youthclubs3 = [[Australian Institute of Sport|AIS]]\n| youthyears4 = 2008\u20132011\n| youthclubs4 = [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]]\n| youthyears5 = 2011\u20132012\n| youthclubs5 = [[Gold Coast United FC|Gold Coast United]]\n