''] at the World Spider Catalog\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2150494}}\n\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1927]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Sumatra]]\n\n\n{{salticidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stagetillus_elegans"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 2002", "text_new": "{{short description|2002 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|title = MLS Cup 2002\n|year  = [[MLS Cup]]\n|image = [[File:MLS Cup 2002 logo.gif]]\n|team1 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|team1score = 1\n|team2 = [[New England Revolution]]\n|team2score = 0\n|details = After [[golden goal]] [[Overtime (Association football)|extra time]]\n|date = October 20, 2002\n|stadium = [[Gillette Stadium]]\n|city = [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], US \n|man_of_the_match1a = [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]]<br />(Los Angeles Galaxy) \n|weather = Sunny, {{convert|56|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n|attendance = 61,316 \n|referee = [[Kevin Terry]]\n|previous = [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]]\n|next = [[MLS Cup 2003|2003]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2002''' was the seventh edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on October 20, 2002. It was hosted at [[Gillette Stadium]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], and contested by the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] to decide the champion of the [[2002 Major League Soccer season|2002 season]]. The Revolution, who were named hosts before the season, were playing in their first MLS Cup; Los Angeles had lost in all three of their previous cup appearances.\n\nLos Angeles won their first championship 1\u20130 in the second overtime on a [[golden goal|sudden-death goal]] scored by [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]]. The match was attended by 61,316 spectators, the largest figure for any MLS Cup until [[MLS Cup 2018|2018]]. It was also the last MLS final to end with a [[golden goal]].\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Gillette Stadium (Top View).jpg|thumb|left|[[Gillette Stadium]], host of MLS Cup 2002]]\n\n[[Gillette Stadium|CMGI Field]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], home of the New England Revolution and the [[New England Patriots]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL), was announced as the [[Home advantage#Neutral venues|neutral-site venue]] of the MLS Cup on February 13, 2002.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 13, 2002 |title=A nice Brazilian blend |page=C14 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref><ref name=\"CMGI\">{{cite press release |date=February 13, 2002 |title=CMGI Field to Host MLS Cup 2002 |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0212cup02.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020601192802/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0212cup02.html |archivedate=June 1, 2002 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The new stadium was built to replace the former [[Foxboro Stadium]], which had hosted the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural MLS Cup in 1996]] and the [[MLS Cup 1999|1999 edition]].<ref>{{cite news |date=February 11, 2002 |title=Mass. Stadium Tapped for MLS Cup |url=https://www.michigansthumb.com/news/article/Mass-Stadium-Tapped-for-MLS-Cup-7335328.php |work=[[Huron Daily Tribune]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Golen |first=Jimmy |date=October 22, 2002 |title=Galaxy title took seven years |page=C4 |work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379855/galaxy_title_took_seven_years_ap/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> CMGI Field was later renamed Gillette Stadium in August after the [[naming rights]] were sold to [[Gillette]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=May 10, 2002 |title=New facility has a multipurpose |page=E8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25152745/new_facility_has_a_multipurpose/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reidy |first1=Chris |last2=Cafardo |first2=Nick|authorlink2=Nick Cafardo |date=August 6, 2002 |title=Gillette scores at Patriots' field; CMGI heads to sidelines |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25152732/gillette_scores_at_patriots_field/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> Approximately 20,000 tickets were sold by October 10, but sales reached 55,000 after the Revolution advanced from the Conference Finals, and were on pace to match or surpass the MLS Cup attendance record of 57,431 set in [[MLS Cup '97|1997]].<ref name=\"LAT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Dillman |first=Lisa |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Another Shot for Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/20/sports/sp-galaxy20 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=October 21, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #30 Occupy Gillette |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/21/top-50-mls-cup-moments-30-occupy-gillette |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref> The stadium's capacity was restricted to 60,000 seats, excluding the [[luxury box|box]] and club seats, and the field itself measured {{convert|75 x 106|yd|m}}, wider than the configuration used in 1999 at Foxboro Stadium.<ref name=\"Globe-Tickets\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 19, 2002 |title=Demand for tickets exceeding officials' expectations |page=E8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349774/demand_for_tickets_exceeding_officials/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{main|2002 Major League Soccer season}}\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2002 Major League Soccer season|2002 season]] was the seventh in the league's history and was contested by ten teams in two conferences following the folding of two teams in [[Florida]] and the reorganization of the [[Central Division (MLS)|Central Division]].<ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=March 24, 2002 |title=Two teams lighter, MLS starts 7th season |page=D6 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349735/two_teams_lighter_mls_starts_7th_season/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Foltman |first=Bob |date=January 9, 2002 |title=MLS drops 2 Florida teams |page=2 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2002-01-09-0201090224-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> Each team played a total of 28 matches in the regular season, which ran from March to September, facing teams within their conference four times and outside of their conference two times.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021003220954/http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |archivedate=October 3, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The playoffs ran from late September to October and was contested by the top eight teams overall, with the top two teams in each conference given a higher seed regardless of overall standing.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The playoffs were organized into three rounds, the first two being a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with the first team to earn five points advancing, and the single-match MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 2002 |title=2002 MLS Cup Playoffs Media Guide |url=http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002pog_pub.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030714174425/http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002pog_pub.pdf |archivedate=July 14, 2003 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 2002 was contested by the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], who also won the regular season's [[Supporters' Shield]], and the [[New England Revolution]], the highest-ranked team from the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]].<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\">{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 18, 2002 |title=A Beaten Path? |page=D15 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/18/sports/sp-revolution18 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT-No1\">{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=September 22, 2002 |title=Galaxy Clinches No. 1 Playoff Seed |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/22/sports/sp-galaxy22 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy and Revolution played each other twice in the regular season: a 3\u20132 victory for New England on May 25 and a 2\u20131 win for Los Angeles on August 10.<ref name=\"AP-Galaxy\">{{cite news |last=Ulman |first=Howard |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Ageless Jones leads Galaxy to final |page=C11 |work=[[The Burlington Free Press]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177027/ageless_jones_leads_galaxy_to_final_ap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The two teams also played each other in the [[2001 U.S. Open Cup Final]], where Los Angeles won 2\u20131 in overtime.<ref name=\"Globe-Buildup\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 14, 2002 |title=Speedy path to success |page=C2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349398/speedy_path_to_success/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Galaxy===\n\nThe Los Angeles Galaxy had qualified for the playoffs in each of the league's previous six seasons and were runners-up at the MLS Cup on three previous occasions: losing to [[D.C. United]] in [[MLS Cup '96|1996]] and [[MLS Cup '99|1999]], and to in-state rivals [[San Jose Earthquakes]] in [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]].<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/> While they had won other competitions, including the [[U.S. Open Cup]] and the [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], the team were compared to the NFL's [[Buffalo Bills]], who were runners-up at the [[Super Bowl]] several times in the 1990s.<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Casey |first=Tim |date=October 21, 2002 |title=After three failures, Galaxy finally vindicated |page=D10 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379873/after_three_failures_galaxy_finally/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> Guatemalan forward [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]], who was acquired in the offseason, scored 24 goals in his first season with the Galaxy and was named the league's [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|most valuable player]] (MVP).<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 19, 2002 |title=Fitting the Bill |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/19/sports/sp-galaxy19 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy finished as Supporters' Shield champions with 51 points, while the remaining Western Conference teams all qualified for the playoffs.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\"/><ref name=\"LAT-No1\"/> Veteran forward [[Cobi Jones]] ranked second in goals scored for the Galaxy, behind Ruiz, and enjoyed a comeback season alongside defender and U.S. compatriot [[Alexi Lalas]].<ref name=\"AP-Galaxy\"/>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Los Angeles faced the bottom-seeded [[Kansas City Wizards]] in a first-to-five point series. The first leg at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California]], was won by the Galaxy 3\u20132 after a golden goal was scored by Ruiz in the 99th minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=September 26, 2002 |title=For Ruiz, Overtime Is His Prime Time |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/26/sports/sp-galaxy26 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The Wizards won 4\u20131 in the second leg at [[Arrowhead Stadium]], setting up a series-deciding third match at the Rose Bowl.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=September 29, 2002 |title=Galaxy Can't Close It Out |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/29/sports/sp-galaxy29 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> Los Angeles won the third leg 5\u20132, with two goals each for Jones and Ruiz, and advanced to the Conference Finals with six points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 3, 2002 |title=Galaxy Kicks It Up a Notch |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/03/sports/sp-galaxy3 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy played against the [[Colorado Rapids]] in the Western Conference Finals, held over the following week under the same format as the Semifinals. The team won 4\u20130 at the Rose Bowl and 1\u20130 at [[INVESCO Field]] in [[Denver]], bringing the Galaxy to their fourth MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 6, 2002 |title=Galaxy Makes Rapid Advance |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/06/sports/sp-galaxy6 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 10, 2002 |title=Ruiz Heads Galaxy Attack |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/10/sports/sp-galaxy10 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===New England Revolution===\n[[File:TaylorTwellman 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|right|x260px|New England Revolution forward [[Taylor Twellman]], who led the team in scoring]]\n\nThe Revolution failed to qualify for the playoffs in 2001,<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 2, 2001 |title=As in history, Revolution suppressed |page=C4 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349136/as_in_history_revolution_suppressed/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> following several years of poor on-field performances that resulted in the worst winning record of the league's ten teams.<ref>{{cite press release |date=January 24, 2002 |title=MLS Announces 2002 Regular Season Schedule |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0124schedule.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020127141936/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0124schedule.html |archivedate=January 27, 2002 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lemieux |first=Jeff |date=October 18, 2016 |title=History Lesson: Recapping every team MVP through the Revs' first 20 seasons |url=https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/post/2016/10/18/history-lesson-recapping-every-team-mvp-through-revs-first-20-seasons |publisher=New England Revolution |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> Despite their league performance, New England finished as runners-up to the Galaxy in the 2001 U.S. Open Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 28, 2001 |title=Revolution crumple in OT |page=C7 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349114/revolution_crumple_in_ot_open_cup/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> During the 2002 preseason, the club acquired several players from the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]] and [[Miami Fusion]] in trades and the [[2002 MLS Allocation Draft|Allocation Draft]] following the contraction of the two clubs, including league MVP [[Alex Pineda Chac\u00f3n]], forward [[Mamadou Diallo]], midfielder [[Steve Ralston]], and defender [[Carlos Llamosa]].<ref name=\"Globe-Clavijo\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=May 24, 2002 |title=Revolutionary change: Clavijo shown gate |page=E10 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25202818/revolutionary_change_clavijo_shown_gate/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 7, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> New England also drafted forward [[Taylor Twellman]] in the [[2002 MLS SuperDraft]] following a successful college career and a return from [[TSV 1860 Munich]].<ref>{{cite news |date=March 21, 2002 |title=New England Revolution: 2002 Outlook |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/s/2002/0319/1354391.html |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHead coach [[Fernando Clavijo]] was fired after the seventh match of the season, with the Revolution only winning two.<ref name=\"Globe-Clavijo\"/> Assistant coach [[Steve Nicol]] was promoted to interim head coach on May 23 and completed a turnaround from last to first in the Eastern Conference, leading the team into the playoffs and earning the [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|coach of the year]] award.<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/><ref name=\"NYT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Revolution and Galaxy Are Pursuing First Title |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/20/sports/soccer-revolution-and-galaxy-are-pursuing-first-title.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> New England finished the season with a six-match unbeaten streak and a total record of 12 wins, 14 losses, and two draws, scoring a league-high 49 goals.<ref name=\"NYT-Preview\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=MLS History: New England Revolution, 2002 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/club/newengland/2002 |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The team narrowly qualified for the playoffs on the final day of the season, with all three qualifiers from the Eastern Conference within one point of each other.<ref name=\"LAT-Preview\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/>\n\nNew England played the seventh-seeded [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] in the Conference Semifinals, winning the first leg 2\u20130 at Gillette Stadium on goals by Twellman and [[Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez (soccer)|Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 27, 2002 |title=Revolution on fire |page=E1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349083/revolution_on_fire/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Fire won the second leg 2\u20131, setting up a deciding match at Gillette Stadium on October 2.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 30, 2002 |title=Harris not discouraged by loss |page=D8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349101/harris_not_discouraged_by_loss/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution won 2\u20130 in the third match, clinching their first playoff series win and advancing to face the [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 3, 2002 |title=Extinguished |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349160/extinguished/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The first leg at Gillette Stadium was a scoreless tie and the Revolution won the second leg in Columbus 1\u20130 on an early goal scored by defender [[Jay Heaps]], who was later ejected for an altercation with [[Freddy Garc\u00eda (footballer)|Freddy Garc\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 7, 2002 |title=They'll proceed\u2014with cautions |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349521/theyll_proceedwith_cautions/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 10, 2002 |title=Revolution take command |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349525/revolution_take_command/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> After earning a 2\u20130 lead in the third leg, New England conceded two late goals to draw 2\u20132 and force overtime. Neither team could score the [[golden goal]] needed to clinch a series win outright, leaving the Revolution with 5\u20132 in points and qualifying them for the MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 13, 2002 |title=A final foothold |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177086/a_final_foothold/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution became the second team to play an MLS Cup final at their home stadium, following [[D.C. United]] in [[MLS Cup '97|1997]], which also held the attendance record.<ref name=\"AP-Galaxy\"/> Despite a sprain in his right knee after the last match of the Conference Final, Twellman recovered in time for the cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 18, 2002 |title=Sunday RSVP for MVP favorite |page=E6 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25380261/sunday_rsvp_for_mvp_favorite/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[New England Revolution]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[2002 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]'''||'''28'''||'''16'''||'''9'''||'''3'''||'''51'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]||28||14||11||3||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||28||12||9||7||'''43'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|4||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||28||13||11||4||'''43'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|5||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||28||9||10||9||'''36'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2002 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2002 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2002 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[New England Revolution]]'''||'''28'''||'''12'''||'''14'''||'''2'''||'''38'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]]||28||11||12||5||'''38'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]||28||11||13||4||'''37'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|MetroStars]]||28||11||15||2||35\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[D.C. United]]||28||9||14||5||32\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2002 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|[[2002 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]] (6\u20133)\n|3\u20132 {{aet}} (H)\n|1\u20134 (A)\n|5\u20132 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] (6\u20133)\n|2\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20132 (A)\n|2\u20130 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]] (6\u20130)\n|4\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20130 (A)\n|\u2014\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] (5\u20132)\n|0\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20130 (A)\n|2\u20132 (H)\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]]. English play-by-play commentary was provided by [[JP Dellacamera]] with color analysis by [[Ty Keough]] and pregame and halftime shows hosted by [[Terry Gannon]] and [[Eric Wynalda]], reprising their roles from ABC's coverage of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Griffith |first=Bill |date=October 19, 2002 |title=He'll have angles covered |page=E8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349656/hell_have_angles_covered/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 18, 2002 |title=Best bets |page=D2 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]}}</ref> The Spanish broadcast was handled by play-by-play commentator [[Ernesto Motta]] and color analyst Andres Rodriguez.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 16, 2002 |title=ABC Sports Presents MLS Cup 2002 |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/abc-sports-presents-mls-cup-2002/n-1976535 |publisher=Major League Soccer |via=Our Sports Central |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The ABC broadcast was watched by an estimated audience of 1.2 million views, the lowest for an MLS Cup at the time.<ref>{{cite news |author=Paulsen |date=November 24, 2010 |title=Record Low Rating For 2010 MLS Cup |url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2010/11/record-low-rating-for-2010-mls-cup/ |work=[[Sports Media Watch]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:CarlosRuiz.jpg|thumb|left|Forward [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]], whose [[golden goal]] won the MLS Cup for the Los Angeles Galaxy|x260px]]\n\nThe 2002 final was referred by [[Kevin Terry]], who previously officiated the [[MLS Cup 1998|1998 final]]. In the event of a draw after regulation time, the match would be decided by two 15-minute [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] periods with the [[golden goal]]s followed by a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] if necessary.<ref name=\"Globe-Tickets\"/><ref name=\"MediaGuide\">{{cite web |date=October 2002 |title=2002 MLS Cup Media Guide |page=9 |url=http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002cup_pub.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030714055453/http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002cup_pub.pdf |archivedate=July 14, 2003 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> At kickoff, set for 1:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastern Time, the weather in Foxborough was sunny with a temperature of {{convert|56|F|C}}.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\">{{cite news |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Galaxy Exorcises Their Demons |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/02/2002mlscup.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021031142336/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/02/2002mlscup.html |archivedate=October 31, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles kicked off the match and had most of the chances in the scoreless first half while preventing the Revolution from making a single shot on goal.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> The Galaxy had the game's first two shots, in the 12th and 17th minutes, but they failed to be shot on target by [[Tyrone Marshall]] and Carlos Ruiz. New England responded with a cross by [[Joe Franchino]] in the 26th minute for [[Taylor Twellman]] and [[Steve Ralston]], but neither could reach the ball in time.<ref name=\"AP-SI\">{{cite news |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Fourth time's the charm: Ruiz's golden goal beats Revs, gives L.A. first MLS title |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2002/mls_cup/news/2002/10/20/mlscup_gamer/ |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021106201215/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2002/mls_cup/news/2002/10/20/mlscup_gamer/ |archivedate=November 6, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> Franchino was shown a [[yellow card (sport)|yellow card]] in the 24th minute for a challenge on [[Cobi Jones]], one of several that the two captains traded.<ref name=\"USA-Dure\">{{cite news |last=Dure |first=Beau |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Golden goal rescues MLS Cup |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/columnist/dure/2002-10-20-dure_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021154231/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/columnist/dure/2002-10-20-dure_x.htm |archivedate=October 21, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe second half began with a series of hard challenges by players on both teams to win possession of the ball, which was sent down the flanks by the Galaxy's Cobi Jones and the Revolution's [[Leo Cullen (soccer)|Leo Cullen]]. Both wingers sent in crosses that were hit towards the goal and deflected away.<ref name=\"USA-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Gardiner |first=Andy |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Finally \u2014 Los Angeles claims MLS title |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2002-10-20-mls-cup_x.htm |work=USA Today |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021024222035/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2002-10-20-mls-cup_x.htm |archivedate=October 24, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Minute\">{{cite news |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Galaxy Take the Cup |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/ |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021022134939/http://www.mlsnet.com/ |archivedate=October 22, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> During the last ten minutes of regulation time, both teams produced several chances that were deflected away by defenders, with the Revolution relying on substitute [[Alex Pineda Chac\u00f3n]], who entered in the 75th minute.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/><ref name=\"USA-Summary\"/> Ruiz was given a clear shot on goal in the 80th minute, but the ball was deflected away by defender [[Daouda Kant\u00e9]] for a goal kick.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 3, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #48 Risky Business |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/03/top-50-mls-cup-moments-48-risky-business |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> A final shot by Chac\u00f3n in [[stoppage time]] was saved by Galaxy goalkeeper [[Kevin Hartman]], his first of the match, and the MLS Cup final was sent into overtime.<ref name=\"USA-Dure\"/>\n\nThe Galaxy took control of the match during overtime, with an early chance in the 93rd minute missed by Jones. A [[bicycle kick]] by Ruiz in the 102nd minute was saved by Revolution goalkeeper [[Adin Brown]], who followed minutes later with a second save on Ruiz at the beginning of the second overtime period.<ref name=\"USA-Summary\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Minute\"/> A wayward shot by New England substitute [[Winston Griffiths (soccer)|Winston Griffiths]] in the 111th minute was deflected and hit the crossbar, preventing the game-winning goal.<ref name=\"USA-Dure\"/> The Galaxy cleared the deflected ball and followed two minutes later with a diagonal cross by defender Tyrone Marshall that found Ruiz, who hit a left-footed that shot past Brown and went into the net.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 21, 2002 |title=Out of this world |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379759/out_of_this_world/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The MLS Cup final, the longest match in MLS Cup history, ended after 113 minutes with Ruiz's golden goal.<ref name=\"AP-SI\"/><ref name=\"USA-Summary\"/> Ruiz was named the MLS Cup [[most valuable player]] for his winning goal.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box \n|date = October 20, 2002\n|time = 13:30 [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|score = 1\u20130 ([[Overtime (sports)|2OT]]) \n|report = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/mls-cup-2002-los-angeles-galaxy-1-new-england-revolution-0 Report]\n|team2 = [[New England Revolution]] \n|goals1 = [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Ruiz]] {{golden goal|113}}\n|goals2 = \n|stadium = [[Gillette Stadium]]<br>[[Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n|attendance = 61,316\n|referee = [[Kevin Terry]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''LOS ANGELES GALAXY:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kevin Hartman]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Califf]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''30'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Alexi Lalas]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Tyrone Marshall]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|VIN}} [[Ezra Hendrickson]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Cobi Jones]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Simon Elliott]] || {{yel|95}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]] || || {{suboff|62}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sasha Victorine]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|GUA}} [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|VEN}} [[Alejandro Moreno]] || || {{suboff|67}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vagenas]] || || {{subon|62}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Albright]] || || {{subon|67}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sigi Schmid]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''NEW ENGLAND REVOLUTION:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Adin Brown]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jay Heaps]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Carlos Llamosa]] || {{yel|60}} || {{suboff|90+2}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|MLI}} [[Daouda Kant\u00e9]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Franchino]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|24}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Ralston]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Leo Cullen (soccer)|Leo Cullen]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez (soccer)|Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Kamler]] || || {{suboff|90}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Wolde Harris]] || || {{suboff|75}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Taylor Twellman]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Rusty Pierce]] || || {{subon|90+2}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|HON}} [[Alex Pineda Chac\u00f3n]] || || {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''25'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Winston Griffiths (soccer)|Winston Griffiths]] || || {{subon|90}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Steve Nicol]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|GUA}} [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]] (Los Angeles Galaxy)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''<ref name=\"MLS-Report\">{{cite web |title=MLS Cup 2002: Los Angeles Galaxy 1, New England Revolution 0 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/mls-cup-2002-los-angeles-galaxy-1-new-england-revolution-0 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Greg Barkey\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Richard Eddy\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Michael Kennedy (referee)|Michael Kennedy]]\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''<ref name=\"MediaGuide\"/>\n*90 minutes of regulation time\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still tied.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe match was the first in MLS Cup history to have a scoreless half and remain scoreless at the end of regulation time.<ref name=\"AP-SI\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Report\"/> It was also the third and final MLS Cup to be decided by a [[golden goal]] in overtime,<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> a short-lived rule that would be replaced with a conventional [[extra time (association football)|extra time]] period in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reineking |first=Jim |date=December 7, 2017 |title=MLS Cup: Ranking every championship game |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2017/12/06/mls-cup-ranking-every-game/926051001/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Turner |first=Elliott |date=November 29, 2013 |title=The final letdown: five US soccer showpieces that failed to achieve lift-off |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/nov/29/mls-cup-sporting-kc-real-salt-lake |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The match was attended by 61,316 spectators,  a figure that remains among the highest in MLS playoff history and set a record for an MLS Cup final that was later surpassed in [[MLS Cup 2018|2018]] by [[Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Roberson |first=Doug |date=December 8, 2018 |title=Atlanta United sets MLS Cup attendance record |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-sets-mls-cup-attendance-record/lJVEXg0pSHjtlNJ7TM06hK/ |work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN-2014\">{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=December 3, 2014 |title=The Galaxy and Revolution set to pen another chapter in MLS history |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/blog/name/93/post/2177571/headline |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 26, 2017 |title=Steffen leads Crew past Atlanta United on penalties |url=http://www.latimes.com/ct-hoy-steffen-leads-crew-past-atlanta-united-on-penalties-20171026-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy finished their 2002 season with a loss to the Columbus Crew in the [[2002 U.S. Open Cup]] four days later in [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dillman |first=Lisa |date=October 25, 2002 |title=Galaxy Is Cut Down by Crew |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/25/sports/sp-galaxy25 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> Both teams qualified for the [[2003 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], where the Revolution would be eliminated in the first round and the Galaxy would lose in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=March 21, 2003 |title=Revolution's road trip not environmentally friendly\n|page=E5 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177320/revolutions_road_trip_concacaf/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gutierrez |first1=Paul |last2=Jones |first2=Grahame L. |date=April 17, 2003 |title=Galaxy Eliminated in Champions Cup |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/apr/17/sports/sp-soccer17 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy and Revolution met again in the [[MLS Cup 2005|2005 final]], where Los Angeles repeated their championship with a 1\u20130 win after [[Overtime (Association football)|extra time]].<ref name=\"ESPN-2014\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 14, 2005 |title=A case of deja blue |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177239/a_case_of_deja_blue/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution would go on to lose the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2006|2006]] and [[MLS Cup 2007|2007]] to the [[Houston Dynamo]] and in [[MLS Cup 2014|2014]] to the Galaxy, who would claim their fifth title.<ref>{{cite news |last=Powers |first=John |date=December 8, 2014 |title=Galaxy defeat Revolution for record fifth MLS title |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Due to their finishes as MLS Cup runners-up, the Revolution are known as the \"[[Buffalo Bills]] of MLS\", mirroring the football team's second-place finishes at the [[Super Bowl]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Felt |first=Hunter |date=December 9, 2014 |title=Can the Revolution ever thrive in the Boston sports market? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/dec/09/can-the-revolution-ever-thrive-in-the-boston-sports-market |work=The Guardian |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLS Cup}}\n{{Los Angeles Galaxy matches}}\n{{New England Revolution matches}}\n\n[[Category:MLS Cup|2002]]\n[[Category:2002 Major League Soccer season|*]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy matches]]\n[[Category:New England Revolution matches]]\n[[Category:October 2002 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2002 in sports in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:21st century in Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2002 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|title = MLS Cup 2002\n|year  = [[MLS Cup]]\n|image = [[File:MLS Cup 2002 logo.gif]]\n|team1 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|team1score = 1\n|team2 = [[New England Revolution]]\n|team2score = 0\n|details = After [[golden goal]] [[Overtime (Association football)|extra time]]\n|date = October 20, 2002\n|stadium = [[Gillette Stadium]]\n|city = [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], US \n|man_of_the_match1a = [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]]<br />(Los Angeles Galaxy) \n|weather = Sunny, {{convert|56|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n|attendance = 61,316 \n|referee = [[Kevin Terry]]\n|previous = [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]]\n|next = [[MLS Cup 2003|2003]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2002''' was the seventh edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on October 20, 2002. It was hosted at [[Gillette Stadium]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], and contested by the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] to decide the champion of the [[2002 Major League Soccer season|2002 season]]. The Revolution, who were named hosts before the season, were playing in their first MLS Cup; Los Angeles had lost in all three of their previous cup appearances.\n\nLos Angeles won their first championship 1\u20130 in the second overtime on a [[golden goal|sudden-death goal]] scored by [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]]. The match was attended by 61,316 spectators, the largest figure for any MLS Cup until [[MLS Cup 2018|2018]]. It was also the last MLS final to end with a [[golden goal]].\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Gillette Stadium (Top View).jpg|thumb|left|[[Gillette Stadium]], host of MLS Cup 2002]]\n\n[[Gillette Stadium|CMGI Field]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]], home of the New England Revolution and the [[New England Patriots]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL), was announced as the [[Home advantage#Neutral venues|neutral-site venue]] of the MLS Cup on February 13, 2002.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 13, 2002 |title=A nice Brazilian blend |page=C14 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref><ref name=\"CMGI\">{{cite press release |date=February 13, 2002 |title=CMGI Field to Host MLS Cup 2002 |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0212cup02.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020601192802/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0212cup02.html |archivedate=June 1, 2002 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The new stadium was built to replace the former [[Foxboro Stadium]], which had hosted the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural MLS Cup in 1996]] and the [[MLS Cup 1999|1999 edition]].<ref>{{cite news |date=February 11, 2002 |title=Mass. Stadium Tapped for MLS Cup |url=https://www.michigansthumb.com/news/article/Mass-Stadium-Tapped-for-MLS-Cup-7335328.php |work=[[Huron Daily Tribune]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Golen |first=Jimmy |date=October 22, 2002 |title=Galaxy title took seven years |page=C4 |work=[[Asheville Citizen-Times]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379855/galaxy_title_took_seven_years_ap/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> CMGI Field was later renamed Gillette Stadium in August after the [[naming rights]] were sold to [[Gillette]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=May 10, 2002 |title=New facility has a multipurpose |page=E8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25152745/new_facility_has_a_multipurpose/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reidy |first1=Chris |last2=Cafardo |first2=Nick|authorlink2=Nick Cafardo |date=August 6, 2002 |title=Gillette scores at Patriots' field; CMGI heads to sidelines |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25152732/gillette_scores_at_patriots_field/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> Approximately 20,000 tickets were sold by October 10, but sales reached 55,000 after the Revolution advanced from the Conference Finals, and were on pace to match or surpass the MLS Cup attendance record of 57,431 set in [[MLS Cup '97|1997]].<ref name=\"LAT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Dillman |first=Lisa |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Another Shot for Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/20/sports/sp-galaxy20 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=October 21, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #30 Occupy Gillette |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/21/top-50-mls-cup-moments-30-occupy-gillette |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref> The stadium's capacity was restricted to 60,000 seats, excluding the [[luxury box|box]] and club seats, and the field itself measured {{convert|75 x 106|yd|m}}, wider than the configuration used in 1999 at Foxboro Stadium.<ref name=\"Globe-Tickets\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 19, 2002 |title=Demand for tickets exceeding officials' expectations |page=E8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349774/demand_for_tickets_exceeding_officials/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{main|2002 Major League Soccer season}}\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2002 Major League Soccer season|2002 season]] was the seventh in the league's history and was contested by ten teams in two conferences following the folding of two teams in [[Florida]] and the reorganization of the [[Central Division (MLS)|Central Division]].<ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=March 24, 2002 |title=Two teams lighter, MLS starts 7th season |page=D6 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349735/two_teams_lighter_mls_starts_7th_season/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Foltman |first=Bob |date=January 9, 2002 |title=MLS drops 2 Florida teams |page=2 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2002-01-09-0201090224-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> Each team played a total of 28 matches in the regular season, which ran from March to September, facing teams within their conference four times and outside of their conference two times.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021003220954/http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |archivedate=October 3, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The playoffs ran from late September to October and was contested by the top eight teams overall, with the top two teams in each conference given a higher seed regardless of overall standing.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The playoffs were organized into three rounds, the first two being a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with the first team to earn five points advancing, and the single-match MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 2002 |title=2002 MLS Cup Playoffs Media Guide |url=http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002pog_pub.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030714174425/http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002pog_pub.pdf |archivedate=July 14, 2003 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 2002 was contested by the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], who also won the regular season's [[Supporters' Shield]], and the [[New England Revolution]], the highest-ranked team from the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]].<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\">{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 18, 2002 |title=A Beaten Path? |page=D15 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/18/sports/sp-revolution18 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT-No1\">{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=September 22, 2002 |title=Galaxy Clinches No. 1 Playoff Seed |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/22/sports/sp-galaxy22 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy and Revolution played each other twice in the regular season: a 3\u20132 victory for New England on May 25 and a 2\u20131 win for Los Angeles on August 10.<ref name=\"AP-Galaxy\">{{cite news |last=Ulman |first=Howard |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Ageless Jones leads Galaxy to final |page=C11 |work=[[The Burlington Free Press]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177027/ageless_jones_leads_galaxy_to_final_ap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The two teams also played each other in the [[2001 U.S. Open Cup Final]], where Los Angeles won 2\u20131 in overtime.<ref name=\"Globe-Buildup\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 14, 2002 |title=Speedy path to success |page=C2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349398/speedy_path_to_success/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Galaxy===\n\nThe Los Angeles Galaxy had qualified for the playoffs in each of the league's previous six seasons and were runners-up at the MLS Cup on three previous occasions: losing to [[D.C. United]] in [[MLS Cup '96|1996]] and [[MLS Cup '99|1999]], and to in-state rivals [[San Jose Earthquakes]] in [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]].<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/> While they had won other competitions, including the [[U.S. Open Cup]] and the [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], the team were compared to the NFL's [[Buffalo Bills]], who were runners-up at the [[Super Bowl]] several times in the 1990s.<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Casey |first=Tim |date=October 21, 2002 |title=After three failures, Galaxy finally vindicated |page=D10 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379873/after_three_failures_galaxy_finally/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> Guatemalan forward [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]], who was acquired in the offseason, scored 24 goals in his first season with the Galaxy and was named the league's [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|most valuable player]] (MVP).<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 19, 2002 |title=Fitting the Bill |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/19/sports/sp-galaxy19 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy finished as Supporters' Shield champions with 51 points, while the remaining Western Conference teams all qualified for the playoffs.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\"/><ref name=\"LAT-No1\"/> Veteran forward [[Cobi Jones]] ranked second in goals scored for the Galaxy, behind Ruiz, and enjoyed a comeback season alongside defender and U.S. compatriot [[Alexi Lalas]].<ref name=\"AP-Galaxy\"/>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Los Angeles faced the bottom-seeded [[Kansas City Wizards]] in a first-to-five point series. The first leg at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California]], was won by the Galaxy 3\u20132 after a golden goal was scored by Ruiz in the 99th minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=September 26, 2002 |title=For Ruiz, Overtime Is His Prime Time |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/26/sports/sp-galaxy26 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The Wizards won 4\u20131 in the second leg at [[Arrowhead Stadium]], setting up a series-deciding third match at the Rose Bowl.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=September 29, 2002 |title=Galaxy Can't Close It Out |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/29/sports/sp-galaxy29 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> Los Angeles won the third leg 5\u20132, with two goals each for Jones and Ruiz, and advanced to the Conference Finals with six points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 3, 2002 |title=Galaxy Kicks It Up a Notch |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/03/sports/sp-galaxy3 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The Galaxy played against the [[Colorado Rapids]] in the Western Conference Finals, held over the following week under the same format as the Semifinals. The team won 4\u20130 at the Rose Bowl and 1\u20130 at [[INVESCO Field]] in [[Denver]], bringing the Galaxy to their fourth MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 6, 2002 |title=Galaxy Makes Rapid Advance |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/06/sports/sp-galaxy6 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 10, 2002 |title=Ruiz Heads Galaxy Attack |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/10/sports/sp-galaxy10 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===New England Revolution===\n[[File:TaylorTwellman 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|right|x260px|New England Revolution forward [[Taylor Twellman]], who led the team in scoring]]\n\nThe Revolution failed to qualify for the playoffs in 2001,<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 2, 2001 |title=As in history, Revolution suppressed |page=C4 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349136/as_in_history_revolution_suppressed/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> following several years of poor on-field performances that resulted in the worst winning record of the league's ten teams.<ref>{{cite press release |date=January 24, 2002 |title=MLS Announces 2002 Regular Season Schedule |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0124schedule.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020127141936/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/02/mls0124schedule.html |archivedate=January 27, 2002 |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lemieux |first=Jeff |date=October 18, 2016 |title=History Lesson: Recapping every team MVP through the Revs' first 20 seasons |url=https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/post/2016/10/18/history-lesson-recapping-every-team-mvp-through-revs-first-20-seasons |publisher=New England Revolution |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> Despite their league performance, New England finished as runners-up to the Galaxy in the 2001 U.S. Open Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 28, 2001 |title=Revolution crumple in OT |page=C7 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349114/revolution_crumple_in_ot_open_cup/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> During the 2002 preseason, the club acquired several players from the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]] and [[Miami Fusion]] in trades and the [[2002 MLS Allocation Draft|Allocation Draft]] following the contraction of the two clubs, including league MVP [[Alex Pineda Chac\u00f3n]], forward [[Mamadou Diallo]], midfielder [[Steve Ralston]], and defender [[Carlos Llamosa]].<ref name=\"Globe-Clavijo\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=May 24, 2002 |title=Revolutionary change: Clavijo shown gate |page=E10 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25202818/revolutionary_change_clavijo_shown_gate/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 7, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> New England also drafted forward [[Taylor Twellman]] in the [[2002 MLS SuperDraft]] following a successful college career and a return from [[TSV 1860 Munich]].<ref>{{cite news |date=March 21, 2002 |title=New England Revolution: 2002 Outlook |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/s/2002/0319/1354391.html |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHead coach [[Fernando Clavijo]] was fired after the seventh match of the season, with the Revolution only winning two.<ref name=\"Globe-Clavijo\"/> Assistant coach [[Steve Nicol]] was promoted to interim head coach on May 23 and completed a turnaround from last to first in the Eastern Conference, leading the team into the playoffs and earning the [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|coach of the year]] award.<ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/><ref name=\"NYT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Revolution and Galaxy Are Pursuing First Title |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/20/sports/soccer-revolution-and-galaxy-are-pursuing-first-title.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> New England finished the season with a six-match unbeaten streak and a total record of 12 wins, 14 losses, and two draws, scoring a league-high 49 goals.<ref name=\"NYT-Preview\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=MLS History: New England Revolution, 2002 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/club/newengland/2002 |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> The team narrowly qualified for the playoffs on the final day of the season, with all three qualifiers from the Eastern Conference within one point of each other.<ref name=\"LAT-Preview\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Revs\"/>\n\nNew England played the seventh-seeded [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] in the Conference Semifinals, winning the first leg 2\u20130 at Gillette Stadium on goals by Twellman and [[Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez (soccer)|Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 27, 2002 |title=Revolution on fire |page=E1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349083/revolution_on_fire/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Fire won the second leg 2\u20131, setting up a deciding match at Gillette Stadium on October 2.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 30, 2002 |title=Harris not discouraged by loss |page=D8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349101/harris_not_discouraged_by_loss/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution won 2\u20130 in the third match, clinching their first playoff series win and advancing to face the [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 3, 2002 |title=Extinguished |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349160/extinguished/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 12, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The first leg at Gillette Stadium was a scoreless tie and the Revolution won the second leg in Columbus 1\u20130 on an early goal scored by defender [[Jay Heaps]], who was later ejected for an altercation with [[Freddy Garc\u00eda (footballer)|Freddy Garc\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 7, 2002 |title=They'll proceed\u2014with cautions |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349521/theyll_proceedwith_cautions/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 10, 2002 |title=Revolution take command |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349525/revolution_take_command/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> After earning a 2\u20130 lead in the third leg, New England conceded two late goals to draw 2\u20132 and force overtime. Neither team could score the [[golden goal]] needed to clinch a series win outright, leaving the Revolution with 5\u20132 in points and qualifying them for the MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 13, 2002 |title=A final foothold |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177086/a_final_foothold/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution became the second team to play an MLS Cup final at their home stadium, following [[D.C. United]] in [[MLS Cup '97|1997]], which also held the attendance record.<ref name=\"AP-Galaxy\"/> Despite a sprain in his right knee after the last match of the Conference Final, Twellman recovered in time for the cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 18, 2002 |title=Sunday RSVP for MVP favorite |page=E6 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25380261/sunday_rsvp_for_mvp_favorite/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[New England Revolution]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[2002 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]'''||'''28'''||'''16'''||'''9'''||'''3'''||'''51'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]||28||14||11||3||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||28||12||9||7||'''43'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|4||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||28||13||11||4||'''43'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|5||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||28||9||10||9||'''36'''\n|}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2002 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2002 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[New England Revolution]]'''||'''28'''||'''12'''||'''14'''||'''2'''||'''38'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]]||28||11||12||5||'''38'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]||28||11||13||4||'''37'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|MetroStars]]||28||11||15||2||35\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[D.C. United]]||28||9||14||5||32\n|}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|[[2002 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]] (6\u20133)\n|3\u20132 {{aet}} (H)\n|1\u20134 (A)\n|5\u20132 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] (6\u20133)\n|2\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20132 (A)\n|2\u20130 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]] (6\u20130)\n|4\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20130 (A)\n|\u2014\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] (5\u20132)\n|0\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20130 (A)\n|2\u20132 (H)\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]]. English play-by-play commentary was provided by [[JP Dellacamera]] with color analysis by [[Ty Keough]] and pregame and halftime shows hosted by [[Terry Gannon]] and [[Eric Wynalda]], reprising their roles from ABC's coverage of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Griffith |first=Bill |date=October 19, 2002 |title=He'll have angles covered |page=E8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25349656/hell_have_angles_covered/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 18, 2002 |title=Best bets |page=D2 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]}}</ref> The Spanish broadcast was handled by play-by-play commentator [[Ernesto Motta]] and color analyst Andres Rodriguez.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 16, 2002 |title=ABC Sports Presents MLS Cup 2002 |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/abc-sports-presents-mls-cup-2002/n-1976535 |publisher=Major League Soccer |via=Our Sports Central |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The ABC broadcast was watched by an estimated audience of 1.2 million views, the lowest for an MLS Cup at the time.<ref>{{cite news |author=Paulsen |date=November 24, 2010 |title=Record Low Rating For 2010 MLS Cup |url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2010/11/record-low-rating-for-2010-mls-cup/ |work=[[Sports Media Watch]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:CarlosRuiz.jpg|thumb|left|Forward [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]], whose [[golden goal]] won the MLS Cup for the Los Angeles Galaxy|x260px]]\n\nThe 2002 final was referred by [[Kevin Terry]], who previously officiated the [[MLS Cup 1998|1998 final]]. In the event of a draw after regulation time, the match would be decided by two 15-minute [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] periods with the [[golden goal]]s followed by a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] if necessary.<ref name=\"Globe-Tickets\"/><ref name=\"MediaGuide\">{{cite web |date=October 2002 |title=2002 MLS Cup Media Guide |page=9 |url=http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002cup_pub.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030714055453/http://mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/2002cup_pub.pdf |archivedate=July 14, 2003 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> At kickoff, set for 1:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastern Time, the weather in Foxborough was sunny with a temperature of {{convert|56|F|C}}.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\">{{cite news |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Galaxy Exorcises Their Demons |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/02/2002mlscup.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021031142336/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/02/2002mlscup.html |archivedate=October 31, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles kicked off the match and had most of the chances in the scoreless first half while preventing the Revolution from making a single shot on goal.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> The Galaxy had the game's first two shots, in the 12th and 17th minutes, but they failed to be shot on target by [[Tyrone Marshall]] and Carlos Ruiz. New England responded with a cross by [[Joe Franchino]] in the 26th minute for [[Taylor Twellman]] and [[Steve Ralston]], but neither could reach the ball in time.<ref name=\"AP-SI\">{{cite news |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Fourth time's the charm: Ruiz's golden goal beats Revs, gives L.A. first MLS title |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2002/mls_cup/news/2002/10/20/mlscup_gamer/ |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021106201215/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2002/mls_cup/news/2002/10/20/mlscup_gamer/ |archivedate=November 6, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> Franchino was shown a [[yellow card (sport)|yellow card]] in the 24th minute for a challenge on [[Cobi Jones]], one of several that the two captains traded.<ref name=\"USA-Dure\">{{cite news |last=Dure |first=Beau |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Golden goal rescues MLS Cup |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/columnist/dure/2002-10-20-dure_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021154231/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/columnist/dure/2002-10-20-dure_x.htm |archivedate=October 21, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe second half began with a series of hard challenges by players on both teams to win possession of the ball, which was sent down the flanks by the Galaxy's Cobi Jones and the Revolution's [[Leo Cullen (soccer)|Leo Cullen]]. Both wingers sent in crosses that were hit towards the goal and deflected away.<ref name=\"USA-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Gardiner |first=Andy |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Finally \u2014 Los Angeles claims MLS title |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2002-10-20-mls-cup_x.htm |work=USA Today |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021024222035/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2002-10-20-mls-cup_x.htm |archivedate=October 24, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Minute\">{{cite news |date=October 20, 2002 |title=Galaxy Take the Cup |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/ |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021022134939/http://www.mlsnet.com/ |archivedate=October 22, 2002 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> During the last ten minutes of regulation time, both teams produced several chances that were deflected away by defenders, with the Revolution relying on substitute [[Alex Pineda Chac\u00f3n]], who entered in the 75th minute.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/><ref name=\"USA-Summary\"/> Ruiz was given a clear shot on goal in the 80th minute, but the ball was deflected away by defender [[Daouda Kant\u00e9]] for a goal kick.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 3, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #48 Risky Business |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/03/top-50-mls-cup-moments-48-risky-business |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> A final shot by Chac\u00f3n in [[stoppage time]] was saved by Galaxy goalkeeper [[Kevin Hartman]], his first of the match, and the MLS Cup final was sent into overtime.<ref name=\"USA-Dure\"/>\n\nThe Galaxy took control of the match during overtime, with an early chance in the 93rd minute missed by Jones. A [[bicycle kick]] by Ruiz in the 102nd minute was saved by Revolution goalkeeper [[Adin Brown]], who followed minutes later with a second save on Ruiz at the beginning of the second overtime period.<ref name=\"USA-Summary\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Minute\"/> A wayward shot by New England substitute [[Winston Griffiths (soccer)|Winston Griffiths]] in the 111th minute was deflected and hit the crossbar, preventing the game-winning goal.<ref name=\"USA-Dure\"/> The Galaxy cleared the deflected ball and followed two minutes later with a diagonal cross by defender Tyrone Marshall that found Ruiz, who hit a left-footed that shot past Brown and went into the net.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 21, 2002 |title=Out of this world |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379759/out_of_this_world/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 13, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The MLS Cup final, the longest match in MLS Cup history, ended after 113 minutes with Ruiz's golden goal.<ref name=\"AP-SI\"/><ref name=\"USA-Summary\"/> Ruiz was named the MLS Cup [[most valuable player]] for his winning goal.<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box \n|date = October 20, 2002\n|time = 13:30 [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|score = 1\u20130 ([[Overtime (sports)|2OT]]) \n|report = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/mls-cup-2002-los-angeles-galaxy-1-new-england-revolution-0 Report]\n|team2 = [[New England Revolution]] \n|goals1 = [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Ruiz]] {{golden goal|113}}\n|goals2 = \n|stadium = [[Gillette Stadium]]<br>[[Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n|attendance = 61,316\n|referee = [[Kevin Terry]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''LOS ANGELES GALAXY:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kevin Hartman]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Califf]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''30'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Alexi Lalas]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Tyrone Marshall]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|VIN}} [[Ezra Hendrickson]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Cobi Jones]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Simon Elliott]] || {{yel|95}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]] || || {{suboff|62}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sasha Victorine]] \n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|GUA}} [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|VEN}} [[Alejandro Moreno]] || || {{suboff|67}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vagenas]] || || {{subon|62}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Albright]] || || {{subon|67}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sigi Schmid]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''NEW ENGLAND REVOLUTION:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Adin Brown]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jay Heaps]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Carlos Llamosa]] || {{yel|60}} || {{suboff|90+2}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|MLI}} [[Daouda Kant\u00e9]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Franchino]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|24}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Ralston]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Leo Cullen (soccer)|Leo Cullen]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez (soccer)|Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Kamler]] || || {{suboff|90}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Wolde Harris]] || || {{suboff|75}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Taylor Twellman]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Rusty Pierce]] || || {{subon|90+2}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|HON}} [[Alex Pineda Chac\u00f3n]] || || {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''25'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Winston Griffiths (soccer)|Winston Griffiths]] || || {{subon|90}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Steve Nicol]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|GUA}} [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]] (Los Angeles Galaxy)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''<ref name=\"MLS-Report\">{{cite web |title=MLS Cup 2002: Los Angeles Galaxy 1, New England Revolution 0 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/mls-cup-2002-los-angeles-galaxy-1-new-england-revolution-0 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Greg Barkey\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Richard Eddy\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Michael Kennedy (referee)|Michael Kennedy]]\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''<ref name=\"MediaGuide\"/>\n*90 minutes of regulation time\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still tied.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe match was the first in MLS Cup history to have a scoreless half and remain scoreless at the end of regulation time.<ref name=\"AP-SI\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Report\"/> It was also the third and final MLS Cup to be decided by a [[golden goal]] in overtime,<ref name=\"MLS-Summary\"/> a short-lived rule that would be replaced with a conventional [[extra time (association football)|extra time]] period in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reineking |first=Jim |date=December 7, 2017 |title=MLS Cup: Ranking every championship game |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2017/12/06/mls-cup-ranking-every-game/926051001/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Turner |first=Elliott |date=November 29, 2013 |title=The final letdown: five US soccer showpieces that failed to achieve lift-off |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/nov/29/mls-cup-sporting-kc-real-salt-lake |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The match was attended by 61,316 spectators,  a figure that remains among the highest in MLS playoff history and set a record for an MLS Cup final that was later surpassed in [[MLS Cup 2018|2018]] by [[Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Roberson |first=Doug |date=December 8, 2018 |title=Atlanta United sets MLS Cup attendance record |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-sets-mls-cup-attendance-record/lJVEXg0pSHjtlNJ7TM06hK/ |work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN-2014\">{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=December 3, 2014 |title=The Galaxy and Revolution set to pen another chapter in MLS history |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/blog/name/93/post/2177571/headline |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 26, 2017 |title=Steffen leads Crew past Atlanta United on penalties |url=http://www.latimes.com/ct-hoy-steffen-leads-crew-past-atlanta-united-on-penalties-20171026-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy finished their 2002 season with a loss to the Columbus Crew in the [[2002 U.S. Open Cup]] four days later in [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dillman |first=Lisa |date=October 25, 2002 |title=Galaxy Is Cut Down by Crew |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/oct/25/sports/sp-galaxy25 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref> Both teams qualified for the [[2003 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], where the Revolution would be eliminated in the first round and the Galaxy would lose in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=March 21, 2003 |title=Revolution's road trip not environmentally friendly\n|page=E5 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177320/revolutions_road_trip_concacaf/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gutierrez |first1=Paul |last2=Jones |first2=Grahame L. |date=April 17, 2003 |title=Galaxy Eliminated in Champions Cup |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/apr/17/sports/sp-soccer17 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy and Revolution met again in the [[MLS Cup 2005|2005 final]], where Los Angeles repeated their championship with a 1\u20130 win after [[Overtime (Association football)|extra time]].<ref name=\"ESPN-2014\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 14, 2005 |title=A case of deja blue |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25177239/a_case_of_deja_blue/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2018}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution would go on to lose the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2006|2006]] and [[MLS Cup 2007|2007]] to the [[Houston Dynamo]] and in [[MLS Cup 2014|2014]] to the Galaxy, who would claim their fifth title.<ref>{{cite news |last=Powers |first=John |date=December 8, 2014 |title=Galaxy defeat Revolution for record fifth MLS title |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Due to their finishes as MLS Cup runners-up, the Revolution are known as the \"[[Buffalo Bills]] of MLS\", mirroring the football team's second-place finishes at the [[Super Bowl]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Felt |first=Hunter |date=December 9, 2014 |title=Can the Revolution ever thrive in the Boston sports market? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/dec/09/can-the-revolution-ever-thrive-in-the-boston-sports-market |work=The Guardian |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLS Cup}}\n{{Los Angeles Galaxy matches}}\n{{New England Revolution matches}}\n\n[[Category:MLS Cup|2002]]\n[[Category:2002 Major League Soccer season|*]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy matches]]\n[[Category:New England Revolution matches]]\n[[Category:October 2002 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2002 in sports in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:21st century in Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary of results:adding source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Cup_2002"}
{"title_page": "Salticus palpalis", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n|regnum=[[Animal]]ia\n|phylum=[[Arthropod]]a\n|classis=[[Arachnid]]a\n|ordo=[[Spider|Araneae]]\n|familia=[[Jumping spider|Salticidae]]\n|genus=''[[Salticus]]''\n|species='''''S. palpalis'''''\n|binomial=''Salticus palpalis''\n|binomial_authority= (Banks, 1904)}}\n\n'''''Salticus palpalis''''' is a species of [[spider]] from the family [[jumping spider|Salticidae]].\n\n==Description==\nThe species are black coloured, with white stripes on the back. The males have brownish back, while females are completely black.<ref>[http://tolweb.org/Salticus_palpalis Description]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4122072}}\n\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders of the United States]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1904]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Nathan Banks]]\n\n\n{{jumping-spider-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n|regnum=[[Animal]]ia\n|phylum=[[Arthropod]]a\n|classis=[[Arachnid]]a\n|ordo=[[Spider|Araneae]]\n|familia=[[Jumping spider|Salticidae]]\n|genus=''[[Salticus]]''\n|species='''''S. palpalis'''''\n|binomial=''Salticus palpalis''\n|binomial_authority= (Banks, 1904)}}\n\n'''''Salticus palpalis''''' is a species of [[spider]] from a [[jumping spider|Salticidae]] family.\n\n==Description==\nThe species are black coloured, with white stripes on the back. The males have brownish back, while females are completely black.<ref>[http://tolweb.org/Salticus_palpalis Description]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4122072}}\n\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders of the United States]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1904]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Nathan Banks]]\n\n\n{{jumping-spider-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salticus_palpalis"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 2001", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|2001 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title = MLS Cup 2001\n| event = [[MLS Cup]]\n| image = MLSCup2001.png\n| image_size = 200\n| team1 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = After [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] with a [[golden goal]]\n| date = October 21, 2001\n| stadium = [[Mapfre Stadium|Columbus Crew Stadium]]\n| city = [[Columbus, Ohio]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Dwayne De Rosario]]<br />(San Jose Earthquakes)\n| weather = Partly cloudy, {{convert|68|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| attendance = 21,626\n| referee = [[Kevin Stott]]\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 2000|2000]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 2002|2002]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2001''' was the sixth edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on October 21, 2001, at [[Columbus Crew Stadium]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. It was contested by the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], a pair of [[California Cl\u00e1sico|in-state rivals]] from [[California]], to decide the champion of the [[2001 Major League Soccer season|2001 season]]. San Jose won their first title, defeating Los Angeles 2\u20131 in overtime with a [[golden goal]] scored by [[Dwayne De Rosario]] in the 96th minute.\n\nSan Jose were appearing in their first MLS Cup, while Los Angeles had lost two previous finals; the two teams finished at the top of the Western Division in regular season play, which was cut short by the [[September 11 attacks]]. The Earthquakes, under their first season with manager [[Frank Yallop]], won their quarterfinals series against the [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] over two legs and defeated the league-leading [[Miami Fusion]] after [[extra time]] in the third leg of the semifinals. The Galaxy defeated the [[MetroStars]] in the quarterfinals and [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] in the semifinals with a golden goal scored in extra time of the third leg for both series.\n\nIt was the first MLS Cup to match two teams from both the same conference and state against each other, and the second MLS Cup to end with a golden goal. Frank Yallop became the first former MLS player to coach a team to an MLS Cup title. Crew Stadium became the first [[soccer-specific stadium]] to host the MLS Cup, which had an attendance of 21,626 spectators.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Columbus crew stadium mls allstars 2005.jpg|thumb|left|[[Columbus Crew Stadium]], the league's first [[soccer-specific stadium]], hosted MLS Cup 2001.|alt=A soccer stadium with a grass field, crowds in the stands, a distant scoreboard, and a blimp flying overhead during the game.]]\n\nThe match was played at [[Columbus Crew Stadium]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]], and was the first MLS Cup to be hosted at a [[soccer-specific stadium]]. [[Lamar Hunt]], owner of the [[Columbus Crew]], built the $28.5 million stadium with soccer and concerts as its primary uses, with a capacity of 22,500 seats (lower than most MLS venues of the time) and close-in seating next to the field.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gardner |first=Charles F. |date=June 1, 1999 |title=Field of dreams: MLS sees Columbus stadium as a model for others |page=8 |work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]}}</ref> MLS awarded the hosting rights for the [[2000 MLS All-Star Game]] and MLS Cup 2001 to Columbus during the stadium's groundbreaking ceremony on August 14, 1998.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=August 15, 1998 |title=Workers will stay busy on Crew stadium |page=D1 |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> The stadium opened on May 15, 1999, and hosted several [[United States men's national soccer team|national team]] matches in the months before the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=April 6, 2001 |title=MLS Cup '01 highlights busy year |page=7 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=June 6, 2001 |title=Ecuador match will test U.S. players' fitness |page=E3 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> The design of Crew Stadium inspired similar soccer-specific stadiums, including the [[Home Depot Center]] for the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] and [[Toyota Park (Bridgeview, Illinois)|Toyota Park]] for the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], which began construction in 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=June 13, 2001 |title=MLS building boom in works: Stadium set for Los Angeles; Chicago, New York next up |page=E7 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]], a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2001 Major League Soccer season|2001 season]] was the sixth in the league's history and was contested by twelve teams organized into three divisions (later renamed conferences). Each team was to play a total of 28 matches in the regular season, which ran from April to September, facing teams within their division four times and outside of their division twice.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010602133302/http://mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |archivedate=June 2, 2001 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The shortened schedule, with four fewer matches, and a smaller roster limited to 18 players under a $1.7 million [[salary cap]] reflected the league's financial troubles at the time.<ref name=\"WT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=April 7, 2001 |title=MLS tightens belt for sixth season |page=C8 |work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref> The MLS Cup Playoffs ran from mid-September to October and was contested by the winners of the three divisions and five [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] teams with the most points regardless of division, who were then seeded based on overall standings.<ref name=\"MN-Rules\">{{cite news |last=Meacham |first=Jody |date=March 18, 2000 |title=MLS revamps rules, divisions |page=D3 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> The playoffs were organized into three rounds, the first two being a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with the first team to earn five points advancing, and the single-match MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\"/>\n\nMLS Cup 2001 was contested between the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], both from the Western Division. It was the first MLS Cup with finalists from the same division and the same state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 10, 2007 |title=Revolution ride bike to MLS Cup |page=C5 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> San Jose had never appeared in an MLS Cup final, while Los Angeles lost the [[MLS Cup 1996|1996]] and [[MLS Cup 1999|1999]] finals to [[D.C. United]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Robledo |first=Fred J. |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Galaxy are ready to win |page=B9 |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]}}</ref> The finalists played each other twice during the regular season, both won by the Earthquakes, but two additional matches in the series to be played at the end of the regular season were canceled after the [[September 11 attacks]], which shortened the league's season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gillespie |first=Charlie |date=October 20, 2001 |title=San Jose tries to go from worst to first |page=D5 |work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28163333/san_jose_tries_to_go_from_worst_to_first/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 13, 2001 |title=MLS Season, Playoffs to Be Adjusted |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-ussoccer13sep13.story?coll=la-headlines-sports-soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010913192714/http://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-ussoccer13sep13.story?coll=la-headlines-sports-soccer |archivedate=September 13, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> Due to several teams having already played an extra match, playoff seeding was determined by [[points per game]] and matches began a week later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 14, 2001 |title=MLS to omit final games of regular season |page=E9 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28124926/mls_to_omit_final_games_of_regular/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 14, 2001 |title=MLS Cancels Rest of Regular Season |page=D7 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/14/sports/sp-45680 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes and Galaxy also met each other in the quarterfinals of the [[2001 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] in July, which Los Angeles won 10\u20139 in a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] following a 1\u20131 draw after [[extra time]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=July 25, 2001 |title=Galaxy Finally Solves Earthquakes in the Open Cup |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/25/sports/sp-26301 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===San Jose Earthquakes===\n{{further|2001 San Jose Earthquakes season}}\n[[File:LandonDonovan1.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|In his rookie season with San Jose, forward [[Landon Donovan]] scored two goals in the quarterfinals of the playoffs.|alt=Landon Donovan, wearing a blue jersey, uses his body to hold off a defender wearing a red jersey.]]\n\nThe San Jose Earthquakes, originally named the San Jose Clash until 2000,<ref name=\"MN-Rules\"/> had historically been among the worst teams in the league and went through four coaching changes in its first six seasons.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Michelle |date=October 5, 2001 |title=Longtime Quakes say wins now are sweeter |page=E2 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Longtime-Quakes-say-wins-now-are-sweeter-2871944.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> The Clash finished sixth overall in the [[1996 Major League Soccer season|inaugural season]] and qualified for the playoffs, where they were eliminated in the first round by the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Secore |first=Damian |date=October 21, 2001 |title=MLS Cup has SoCal feeling |page=C3 |work=The Press-Enterprise}}</ref> The team then missed the playoffs in the following five seasons, including four with losing records and finishing last in the league twice and second-to-last three times.<ref name=\"Payne-0201\">{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=February 13, 2001 |title=Team made several off-season moves: Quakes' shake-up put to test |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The Earthquakes finished last in the league during the 2000 season with only seven wins and declined to renew the contract of head coach [[Lothar Osiander]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=January 13, 2001 |title=Quakes opt not to renew Osiander's contract as coach |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Killion |first=Ann |date=January 23, 2001 |title=Sharks giving Quakes chance in sudden death |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> Despite rumors that the team would fold, the [[San Jose Sharks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] took over business operations from the [[Robert Kraft|Kraft Sports Group]] in January 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last=Oritz |first=Jorge L. |date=January 11, 2001 |title=Sharks Bosses to Run Quakes |page=D8 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[D.C. United]] assistant coach [[Frank Yallop]] was hired as San Jose's head coach days before the [[2001 MLS SuperDraft|2001 draft]], where he began a series of player moves alongside assistant coach [[Dominic Kinnear]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giesin |first=Dan |date=February 4, 2001 |title=Earthquakes' Draft Should Shake Up Existing Roster |page=C9 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Earthquakes-Draft-Should-Shake-Up-Existing-Roster-2955688.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> During the first week of Yallop's tenure, the Earthquakes acquired defender [[Jeff Agoos]] from D.C. United, [[Manny Lagos]] from the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]], and defender [[Zak Ibsen]] from the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref name=\"Payne-0201\"/> Yallop also used the league's allocation system to sign U.S. forward [[Landon Donovan]] from [[Bayer Leverkusen]] in March and Canadian forward [[Dwayne De Rosario]] from the [[Richmond Kickers]] of the second-division [[A-League (1995\u20132004)|A-League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giesin |first=Dan |date=March 30, 2001 |title=Quakes Get Budding Star |page=E11 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=February 5, 2001 |title=Earthquakes Trade For United's Agoos |page=C8 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SOCCER-Earthquakes-Trade-For-United-s-Agoos-2955597.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> By the end of their preseason preparations in April, the team had also traded with the [[MetroStars]] for defender [[Ramiro Corrales]] and signed Danish midfielder [[Ronnie Ekelund]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=February 23, 2001 |title=MetroStars Trade For Goalie |page=D9 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/23/sports/plus-soccer-metrostars-trade-for-goalie.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=April 18, 2001 |title=Preki, Kansas City brace for homecoming |page=D3 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes opened their regular season with a 3\u20132 win in the [[California Cl\u00e1sico]] over the Los Angeles Galaxy, but lost their next two matches to Dallas and Miami.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 8, 2001 |title=Galaxy Runs Cold and Hot in Opener |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/08/sports/sp-48590 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=April 29, 2001 |title=Stingy Cannon helps 'Quakes tie Wizards |page=B9 |work=[[Contra Costa Times]]}}</ref> The team then went on twelve-match unbeaten streak from late April to early July, winning seven matches and drawing in five, taking a lead in the Western Division standings ahead of Los Angeles.<ref name=\"SJE-History\">{{cite web |title=Club History |url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/club/history |publisher=San Jose Earthquakes |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=July 5, 2001 |title=Holding their ground |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> Yallop relied on a strong central core, consisting of Agoos and [[Troy Dayak]] in defense alongside Ekelund and [[Richard Mulrooney]] in the midfield to support the team's rotating attackers.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 25, 2001 |title=Donovan, Lagos are keys up front for San Jose |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/09/25/quakes_outlook_sa/ |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020224043724/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/09/25/quakes_outlook_sa/ |archivedate=February 24, 2002 |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> Six players from the Earthquakes were named to the league's Western Division roster at the [[2001 MLS All-Star Game]], which was hosted at San Jose's [[Spartan Stadium (San Jose)|Spartan Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=July 28, 2001  |title=Quakes a magnitude six on the All-Star pitch |page=D1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/SOCCER-NOTEBOOK-Quakes-a-magnitude-six-on-the-2894453.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the last months of the season, the Earthquakes were defeated in several matches and lost their first-place spot to the Galaxy only to regain it on several occasions.<ref name=\"SCS-Aug\">{{cite news |last=McMorries |first=Ben |date=August 22, 2001 |title=Quakes falling short of their goals |page=D2 |work=Santa Cruz Sentinel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28201153/quakes_falling_short_of_their_goals/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 8, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> San Jose clinched a playoff spot and second place in the Western Division with 45 points after losing to the [[Kansas City Wizards]] prior to the cancellation of the two remaining matches against the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 9, 2001 |title=Quakes fall out of lead in West |page=D7 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref><ref name=\"SJM-Halt\">{{cite news |last=Miedema |first=Laurence |date=September 14, 2001 |title=MLS halts season, prepares for playoffs |page=D2 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The Earthquakes finished the season with the best record and winning percentage in club history, while the defense lead the league with only 30 allowed goals.<ref name=\"SJE-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=September 23, 2001 |title=Quakes win with defense |page=C3 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> Frank Yallop was voted the [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]], while Agoos earned [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|Defender of the Year]] honors and Dayak was named the [[MLS Comeback Player of the Year Award|Comeback Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=October 20, 2001 |title=Agoos, Llamosa are young at heart |page=C5 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\nSan Jose were seeded fifth in the playoffs and faced the fourth-seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]], who had earned the same number of points but won a head-to-head tiebreaker.<ref name=\"SJM-Halt\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=September 14, 2001 |title=Crew winds up with home-field advantage |page=E3 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> The Earthquakes won 3\u20131 during the first leg in Columbus, with Donovan scoring two goals and Manny Lagos scoring another after having his [[red card (sports)|red card]] suspension rescinded by the league.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=September 23, 2001 |title=Earthquakes rock Crew with opening-game win |page=D1 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> San Jose defeated Columbus 3\u20130 in the second leg and advanced with six points to their first-ever MLS Cup semifinal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gomez |first=Mark |date=September 27, 2001 |title=Quakes sweep series with Crew |page=D8 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The Earthquakes fell 1\u20130 to the [[Supporters' Shield]]-winning Miami Fusion in the first leg of the semifinals, but responded with a 4\u20130 win at Spartan Stadium to tie the series at three points apiece and force a third match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Michelle |date=October 15, 2001 |title=Quakes shake Fusion; Donovan's goal helps force deciding game |page=D3 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Quakes-shake-Fusion-Donovan-s-goal-helps-force-2868987.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gomez |first=Mark |date=October 15, 2001 |title=Earthquakes beat back Fusion to force a decisive third game |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The third match, played in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], remained scoreless into extra time, where Troy Dayak scored a [[golden goal]] in the 94th minute to clinch a series victory and San Jose's first appearance at an MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 18, 2001 |title=Earthquakes reach MLS title game |page=E1 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Galaxy===\n{{further|2001 Los Angeles Galaxy season}}\n\nThe Los Angeles Galaxy were one of the most successful teams during the early years of MLS, winning the Western Conference three times and appearing in five consecutive playoffs prior to 2001.<ref name=\"SeasonReview\">{{cite web |title=2001 Season in Review |url=https://www.lagalaxy.com/club/history/2001 |publisher=LA Galaxy |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=October 2002 |title=MLS Cup Preview: Los Angeles Galaxy |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/teams_la.html |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030214222408/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/teams_la.html |archivedate=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The team advanced to the MLS Cup final in 1996 and 1999, losing both times to [[D.C. United]].<ref name=\"LAT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Galaxy Ties It Again |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/21/sports/sp-59894 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy won the 1998 [[Supporters' Shield]] and the [[2000 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], becoming the second MLS team to win a continental trophy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=Matthew |date=October 8, 2011 |title=LA clinch 2nd straight Supporters' Shield with Seattle loss |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/09/la-clinch-2nd-straight-supporters-shield-seattle-loss |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> [[Sigi Schmid]] was named the team's head coach early in the 1999 season and took the team to the MLS Cup with an emphasis on defensive play.<ref>{{cite news |last=Green |first=Jeff |date=December 19, 1999 |title=One trophy short: L.A. wins individual awards, seeks ultimate team reward |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/1999/mls_cup/news/1999/11/20/galaxysaturday_practice/ |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604151112/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/1999/mls_cup/news/1999/11/20/galaxysaturday_practice/ |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The team finished the 2000 season as the second-placed team in the Western Conference and were eliminated in the playoff semifinals by the division-leading [[Kansas City Wizards]], who would go on to win the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 7, 2000 |title=It's End of the Road for Galaxy |page=D2 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/oct/07/sports/sp-32932 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 16, 2000 |title=Wizards' Meola Saves Best for Last |page=D1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A13474-2000Oct15.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy traded captain and veteran defender [[Robin Fraser]] to the [[Colorado Rapids]] before the 2001 season to meet the league's [[salary cap]] requirements.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 2, 2001 |title=Fraser's Galaxy Days Are Finished |page=D13 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/02/sports/sp-45907 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The team remained mostly unchanged from the 2000 season, with the addition of veteran defender [[Alexi Lalas]] and young forwards [[Brian Ching]] and [[Brian Mullan]] picked during the SuperDraft.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 7, 2001 |title=Start of MLS Season Can't Come Soon Enough for Lalas |page=D2 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/07/sports/sp-48012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Schmid planned to use a 3\u20135\u20132 formation to take advantage of the team's midfield depth, with the ability to switch to a 4\u20133\u20133 in certain situations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 5, 2001 |title=Galaxy Has Big-Time Goals |page=D10 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28242875/galaxy_has_bigtime_goals/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 10, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles lost its opening two matches to San Jose and Kansas City, but a change in several starting positions lead to three consecutive wins and a 4\u20134 draw with the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 22, 2001 |title=Galaxy Cures Its Early Troubles |page=D8 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/22/sports/sp-54280 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=May 10, 2001 |title=Galaxy Salvages 4-4 Tie |page=D9 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/10/sports/sp-61577 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy used its several wins to reach second in the Western Division standings, passing Kansas City but falling behind the unbeaten San Jose Earthquakes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=June 24, 2001 |title=Galaxy Strikes Late in Victory |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jun/24/sports/sp-14252 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The cancellation of the [[2001 FIFA Club World Championship]] left a gap in the team's schedule in late July and early August, which was partially replaced with previously-rescheduled league matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=May 19, 2001 |title=Galaxy's World Is Rocked |page=D11 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/19/sports/sp-65535 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> By early September, the Galaxy had begun challenging the Earthquakes for first place in the Western Division, winning seven of nine matches before a scheduled two-match series against San Jose to close out the regular season.<ref name=\"SCS-Aug\"/><ref name=\"SeasonReview\"/> After the matches were canceled, Los Angeles was declared the Western Division champion with 47 points and seeded third in the playoffs bracket.<ref name=\"SJM-Halt\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Balderas |first=Al |date=September 14, 2001 |title=Galaxy given division title by MLS |page=A1 |work=[[Orange County Register]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy played against the sixth-seeded New York/New Jersey [[MetroStars]] in the quarterfinals, coached by former Galaxy manager [[Octavio Zambrano]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 23, 2001 |title=Apple of His Eye |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/23/sports/sp-49001 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first leg, at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]], ended in a 1\u20131 draw after a second-half goal by [[Paul Caligiuri]], who was ejected in the second half alongside MetroStars midfielder [[Gilmar Ant\u00f4nio Batista|Gilmar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Arkush |first=Michael |date=September 24, 2001 |title=Depleted MetroStars Hang On for Tie |page=D12 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/24/sports/soccer-depleted-metrostars-hang-on-for-tie.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The second leg, played at [[Giants Stadium]] in New Jersey, was one of the first sporting events in the New York City area following the September 11 attacks;<ref>{{cite news |last=Bolster |first=John |date=September 7, 2011 |title=9/11 Memorial: MLSers recall when soccer returned to NY |url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2011/09/07/911-memorial-mlsers-recall-when-soccer-returned-ny |publisher=[[New York Red Bulls]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> the MetroStars defeated the Galaxy by a scoreline of 4\u20131, coming from behind after conceding an early goal to Los Angeles, and took a three-point lead in the quarterfinals series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 27, 2001 |title=Galaxy on the Brink of Elimination After Loss |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/27/sports/sp-50414 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles hosted the third match of the series at the Rose Bowl and took a 2\u20130 lead in the first half on two goals by [[Sasha Victorine]]. After conceding a third goal in the second half, the MetroStars responded with two goals by [[Petter Villegas]], losing 3\u20132 to the Galaxy in regular time to tie the series at four points apiece. The tie went into [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death]] extra time, which ended after eight minutes when [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]] scored the winning golden goal for Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Arkush |first=Michael |date=September 30, 2001 |title=Two Chances to Advance Aren't Enough for MetroStars |page=D6 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/30/sports/soccer-two-chances-to-advance-aren-t-enough-for-metrostars.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 30, 2001 |title=After Long Day, Galaxy Advances |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/30/sports/sp-51731 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a rematch of the U.S. Open Cup semifinal, Los Angeles faced the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], winners of the Central Division, in the MLS Cup semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 10, 2001 |title=Galaxy Will Need to Put It Together Against the Fire |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/10/sports/sp-55471 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first leg at Chicago's [[Soldier Field]] ended in a 1\u20131 draw between the two teams after an overtime goal by Cobi Jones was ruled invalid due to a tackle by Brian Mullan.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 11, 2001 |title=Galaxy Can't Put Out Fire |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/11/sports/sp-55939 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy won 1\u20130 overtime in the second leg on a golden goal from [[Peter Vagenas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 14, 2001 |title=Hernandez Is Just in Time |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/14/sports/sp-57224 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The third and final leg, also hosted at Soldier Field, remained tied at 1\u20131 after regular time and finished with a golden goal scored by Cienfuegos in the 98th minute of extra time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Foltman |first=Bob |date=October 18, 2001 |title=Fire's season comes to end |page=3 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-10-18-0110180351-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> With their 2\u20131 victory over Chicago, the Los Angeles Galaxy advanced to their third MLS Cup final in six seasons. The team would also have a chance to be the first American team to win a continental [[treble (association football)|treble]], having already won the [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] in January and being scheduled to play in the [[U.S. Open Cup]] final a week after the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 18, 2001 |title=Galaxy on Target, and in Title Game |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/18/sports/sp-58694 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|2nd place in [[2001 Major League Soccer season#Western Division|Western Division]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|1||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||26||14||7||5||'''47'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|'''2'''||align=left|'''[[San Jose Earthquakes]]'''||'''26'''||'''13'''||'''7'''||'''6'''||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||27||11||13||3||'''36'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||26||5||13||4||'''23'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2001 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2001 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2001 Major League Soccer season#Western Division|Western Division]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]'''||'''26'''||'''14'''||'''7'''||'''5'''||'''47'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]||26||13||7||6||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||27||11||13||3||'''36'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||26||5||13||4||'''23'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2001 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|[[2001 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] (6\u20130)\n|3\u20131 (A)\n|3\u20130 (H)\n|\u2014\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Quarterfinals\n|align=left|[[MetroStars]] (4\u20134)\n|1\u20131 (H)\n|1\u20134 (A)\n|3\u20132 ([[Sudden death (sport)|SDET]]) (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[Miami Fusion]] (6\u20133)\n|0\u20131 (A)\n|4\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20130 {{aet}} (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] (7\u20131)\n|1\u20131 (A)\n|1\u20130 {{aet}} (H)\n|2\u20131 {{aet}} (A)\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish. The network moved the start time of the match by one hour from 1:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]] to 12:30&nbsp;p.m. to accommodate scheduling changes caused by the September 11 attacks.<ref name=\"MLS-Oct\">{{cite press release |date=October 1, 2001 |title=MLS Cup Start Time Moved To 12:30ET |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/mls1001mlscuptime.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020630191413/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/mls1001mlscuptime.html |archivedate=June 30, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> The English commentary crew consisted of [[Jack Edwards (sportscaster)|Jack Edwards]] for play-by-play, [[Ty Keough]] with [[Color commentator|color analysis]], and other programming hosted by [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]] and [[Dave Dir]].<ref name=\"MLS-Oct\"/> The Spanish broadcast was transmitted over [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]] on ABC and was headlined by play-by-play commentator [[Hammer Londo\u00f1o]] and color analyst [[Hernan Pereyra]] of [[Radio Unica]]. The match was also broadcast in 108 other countries by [[ESPN International]].<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 16, 2001 |title=Down To The Wire |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/weekly1016.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011109070329/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/weekly1016.html |archivedate=November 9, 2001 |accessdate=March  7, 2019}}</ref> The ABC broadcast earned a 1.0 [[Nielsen rating]], beating the previous two editions of the cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=December 4, 2012 |title=MLS Cup television ratings dip |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/49487/mls-cup-television-ratings-dip.html |work=Soccer America |url-access=subscription |accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:DwayneDeRosario.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|[[Dwayne De Rosario]] scored the [[golden goal]] to win the MLS Cup for San Jose and was named the match MVP.|alt=Dwayne De Rosario, wearing a blue jersey, prepares to strike a soccer ball on the ground with his right foot.]]\n\nThe match was played only four days after the MLS Cup semifinals, in front of a predominantly neutral crowd of 21,626 at Columbus Crew Stadium with several thousand no-show ticketholders.<ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 22, 2001 |title=From Bottom to Top |page=D14 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A30928-2001Oct21.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> A group of about 100 Chicago Fire supporters appeared at the match to taunt the Galaxy with chants and drums.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pucin |first=Diane |date=October 22, 2001 |title=He's Just What MLS Needs |page=D11 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/22/sports/sp-60186 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The pregame ceremony included an appearance by six members of the [[New York City Fire Department]] and [[New York City Police Department]] and the national anthem sung by [[Toya (singer)|Toya]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite press release |date=October 18, 2001 |title=MLS Cup 2001 News & Notes |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/mls-cup-2001-news--notes/n-2708532 |publisher=Major League Soccer |via=Our Sports Central |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BH\">{{cite news |last=Martins |first=Gus |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Schmid, Galaxy must kick back |page=72 |work=[[The Boston Herald]]}}</ref> The match was the first MLS Cup to be refereed by [[Kevin Stott]], who previously served as the fourth official at [[MLS Cup 2000]].<ref name=\"Notes\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=MLS Cup Roll of Honor |url=http://proreferees.com/officials/mls-cup-roll-of-honor/ |publisher=[[Professional Referee Organization]] |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes began the match with the majority of possession, which was used to build up to several attacking chances that were cleared away by Galaxy goalkeeper [[Kevin Hartman]]. Los Angeles, however, had a chance of its own in the 14th minute on a cross by [[Cobi Jones]] towards [[Sasha Victorine]] that was passed on to [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]], whose shot was cleared away by San Jose. The Galaxy opened the scoring in 21st minute on a goal by [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Luis Hern\u00e1ndez]], who received a {{convert|40|yd|m|adj=mid}} pass from defender [[Greg Vanney]].<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite news |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Worst to first: Golden goal lifts Quakes over Galaxy 2-1 in MLS Cup |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/10/21/mlscup_gamer/ |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113001048/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/10/21/mlscup_gamer/ |archivedate=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles then missed an opportunity to take a 2\u20130 lead in the 35th minute after a shot from Cobi Jones was saved by goalkeeper [[Joe Cannon (soccer)|Joe Cannon]].<ref name=\"LAT-Report\">{{cite news |date=October 22, 2001 |title=MLS Cup Game Report |page=D11 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28281436/mls_cup_game_report/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=March 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Earthquakes found an equalizing goal shortly before halftime in the 43rd minute on a play started by [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]]'s run down the right wing. He slipped a pass to [[Richard Mulrooney]], whose cross over the box was volleyed by [[Landon Donovan]] into the top-right corner of the goal.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"SI\"/>\n\nSan Jose went on to outshoot Los Angeles 12\u20133 in the second half and created several chances to score, including a free kick taken by [[Jeff Agoos]] that hit the left goalpost.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"SI\"/> After receiving a [[yellow card (sport)|yellow card]] for a challenge on Ian Russell, Galaxy defender [[Paul Caligiuri]] was substituted in the 53rd minute\u2014marking the end of his MLS career.<ref name=\"LAT-Report\"/> Three additional yellow cards were issued in the second half to [[Danny Califf]], [[Ronnie Ekelund]], and [[Zak Ibsen]]; Ibsen had only been substituted a minute before drawing the card.<ref name=\"BH\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Report\"/> [[Dwayne De Rosario]] was substituted into the game in the 85th minute for [[Ronald Cerritos]], shortly before the tied match forced a sudden-death overtime.<ref name=\"SI\"/> De Rosario scored the winning [[golden goal]] in the sixth minute of overtime with a dribble around Califf and a shot from {{convert|17|yd|m}} that Hartman managed to touch, but was unable to save.<ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=October 22, 2001 |title=DeRosario's overtime goal lifts Quakes to MLS crown |url=http://www.bayarea.com/c/category/sports_and_recreation/soccer/san_jose_earthquakes/docs/mercurynews/quakes22x.htm |work=The Mercury News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011211224401/http://www.bayarea.com/c/category/sports_and_recreation/soccer/san_jose_earthquakes/docs/mercurynews/quakes22x.htm |archivedate=December 11, 2001 |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Earthquakes' victory is extra special |page= |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Earthquakes-victory-is-extra-special-2866446.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> It was the second time in MLS Cup history that the title was decided by a golden goal, following the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural edition]] between D.C. United and the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 21, 2001 |title=DeRosario Stunner Gives San Jose the Title |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/01/mlscup2001.html |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011122133507/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/01/mlscup2001.html |archivedate=November 22, 2001 |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box \n|date = October 21, 2001\n|time = 12:30 [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|score = 2\u20131 {{aet}}\n|report = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2001 Report]\n|team2 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] \n|goals1 = \n* [[Landon Donovan|Donovan]] {{goal|43}}\n* [[Dwayne De Rosario|De Rosario]] {{golden goal|96}}\n|goals2 = [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Hern\u00e1ndez]] {{goal|21}}\n|stadium = [[Columbus Crew Stadium]]\n|location = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n|attendance = 21,626\n|referee = [[Kevin Stott]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''SAN JOSE EARTHQUAKES:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Cannon (soccer)|Joe Cannon]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jimmy Conrad]] || {{yel|28}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Troy Dayak]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Wade Barrett (soccer)|Wade Barrett]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ramiro Corrales]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Ronnie Ekelund]] || {{yel|78}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richard Mulrooney]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]] || || {{suboff|82}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Landon Donovan]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Ronald Cerritos]] || || {{suboff|85}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''0''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jon Conway]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Zak Ibsen]] || {{yel|83}} || {{subon|82}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Manny Lagos]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Bower]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]] || || {{subon|85}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Junior Agogo]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Frank Yallop]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''LOS ANGELES GALAXY:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kevin Hartman]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Greg Vanney]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|VIN}} [[Ezra Hendrickson]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Caligiuri]] || {{yel|48}} || {{suboff|53}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Califf]] || {{yel|76}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vagenas]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Simon Elliott]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Cobi Jones]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|FW ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sasha Victorine]] || || {{suboff|75}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Luis Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Reis]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Craig Waibel]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Adam Frye]] || || {{subon|53}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Isaias Bardales Jr.]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Ching]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Mullan]] || || {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''25'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Marvin Quijano]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sigi Schmid]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]] (San Jose Earthquakes)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Roger Itaya\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Daniel Wilson\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Tamberino]]\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with a [[golden goal]] to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still tied.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe Earthquakes completed a \"worst to first\" finish, which was named the greatest turnaround in MLS history.<ref name=\"AP-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Gillespie |first=Charley |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Earthquakes Shake L.A. To Capture MLS Cup |page=B5 |work=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28281322/earthquakes_shake_la_to_capture_mls/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 10, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Frank Yallop became the first former MLS player to win the MLS Cup as head coach, as well as the first non-American manager to win the championship.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Wise |first=Mike |date=November 15, 2004 |title=United on Top of Its Game |page=A1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A50056-2004Nov14.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref> Dwayne De Rosario was named the MLS Cup MVP for his golden goal, despite entering the match in the 85th minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robledo |first=Fred J. |date=October 22, 2001 |title=This one's just not in the stars for Galaxy |page=B1 |work=Long Beach Press-Telegram}}</ref> The Galaxy lost their third final in six years, with the match against San Jose described as the \"most difficult\" by coach Sigi Schmid.<ref>{{cite news |last=Znidar |first=Mark |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Galaxy endures yet another cup spill |page=D3 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> The Galaxy went on to win the [[2001 U.S. Open Cup]] a week later, defeating the [[New England Revolution]] 2\u20131 in overtime.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 28, 2001 |title=Redemption Corner for Califf, Galaxy |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/28/sports/sp-62639 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles met New England again at [[MLS Cup 2002]], winning 1\u20130 in overtime for their first MLS Cup title.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 21, 2002 |title=Galaxy Sitting on Top of World |page=D6 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A56525-2002Oct20.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> San Jose won their second MLS Cup in the [[MLS Cup 2003|2003 final]] at the Galaxy's newly-constructed [[soccer-specific stadium]], the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], after eliminating the hosts in the playoffs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Earthquakes Win MLS Cup |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/24/sports/sp-mls24 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSan Jose qualified for the [[2002 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] alongside the finalists from [[MLS Cup 2000]], Chicago and Kansas City, due to the cancellation of the previous Champions' Cup and the transition to the new, expanded cup format.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 10, 2001 |title=Club Competitions in the Football Confederation Reborn as FC Champons' Cup Begins New League Format for 2002 |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2014/03/17/13/58/club-competitions-in-the-football-confederation-reborn-as-fc-champons-cup-begins-new-league-format-f |publisher=[[United States Soccer Federation]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes advanced from the first round against [[Club Deportivo Olimpia|C.D. Olimpia]] by winning 1\u20130 at the [[Miami Orange Bowl]] and 3\u20131 at a small stadium in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Voet |first=Gary |date=March 17, 2002 |title=Sellout crowd sees Quakes roll |page=C2 |work=[[Sacramento Bee]]}}</ref> San Jose then faced [[C.F. Pachuca]] in the quarterfinals and lost 3\u20130 in the away leg played in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=April 24, 2002 |title=Pachuca has big edge in series |page=C3 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Pachuca-has-big-edge-in-series-2846379.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes rallied to win 1\u20130 the following week in the home leg, but were eliminated from the cup with an [[aggregate score]] of 1\u20133.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Jelani |date=April 25, 2002 |title=Quakes win game, lose series |work=[[The Argus (Fremont)|The Argus]] |location=Fremont, California}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes and its players were later relocated to Houston after the 2005 season, becoming the [[Houston Dynamo]]. The Dynamo won consecutive MLS Cup championships in their first two seasons after relocation, while the Earthquakes returned to the league as an [[expansion team]] in the 2008 season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 19, 2007 |title=The Dynamo's Double Standard |page=E1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/18/AR2007111800390.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy went on to win five MLS Cup titles, including two against the Dynamo in the [[MLS Cup 2011|2011]] and [[MLS Cup 2012|2012]] finals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Powers |first=John |date=December 8, 2014 |title=Galaxy defeat Revolution for record fifth MLS title |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLS Cup}}\n<!--{{2001 in American soccer}}-->\n{{San Jose Earthquakes matches}}\n{{Los Angeles Galaxy matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2001 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:2001 Major League Soccer season|*MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy matches|MLS Cup 2001]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes matches|MLS Cup 2001]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:October 2001 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2001 in sports in Ohio]]\n[[Category:21st century in Columbus, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|2001 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title = MLS Cup 2001\n| event = [[MLS Cup]]\n| image = MLSCup2001.png\n| image_size = 200\n| team1 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = After [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] with a [[golden goal]]\n| date = October 21, 2001\n| stadium = [[Mapfre Stadium|Columbus Crew Stadium]]\n| city = [[Columbus, Ohio]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Dwayne De Rosario]]<br />(San Jose Earthquakes)\n| weather = Partly cloudy, {{convert|68|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| attendance = 21,626\n| referee = [[Kevin Stott]]\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 2000|2000]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 2002|2002]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2001''' was the sixth edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), which took place on October 21, 2001, at [[Columbus Crew Stadium]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. It was contested by the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], a pair of [[California Cl\u00e1sico|in-state rivals]] from [[California]], to decide the champion of the [[2001 Major League Soccer season|2001 season]]. San Jose won their first title, defeating Los Angeles 2\u20131 in overtime with a [[golden goal]] scored by [[Dwayne De Rosario]] in the 96th minute.\n\nSan Jose were appearing in their first MLS Cup, while Los Angeles had lost two previous finals; the two teams finished at the top of the Western Division in regular season play, which was cut short by the [[September 11 attacks]]. The Earthquakes, under their first season with manager [[Frank Yallop]], won their quarterfinals series against the [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] over two legs and defeated the league-leading [[Miami Fusion]] after [[extra time]] in the third leg of the semifinals. The Galaxy defeated the [[MetroStars]] in the quarterfinals and [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] in the semifinals with a golden goal scored in extra time of the third leg for both series.\n\nIt was the first MLS Cup to match two teams from both the same conference and state against each other, and the second MLS Cup to end with a golden goal. Frank Yallop became the first former MLS player to coach a team to an MLS Cup title. Crew Stadium became the first [[soccer-specific stadium]] to host the MLS Cup, which had an attendance of 21,626 spectators.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Columbus crew stadium mls allstars 2005.jpg|thumb|left|[[Columbus Crew Stadium]], the league's first [[soccer-specific stadium]], hosted MLS Cup 2001.|alt=A soccer stadium with a grass field, crowds in the stands, a distant scoreboard, and a blimp flying overhead during the game.]]\n\nThe match was played at [[Columbus Crew Stadium]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]], and was the first MLS Cup to be hosted at a [[soccer-specific stadium]]. [[Lamar Hunt]], owner of the [[Columbus Crew]], built the $28.5 million stadium with soccer and concerts as its primary uses, with a capacity of 22,500 seats (lower than most MLS venues of the time) and close-in seating next to the field.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gardner |first=Charles F. |date=June 1, 1999 |title=Field of dreams: MLS sees Columbus stadium as a model for others |page=8 |work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]}}</ref> MLS awarded the hosting rights for the [[2000 MLS All-Star Game]] and MLS Cup 2001 to Columbus during the stadium's groundbreaking ceremony on August 14, 1998.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=August 15, 1998 |title=Workers will stay busy on Crew stadium |page=D1 |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> The stadium opened on May 15, 1999, and hosted several [[United States men's national soccer team|national team]] matches in the months before the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=April 6, 2001 |title=MLS Cup '01 highlights busy year |page=7 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=June 6, 2001 |title=Ecuador match will test U.S. players' fitness |page=E3 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> The design of Crew Stadium inspired similar soccer-specific stadiums, including the [[Home Depot Center]] for the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] and [[Toyota Park (Bridgeview, Illinois)|Toyota Park]] for the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], which began construction in 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=June 13, 2001 |title=MLS building boom in works: Stadium set for Los Angeles; Chicago, New York next up |page=E7 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]], a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2001 Major League Soccer season|2001 season]] was the sixth in the league's history and was contested by twelve teams organized into three divisions (later renamed conferences). Each team was to play a total of 28 matches in the regular season, which ran from April to September, facing teams within their division four times and outside of their division twice.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010602133302/http://mlsnet.com/about/league/overview.html |archivedate=June 2, 2001 |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> The shortened schedule, with four fewer matches, and a smaller roster limited to 18 players under a $1.7 million [[salary cap]] reflected the league's financial troubles at the time.<ref name=\"WT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=April 7, 2001 |title=MLS tightens belt for sixth season |page=C8 |work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref> The MLS Cup Playoffs ran from mid-September to October and was contested by the winners of the three divisions and five [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] teams with the most points regardless of division, who were then seeded based on overall standings.<ref name=\"MN-Rules\">{{cite news |last=Meacham |first=Jody |date=March 18, 2000 |title=MLS revamps rules, divisions |page=D3 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref> The playoffs were organized into three rounds, the first two being a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with the first team to earn five points advancing, and the single-match MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\"/>\n\nMLS Cup 2001 was contested between the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], both from the Western Division. It was the first MLS Cup with finalists from the same division and the same state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 10, 2007 |title=Revolution ride bike to MLS Cup |page=C5 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> San Jose had never appeared in an MLS Cup final, while Los Angeles lost the [[MLS Cup 1996|1996]] and [[MLS Cup 1999|1999]] finals to [[D.C. United]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Robledo |first=Fred J. |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Galaxy are ready to win |page=B9 |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]}}</ref> The finalists played each other twice during the regular season, both won by the Earthquakes, but two additional matches in the series to be played at the end of the regular season were canceled after the [[September 11 attacks]], which shortened the league's season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gillespie |first=Charlie |date=October 20, 2001 |title=San Jose tries to go from worst to first |page=D5 |work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28163333/san_jose_tries_to_go_from_worst_to_first/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 13, 2001 |title=MLS Season, Playoffs to Be Adjusted |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-ussoccer13sep13.story?coll=la-headlines-sports-soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010913192714/http://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-ussoccer13sep13.story?coll=la-headlines-sports-soccer |archivedate=September 13, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> Due to several teams having already played an extra match, playoff seeding was determined by [[points per game]] and matches began a week later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=September 14, 2001 |title=MLS to omit final games of regular season |page=E9 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28124926/mls_to_omit_final_games_of_regular/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 14, 2001 |title=MLS Cancels Rest of Regular Season |page=D7 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/14/sports/sp-45680 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes and Galaxy also met each other in the quarterfinals of the [[2001 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] in July, which Los Angeles won 10\u20139 in a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] following a 1\u20131 draw after [[extra time]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=July 25, 2001 |title=Galaxy Finally Solves Earthquakes in the Open Cup |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/25/sports/sp-26301 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===San Jose Earthquakes===\n{{further|2001 San Jose Earthquakes season}}\n[[File:LandonDonovan1.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|In his rookie season with San Jose, forward [[Landon Donovan]] scored two goals in the quarterfinals of the playoffs.|alt=Landon Donovan, wearing a blue jersey, uses his body to hold off a defender wearing a red jersey.]]\n\nThe San Jose Earthquakes, originally named the San Jose Clash until 2000,<ref name=\"MN-Rules\"/> had historically been among the worst teams in the league and went through four coaching changes in its first six seasons.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Michelle |date=October 5, 2001 |title=Longtime Quakes say wins now are sweeter |page=E2 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Longtime-Quakes-say-wins-now-are-sweeter-2871944.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> The Clash finished sixth overall in the [[1996 Major League Soccer season|inaugural season]] and qualified for the playoffs, where they were eliminated in the first round by the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Secore |first=Damian |date=October 21, 2001 |title=MLS Cup has SoCal feeling |page=C3 |work=The Press-Enterprise}}</ref> The team then missed the playoffs in the following five seasons, including four with losing records and finishing last in the league twice and second-to-last three times.<ref name=\"Payne-0201\">{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=February 13, 2001 |title=Team made several off-season moves: Quakes' shake-up put to test |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The Earthquakes finished last in the league during the 2000 season with only seven wins and declined to renew the contract of head coach [[Lothar Osiander]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=January 13, 2001 |title=Quakes opt not to renew Osiander's contract as coach |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Killion |first=Ann |date=January 23, 2001 |title=Sharks giving Quakes chance in sudden death |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> Despite rumors that the team would fold, the [[San Jose Sharks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] took over business operations from the [[Robert Kraft|Kraft Sports Group]] in January 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last=Oritz |first=Jorge L. |date=January 11, 2001 |title=Sharks Bosses to Run Quakes |page=D8 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[D.C. United]] assistant coach [[Frank Yallop]] was hired as San Jose's head coach days before the [[2001 MLS SuperDraft|2001 draft]], where he began a series of player moves alongside assistant coach [[Dominic Kinnear]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giesin |first=Dan |date=February 4, 2001 |title=Earthquakes' Draft Should Shake Up Existing Roster |page=C9 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Earthquakes-Draft-Should-Shake-Up-Existing-Roster-2955688.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> During the first week of Yallop's tenure, the Earthquakes acquired defender [[Jeff Agoos]] from D.C. United, [[Manny Lagos]] from the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]], and defender [[Zak Ibsen]] from the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref name=\"Payne-0201\"/> Yallop also used the league's allocation system to sign U.S. forward [[Landon Donovan]] from [[Bayer Leverkusen]] in March and Canadian forward [[Dwayne De Rosario]] from the [[Richmond Kickers]] of the second-division [[A-League (1995\u20132004)|A-League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giesin |first=Dan |date=March 30, 2001 |title=Quakes Get Budding Star |page=E11 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=February 5, 2001 |title=Earthquakes Trade For United's Agoos |page=C8 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SOCCER-Earthquakes-Trade-For-United-s-Agoos-2955597.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> By the end of their preseason preparations in April, the team had also traded with the [[MetroStars]] for defender [[Ramiro Corrales]] and signed Danish midfielder [[Ronnie Ekelund]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=February 23, 2001 |title=MetroStars Trade For Goalie |page=D9 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/23/sports/plus-soccer-metrostars-trade-for-goalie.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=April 18, 2001 |title=Preki, Kansas City brace for homecoming |page=D3 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes opened their regular season with a 3\u20132 win in the [[California Cl\u00e1sico]] over the Los Angeles Galaxy, but lost their next two matches to Dallas and Miami.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 8, 2001 |title=Galaxy Runs Cold and Hot in Opener |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/08/sports/sp-48590 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=April 29, 2001 |title=Stingy Cannon helps 'Quakes tie Wizards |page=B9 |work=[[Contra Costa Times]]}}</ref> The team then went on twelve-match unbeaten streak from late April to early July, winning seven matches and drawing in five, taking a lead in the Western Division standings ahead of Los Angeles.<ref name=\"SJE-History\">{{cite web |title=Club History |url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/club/history |publisher=San Jose Earthquakes |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=July 5, 2001 |title=Holding their ground |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> Yallop relied on a strong central core, consisting of Agoos and [[Troy Dayak]] in defense alongside Ekelund and [[Richard Mulrooney]] in the midfield to support the team's rotating attackers.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 25, 2001 |title=Donovan, Lagos are keys up front for San Jose |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/09/25/quakes_outlook_sa/ |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020224043724/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/09/25/quakes_outlook_sa/ |archivedate=February 24, 2002 |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> Six players from the Earthquakes were named to the league's Western Division roster at the [[2001 MLS All-Star Game]], which was hosted at San Jose's [[Spartan Stadium (San Jose)|Spartan Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=July 28, 2001  |title=Quakes a magnitude six on the All-Star pitch |page=D1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/SOCCER-NOTEBOOK-Quakes-a-magnitude-six-on-the-2894453.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the last months of the season, the Earthquakes were defeated in several matches and lost their first-place spot to the Galaxy only to regain it on several occasions.<ref name=\"SCS-Aug\">{{cite news |last=McMorries |first=Ben |date=August 22, 2001 |title=Quakes falling short of their goals |page=D2 |work=Santa Cruz Sentinel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28201153/quakes_falling_short_of_their_goals/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 8, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> San Jose clinched a playoff spot and second place in the Western Division with 45 points after losing to the [[Kansas City Wizards]] prior to the cancellation of the two remaining matches against the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 9, 2001 |title=Quakes fall out of lead in West |page=D7 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref><ref name=\"SJM-Halt\">{{cite news |last=Miedema |first=Laurence |date=September 14, 2001 |title=MLS halts season, prepares for playoffs |page=D2 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The Earthquakes finished the season with the best record and winning percentage in club history, while the defense lead the league with only 30 allowed goals.<ref name=\"SJE-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=September 23, 2001 |title=Quakes win with defense |page=C3 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> Frank Yallop was voted the [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]], while Agoos earned [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|Defender of the Year]] honors and Dayak was named the [[MLS Comeback Player of the Year Award|Comeback Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=October 20, 2001 |title=Agoos, Llamosa are young at heart |page=C5 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\nSan Jose were seeded fifth in the playoffs and faced the fourth-seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]], who had earned the same number of points but won a head-to-head tiebreaker.<ref name=\"SJM-Halt\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=September 14, 2001 |title=Crew winds up with home-field advantage |page=E3 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> The Earthquakes won 3\u20131 during the first leg in Columbus, with Donovan scoring two goals and Manny Lagos scoring another after having his [[red card (sports)|red card]] suspension rescinded by the league.<ref>{{cite news |last=Merz |first=Craig |date=September 23, 2001 |title=Earthquakes rock Crew with opening-game win |page=D1 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> San Jose defeated Columbus 3\u20130 in the second leg and advanced with six points to their first-ever MLS Cup semifinal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gomez |first=Mark |date=September 27, 2001 |title=Quakes sweep series with Crew |page=D8 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The Earthquakes fell 1\u20130 to the [[Supporters' Shield]]-winning Miami Fusion in the first leg of the semifinals, but responded with a 4\u20130 win at Spartan Stadium to tie the series at three points apiece and force a third match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Michelle |date=October 15, 2001 |title=Quakes shake Fusion; Donovan's goal helps force deciding game |page=D3 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Quakes-shake-Fusion-Donovan-s-goal-helps-force-2868987.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gomez |first=Mark |date=October 15, 2001 |title=Earthquakes beat back Fusion to force a decisive third game |page=D1 |work=The Mercury News}}</ref> The third match, played in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], remained scoreless into extra time, where Troy Dayak scored a [[golden goal]] in the 94th minute to clinch a series victory and San Jose's first appearance at an MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 18, 2001 |title=Earthquakes reach MLS title game |page=E1 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Galaxy===\n{{further|2001 Los Angeles Galaxy season}}\n\nThe Los Angeles Galaxy were one of the most successful teams during the early years of MLS, winning the Western Conference three times and appearing in five consecutive playoffs prior to 2001.<ref name=\"SeasonReview\">{{cite web |title=2001 Season in Review |url=https://www.lagalaxy.com/club/history/2001 |publisher=LA Galaxy |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=October 2002 |title=MLS Cup Preview: Los Angeles Galaxy |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/teams_la.html |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030214222408/http://www.mlsnet.com/special/mlscup/02/teams_la.html |archivedate=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The team advanced to the MLS Cup final in 1996 and 1999, losing both times to [[D.C. United]].<ref name=\"LAT-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Galaxy Ties It Again |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/21/sports/sp-59894 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy won the 1998 [[Supporters' Shield]] and the [[2000 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], becoming the second MLS team to win a continental trophy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=Matthew |date=October 8, 2011 |title=LA clinch 2nd straight Supporters' Shield with Seattle loss |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/09/la-clinch-2nd-straight-supporters-shield-seattle-loss |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> [[Sigi Schmid]] was named the team's head coach early in the 1999 season and took the team to the MLS Cup with an emphasis on defensive play.<ref>{{cite news |last=Green |first=Jeff |date=December 19, 1999 |title=One trophy short: L.A. wins individual awards, seeks ultimate team reward |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/1999/mls_cup/news/1999/11/20/galaxysaturday_practice/ |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604151112/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/1999/mls_cup/news/1999/11/20/galaxysaturday_practice/ |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The team finished the 2000 season as the second-placed team in the Western Conference and were eliminated in the playoff semifinals by the division-leading [[Kansas City Wizards]], who would go on to win the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=October 7, 2000 |title=It's End of the Road for Galaxy |page=D2 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/oct/07/sports/sp-32932 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 16, 2000 |title=Wizards' Meola Saves Best for Last |page=D1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A13474-2000Oct15.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy traded captain and veteran defender [[Robin Fraser]] to the [[Colorado Rapids]] before the 2001 season to meet the league's [[salary cap]] requirements.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 2, 2001 |title=Fraser's Galaxy Days Are Finished |page=D13 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/02/sports/sp-45907 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The team remained mostly unchanged from the 2000 season, with the addition of veteran defender [[Alexi Lalas]] and young forwards [[Brian Ching]] and [[Brian Mullan]] picked during the SuperDraft.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 7, 2001 |title=Start of MLS Season Can't Come Soon Enough for Lalas |page=D2 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/07/sports/sp-48012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Schmid planned to use a 3\u20135\u20132 formation to take advantage of the team's midfield depth, with the ability to switch to a 4\u20133\u20133 in certain situations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 5, 2001 |title=Galaxy Has Big-Time Goals |page=D10 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28242875/galaxy_has_bigtime_goals/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 10, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles lost its opening two matches to San Jose and Kansas City, but a change in several starting positions lead to three consecutive wins and a 4\u20134 draw with the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 22, 2001 |title=Galaxy Cures Its Early Troubles |page=D8 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/22/sports/sp-54280 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=May 10, 2001 |title=Galaxy Salvages 4-4 Tie |page=D9 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/10/sports/sp-61577 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy used its several wins to reach second in the Western Division standings, passing Kansas City but falling behind the unbeaten San Jose Earthquakes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=June 24, 2001 |title=Galaxy Strikes Late in Victory |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jun/24/sports/sp-14252 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The cancellation of the [[2001 FIFA Club World Championship]] left a gap in the team's schedule in late July and early August, which was partially replaced with previously-rescheduled league matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=May 19, 2001 |title=Galaxy's World Is Rocked |page=D11 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/19/sports/sp-65535 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> By early September, the Galaxy had begun challenging the Earthquakes for first place in the Western Division, winning seven of nine matches before a scheduled two-match series against San Jose to close out the regular season.<ref name=\"SCS-Aug\"/><ref name=\"SeasonReview\"/> After the matches were canceled, Los Angeles was declared the Western Division champion with 47 points and seeded third in the playoffs bracket.<ref name=\"SJM-Halt\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Balderas |first=Al |date=September 14, 2001 |title=Galaxy given division title by MLS |page=A1 |work=[[Orange County Register]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy played against the sixth-seeded New York/New Jersey [[MetroStars]] in the quarterfinals, coached by former Galaxy manager [[Octavio Zambrano]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 23, 2001 |title=Apple of His Eye |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/23/sports/sp-49001 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first leg, at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]], ended in a 1\u20131 draw after a second-half goal by [[Paul Caligiuri]], who was ejected in the second half alongside MetroStars midfielder [[Gilmar Ant\u00f4nio Batista|Gilmar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Arkush |first=Michael |date=September 24, 2001 |title=Depleted MetroStars Hang On for Tie |page=D12 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/24/sports/soccer-depleted-metrostars-hang-on-for-tie.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The second leg, played at [[Giants Stadium]] in New Jersey, was one of the first sporting events in the New York City area following the September 11 attacks;<ref>{{cite news |last=Bolster |first=John |date=September 7, 2011 |title=9/11 Memorial: MLSers recall when soccer returned to NY |url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2011/09/07/911-memorial-mlsers-recall-when-soccer-returned-ny |publisher=[[New York Red Bulls]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> the MetroStars defeated the Galaxy by a scoreline of 4\u20131, coming from behind after conceding an early goal to Los Angeles, and took a three-point lead in the quarterfinals series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 27, 2001 |title=Galaxy on the Brink of Elimination After Loss |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/27/sports/sp-50414 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles hosted the third match of the series at the Rose Bowl and took a 2\u20130 lead in the first half on two goals by [[Sasha Victorine]]. After conceding a third goal in the second half, the MetroStars responded with two goals by [[Petter Villegas]], losing 3\u20132 to the Galaxy in regular time to tie the series at four points apiece. The tie went into [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death]] extra time, which ended after eight minutes when [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]] scored the winning golden goal for Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Arkush |first=Michael |date=September 30, 2001 |title=Two Chances to Advance Aren't Enough for MetroStars |page=D6 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/30/sports/soccer-two-chances-to-advance-aren-t-enough-for-metrostars.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 30, 2001 |title=After Long Day, Galaxy Advances |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/30/sports/sp-51731 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a rematch of the U.S. Open Cup semifinal, Los Angeles faced the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], winners of the Central Division, in the MLS Cup semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 10, 2001 |title=Galaxy Will Need to Put It Together Against the Fire |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/10/sports/sp-55471 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The first leg at Chicago's [[Soldier Field]] ended in a 1\u20131 draw between the two teams after an overtime goal by Cobi Jones was ruled invalid due to a tackle by Brian Mullan.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 11, 2001 |title=Galaxy Can't Put Out Fire |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/11/sports/sp-55939 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy won 1\u20130 overtime in the second leg on a golden goal from [[Peter Vagenas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 14, 2001 |title=Hernandez Is Just in Time |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/14/sports/sp-57224 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The third and final leg, also hosted at Soldier Field, remained tied at 1\u20131 after regular time and finished with a golden goal scored by Cienfuegos in the 98th minute of extra time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Foltman |first=Bob |date=October 18, 2001 |title=Fire's season comes to end |page=3 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-10-18-0110180351-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> With their 2\u20131 victory over Chicago, the Los Angeles Galaxy advanced to their third MLS Cup final in six seasons. The team would also have a chance to be the first American team to win a continental [[treble (association football)|treble]], having already won the [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] in January and being scheduled to play in the [[U.S. Open Cup]] final a week after the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 18, 2001 |title=Galaxy on Target, and in Title Game |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/18/sports/sp-58694 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top align=center|2nd place in [[2001 Major League Soccer season#Western Division|Western Division]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|1||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||26||14||7||5||'''47'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|'''2'''||align=left|'''[[San Jose Earthquakes]]'''||'''26'''||'''13'''||'''7'''||'''6'''||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||27||11||13||3||'''36'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||26||5||13||4||'''23'''\n|}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2001 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2001 Major League Soccer season#Western Division|Western Division]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|D|Draws}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]'''||'''26'''||'''14'''||'''7'''||'''5'''||'''47'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|2||align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]||26||13||7||6||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCD;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||27||11||13||3||'''36'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]||26||5||13||4||'''23'''\n|}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|[[2001 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent<br />({{tooltip|Pts.|Points}})\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|3rd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] (6\u20130)\n|3\u20131 (A)\n|3\u20130 (H)\n|\u2014\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Quarterfinals\n|align=left|[[MetroStars]] (4\u20134)\n|1\u20131 (H)\n|1\u20134 (A)\n|3\u20132 ([[Sudden death (sport)|SDET]]) (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[Miami Fusion]] (6\u20133)\n|0\u20131 (A)\n|4\u20130 (H)\n|1\u20130 {{aet}} (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] (7\u20131)\n|1\u20131 (A)\n|1\u20130 {{aet}} (H)\n|2\u20131 {{aet}} (A)\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish. The network moved the start time of the match by one hour from 1:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]] to 12:30&nbsp;p.m. to accommodate scheduling changes caused by the September 11 attacks.<ref name=\"MLS-Oct\">{{cite press release |date=October 1, 2001 |title=MLS Cup Start Time Moved To 12:30ET |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/mls1001mlscuptime.html |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020630191413/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/mls1001mlscuptime.html |archivedate=June 30, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> The English commentary crew consisted of [[Jack Edwards (sportscaster)|Jack Edwards]] for play-by-play, [[Ty Keough]] with [[Color commentator|color analysis]], and other programming hosted by [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]] and [[Dave Dir]].<ref name=\"MLS-Oct\"/> The Spanish broadcast was transmitted over [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]] on ABC and was headlined by play-by-play commentator [[Hammer Londo\u00f1o]] and color analyst [[Hernan Pereyra]] of [[Radio Unica]]. The match was also broadcast in 108 other countries by [[ESPN International]].<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 16, 2001 |title=Down To The Wire |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/weekly1016.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011109070329/http://www.mlsnet.com/content/01/weekly1016.html |archivedate=November 9, 2001 |accessdate=March  7, 2019}}</ref> The ABC broadcast earned a 1.0 [[Nielsen rating]], beating the previous two editions of the cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=December 4, 2012 |title=MLS Cup television ratings dip |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/49487/mls-cup-television-ratings-dip.html |work=Soccer America |url-access=subscription |accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:DwayneDeRosario.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|[[Dwayne De Rosario]] scored the [[golden goal]] to win the MLS Cup for San Jose and was named the match MVP.|alt=Dwayne De Rosario, wearing a blue jersey, prepares to strike a soccer ball on the ground with his right foot.]]\n\nThe match was played only four days after the MLS Cup semifinals, in front of a predominantly neutral crowd of 21,626 at Columbus Crew Stadium with several thousand no-show ticketholders.<ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 22, 2001 |title=From Bottom to Top |page=D14 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A30928-2001Oct21.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> A group of about 100 Chicago Fire supporters appeared at the match to taunt the Galaxy with chants and drums.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pucin |first=Diane |date=October 22, 2001 |title=He's Just What MLS Needs |page=D11 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/22/sports/sp-60186 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The pregame ceremony included an appearance by six members of the [[New York City Fire Department]] and [[New York City Police Department]] and the national anthem sung by [[Toya (singer)|Toya]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite press release |date=October 18, 2001 |title=MLS Cup 2001 News & Notes |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/mls-cup-2001-news--notes/n-2708532 |publisher=Major League Soccer |via=Our Sports Central |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BH\">{{cite news |last=Martins |first=Gus |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Schmid, Galaxy must kick back |page=72 |work=[[The Boston Herald]]}}</ref> The match was the first MLS Cup to be refereed by [[Kevin Stott]], who previously served as the fourth official at [[MLS Cup 2000]].<ref name=\"Notes\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=MLS Cup Roll of Honor |url=http://proreferees.com/officials/mls-cup-roll-of-honor/ |publisher=[[Professional Referee Organization]] |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes began the match with the majority of possession, which was used to build up to several attacking chances that were cleared away by Galaxy goalkeeper [[Kevin Hartman]]. Los Angeles, however, had a chance of its own in the 14th minute on a cross by [[Cobi Jones]] towards [[Sasha Victorine]] that was passed on to [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]], whose shot was cleared away by San Jose. The Galaxy opened the scoring in 21st minute on a goal by [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Luis Hern\u00e1ndez]], who received a {{convert|40|yd|m|adj=mid}} pass from defender [[Greg Vanney]].<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite news |date=October 21, 2001 |title=Worst to first: Golden goal lifts Quakes over Galaxy 2-1 in MLS Cup |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/10/21/mlscup_gamer/ |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113001048/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/mls/2001/mls_cup/news/2001/10/21/mlscup_gamer/ |archivedate=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles then missed an opportunity to take a 2\u20130 lead in the 35th minute after a shot from Cobi Jones was saved by goalkeeper [[Joe Cannon (soccer)|Joe Cannon]].<ref name=\"LAT-Report\">{{cite news |date=October 22, 2001 |title=MLS Cup Game Report |page=D11 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28281436/mls_cup_game_report/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=March 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Earthquakes found an equalizing goal shortly before halftime in the 43rd minute on a play started by [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]]'s run down the right wing. He slipped a pass to [[Richard Mulrooney]], whose cross over the box was volleyed by [[Landon Donovan]] into the top-right corner of the goal.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"SI\"/>\n\nSan Jose went on to outshoot Los Angeles 12\u20133 in the second half and created several chances to score, including a free kick taken by [[Jeff Agoos]] that hit the left goalpost.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"SI\"/> After receiving a [[yellow card (sport)|yellow card]] for a challenge on Ian Russell, Galaxy defender [[Paul Caligiuri]] was substituted in the 53rd minute\u2014marking the end of his MLS career.<ref name=\"LAT-Report\"/> Three additional yellow cards were issued in the second half to [[Danny Califf]], [[Ronnie Ekelund]], and [[Zak Ibsen]]; Ibsen had only been substituted a minute before drawing the card.<ref name=\"BH\"/><ref name=\"LAT-Report\"/> [[Dwayne De Rosario]] was substituted into the game in the 85th minute for [[Ronald Cerritos]], shortly before the tied match forced a sudden-death overtime.<ref name=\"SI\"/> De Rosario scored the winning [[golden goal]] in the sixth minute of overtime with a dribble around Califf and a shot from {{convert|17|yd|m}} that Hartman managed to touch, but was unable to save.<ref>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Dave |date=October 22, 2001 |title=DeRosario's overtime goal lifts Quakes to MLS crown |url=http://www.bayarea.com/c/category/sports_and_recreation/soccer/san_jose_earthquakes/docs/mercurynews/quakes22x.htm |work=The Mercury News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011211224401/http://www.bayarea.com/c/category/sports_and_recreation/soccer/san_jose_earthquakes/docs/mercurynews/quakes22x.htm |archivedate=December 11, 2001 |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Earthquakes' victory is extra special |page= |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Earthquakes-victory-is-extra-special-2866446.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> It was the second time in MLS Cup history that the title was decided by a golden goal, following the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural edition]] between D.C. United and the Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 21, 2001 |title=DeRosario Stunner Gives San Jose the Title |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/games/01/mlscup2001.html |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011122133507/http://www.mlsnet.com/games/01/mlscup2001.html |archivedate=November 22, 2001 |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box \n|date = October 21, 2001\n|time = 12:30 [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|score = 2\u20131 {{aet}}\n|report = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2001 Report]\n|team2 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] \n|goals1 = \n* [[Landon Donovan|Donovan]] {{goal|43}}\n* [[Dwayne De Rosario|De Rosario]] {{golden goal|96}}\n|goals2 = [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Hern\u00e1ndez]] {{goal|21}}\n|stadium = [[Columbus Crew Stadium]]\n|location = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n|attendance = 21,626\n|referee = [[Kevin Stott]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''SAN JOSE EARTHQUAKES:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Cannon (soccer)|Joe Cannon]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|DF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jimmy Conrad]] || {{yel|28}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Troy Dayak]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Wade Barrett (soccer)|Wade Barrett]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ramiro Corrales]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Ronnie Ekelund]] || {{yel|78}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richard Mulrooney]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]] || || {{suboff|82}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Landon Donovan]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Ronald Cerritos]] || || {{suboff|85}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''0''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jon Conway]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Zak Ibsen]] || {{yel|83}} || {{subon|82}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Manny Lagos]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ian Russell (soccer)|Ian Russell]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Bower]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]] || || {{subon|85}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Junior Agogo]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Frank Yallop]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|'''LOS ANGELES GALAXY:'''\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kevin Hartman]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Greg Vanney]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|VIN}} [[Ezra Hendrickson]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Caligiuri]] || {{yel|48}} || {{suboff|53}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Califf]] || {{yel|76}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vagenas]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Mauricio Cienfuegos]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Simon Elliott]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Cobi Jones]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|FW ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sasha Victorine]] || || {{suboff|75}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Luis Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Reis]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Craig Waibel]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Adam Frye]] || || {{subon|53}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Isaias Bardales Jr.]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Ching]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Mullan]] || || {{subon|75}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''25'''||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Marvin Quijano]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sigi Schmid]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]] (San Jose Earthquakes)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Roger Itaya\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Daniel Wilson\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Tamberino]]\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with a [[golden goal]] to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still tied.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe Earthquakes completed a \"worst to first\" finish, which was named the greatest turnaround in MLS history.<ref name=\"AP-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Gillespie |first=Charley |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Earthquakes Shake L.A. To Capture MLS Cup |page=B5 |work=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28281322/earthquakes_shake_la_to_capture_mls/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=February 10, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Frank Yallop became the first former MLS player to win the MLS Cup as head coach, as well as the first non-American manager to win the championship.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Wise |first=Mike |date=November 15, 2004 |title=United on Top of Its Game |page=A1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A50056-2004Nov14.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref> Dwayne De Rosario was named the MLS Cup MVP for his golden goal, despite entering the match in the 85th minute.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robledo |first=Fred J. |date=October 22, 2001 |title=This one's just not in the stars for Galaxy |page=B1 |work=Long Beach Press-Telegram}}</ref> The Galaxy lost their third final in six years, with the match against San Jose described as the \"most difficult\" by coach Sigi Schmid.<ref>{{cite news |last=Znidar |first=Mark |date=October 22, 2001 |title=Galaxy endures yet another cup spill |page=D3 |work=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> The Galaxy went on to win the [[2001 U.S. Open Cup]] a week later, defeating the [[New England Revolution]] 2\u20131 in overtime.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 28, 2001 |title=Redemption Corner for Califf, Galaxy |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/28/sports/sp-62639 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles met New England again at [[MLS Cup 2002]], winning 1\u20130 in overtime for their first MLS Cup title.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 21, 2002 |title=Galaxy Sitting on Top of World |page=D6 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A56525-2002Oct20.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> San Jose won their second MLS Cup in the [[MLS Cup 2003|2003 final]] at the Galaxy's newly-constructed [[soccer-specific stadium]], the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], after eliminating the hosts in the playoffs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=November 24, 2003 |title=Earthquakes Win MLS Cup |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/24/sports/sp-mls24 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSan Jose qualified for the [[2002 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] alongside the finalists from [[MLS Cup 2000]], Chicago and Kansas City, due to the cancellation of the previous Champions' Cup and the transition to the new, expanded cup format.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 10, 2001 |title=Club Competitions in the Football Confederation Reborn as FC Champons' Cup Begins New League Format for 2002 |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2014/03/17/13/58/club-competitions-in-the-football-confederation-reborn-as-fc-champons-cup-begins-new-league-format-f |publisher=[[United States Soccer Federation]] |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes advanced from the first round against [[Club Deportivo Olimpia|C.D. Olimpia]] by winning 1\u20130 at the [[Miami Orange Bowl]] and 3\u20131 at a small stadium in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Voet |first=Gary |date=March 17, 2002 |title=Sellout crowd sees Quakes roll |page=C2 |work=[[Sacramento Bee]]}}</ref> San Jose then faced [[C.F. Pachuca]] in the quarterfinals and lost 3\u20130 in the away leg played in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chapin |first=Dwight |date=April 24, 2002 |title=Pachuca has big edge in series |page=C3 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Pachuca-has-big-edge-in-series-2846379.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes rallied to win 1\u20130 the following week in the home leg, but were eliminated from the cup with an [[aggregate score]] of 1\u20133.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Jelani |date=April 25, 2002 |title=Quakes win game, lose series |work=[[The Argus (Fremont)|The Argus]] |location=Fremont, California}}</ref>\n\nThe Earthquakes and its players were later relocated to Houston after the 2005 season, becoming the [[Houston Dynamo]]. The Dynamo won consecutive MLS Cup championships in their first two seasons after relocation, while the Earthquakes returned to the league as an [[expansion team]] in the 2008 season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 19, 2007 |title=The Dynamo's Double Standard |page=E1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/18/AR2007111800390.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy went on to win five MLS Cup titles, including two against the Dynamo in the [[MLS Cup 2011|2011]] and [[MLS Cup 2012|2012]] finals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Powers |first=John |date=December 8, 2014 |title=Galaxy defeat Revolution for record fifth MLS title |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLS Cup}}\n<!--{{2001 in American soccer}}-->\n{{San Jose Earthquakes matches}}\n{{Los Angeles Galaxy matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2001 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:2001 Major League Soccer season|*MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy matches|MLS Cup 2001]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes matches|MLS Cup 2001]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:October 2001 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2001 in sports in Ohio]]\n[[Category:21st century in Columbus, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary of results:adding source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Cup_2001"}
{"title_page": "Rainbow Bridge (Kansas)", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Brush Creek Bridge\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image = Rainbow Curve Bridge 2006-07-03.jpg\n  | caption = Rainbow Bridge\n  | nearest_city= [[Baxter Springs, Kansas]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|37|4|24.25|N|94|44|26.04|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Kansas#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1923\n| architect= [[James Barney Marsh]]\n | added = March 10, 1983\n | governing_body = Local\n | mpsub=Rainbow Arch Marsh Arch Bridges of Kansas TR\n | refnum=83000419<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n[[Image:Rainbow Marsh Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|Rainbow bridge over Brush Creek]]\nThe '''Rainbow Bridge''' is an old bridge over Brush Creek approximately two miles west of [[Riverton, Kansas]] on former [[U.S. Route 66 in Kansas|U.S. Route&nbsp;66]] (US-66), now a county road. The bridge is a single-span concrete [[James Barney Marsh|Marsh arch bridge]] and is the sole surviving bridge of this type on the entire length of the former highway. Two other Marsh arch bridges were also located on US-66 in Kansas, both over the [[Spring River (Missouri)|Spring River]]. It was built in 1923.\n\nThe bridge has often been covered with graffiti, but was recently re-painted white. The bridge has been placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (as the Brush Creek Bridge) on March 10, 1983, due to its connection with US-66 and is also a Kansas state landmark. In 2014, Kansas Rt. 66 Historic Byway nominated a bypassed {{convert|2.1|mi|km}} section of original 1926 highway, which ran south from the Brush Creek to the Willow Creek bridge near Baxter Springs, for an NRHP listing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kshs.org/preserve/pdfs/007_ks_cherokeecounty_route66.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223010729/http://www.kshs.org/preserve/pdfs/007_ks_cherokeecounty_route66.pdf |archivedate=2015-02-23 }}</ref>\n\nThe bridge is fairly narrow, and due to traffic on the road, a replacement bridge has been built. The road curves toward the new bridge toward [[Baxter Springs, Kansas|Baxter Springs]], but a short, one-way road carries traffic to the Rainbow Bridge, which may still be crossed. This was part of a compromise after a disagreement between the county and the Kansas Route 66 Association as federal funds used for construction of the new bridge required demolition of the old. The bridge had been listed with the National Register, which prohibited condemnation of the old bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofamerica.com/picturepages/66KS-7-Baxter-RainbowBridge.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710232110/http://www.legendsofamerica.com/picturepages/66KS-7-Baxter-RainbowBridge.html |archivedate=2012-07-10 }}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2000, country singer [[Brad Paisley]] performed \"[[Route 66 (song)|Route 66]]\" on the bridge for the [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] special, \"Route 66: Main Street America\".\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|Transport}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Engineering}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Kansas}}\n* {{Portal-inline|National Register of Historic Places}}\n* [[List of bridges on the National Register of Historic Places in Kansas]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Cherokee County, Kansas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Rainbow Curve Bridge}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1923]]\n[[Category:Road bridges on the National Register of Historic Places in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Bridges on U.S. Route 66]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cherokee County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Through arch bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Concrete bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Kansas]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 66 in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the United States Numbered Highways]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Cherokee County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Brush Creek Bridge\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image = Rainbow Curve Bridge 2006-07-03.jpg\n  | caption = Rainbow Bridge\n  | nearest_city= [[Baxter Springs, Kansas]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|37|4|24.25|N|94|44|26.04|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Kansas#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1923\n| architect= [[James Barney Marsh]]\n | added = March 10, 1983\n | governing_body = Local\n | mpsub=Rainbow Arch Marsh Arch Bridges of Kansas TR\n | refnum=83000419<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n[[Image:Rainbow Marsh Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|Rainbow bridge over Brush Creek]]\nThe '''Rainbow Bridge''' is an old bridge over Brush Creek approximately two miles west of [[Riverton, Kansas]] on former [[U.S. Route 66 in Kansas|U.S. Route&nbsp;66]] (US-66), now a county road. The bridge is a single-span concrete [[James Barney Marsh|Marsh arch bridge]] and is the sole surviving bridge of this type on the entire length of the former highway. Two other Marsh arch bridges were also located on US-66 in Kansas, both over the [[Spring River (Missouri)|Spring River]]. It was built in 1923.\n\nThe bridge has often been covered with graffiti, but was recently re-painted white. The bridge has been placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (as the Brush Creek Bridge) on March 10, 1983, due to its connection with US-66 and is also a Kansas state landmark. In 2014, Kansas Rt. 66 Historic Byway nominated a bypassed {{convert|2.1|mi|km}} section of original 1926 highway, which ran south from the Brush Creek to the Willow Creek bridge near Baxter Springs, for an NRHP listing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kshs.org/preserve/pdfs/007_ks_cherokeecounty_route66.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223010729/http://www.kshs.org/preserve/pdfs/007_ks_cherokeecounty_route66.pdf |archivedate=2015-02-23 }}</ref>\n\nThe bridge is fairly narrow, and due to traffic on the road, a replacement bridge has been built. The road curves toward the new bridge toward [[Baxter Springs, Kansas|Baxter Springs]], but a short, one-way road carries traffic to the Rainbow Bridge, which may still be crossed. This was part of a compromise after a disagreement between the county and the Kansas Route 66 Association as federal funds used for construction of the new bridge required demolition of the old. The bridge had been listed with the National Register, which prohibited condemnation of the old bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofamerica.com/picturepages/66KS-7-Baxter-RainbowBridge.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710232110/http://www.legendsofamerica.com/picturepages/66KS-7-Baxter-RainbowBridge.html |archivedate=2012-07-10 }}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2000, country singer [[Brad Paisley]] performed \"[[Route 66 (song)|Route 66]]\" on the bridge for the [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] special, \"Route 66: Main Street America\".\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|Transport}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Engineering}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Kansas}}\n* {{Portal-inline|National Register of Historic Places}}\n* [[List of bridges on the National Register of Historic Places in Kansas]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Cherokee County, Kansas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Rainbow Curve Bridge}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1923]]\n[[Category:Road bridges on the National Register of Historic Places in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Bridges on U.S. Route 66]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cherokee County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Through arch bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Concrete bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Kansas]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 66 in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the United States Numbered Highways]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Cherokee County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Kansas]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rainbow_Bridge_(Kansas)"}
{"title_page": "Pawnee Rock", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =Pawnee Rock\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = Pawnee Rock 2013-09-26 14-17-58.jpg\n| caption = Monument at Pawnee Rock\n| nearest_city= [[Pawnee Rock, Kansas]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|38|16|19.57|N|98|58|53.33|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin=Kansas\n| area =\n| architect= \n| architecture= \n| added = December 29, 1970\n| governing_body = State\n| refnum=70000247<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pawnee Rock''', one of the most famous and beautiful landmarks on the [[Santa Fe Trail]], is located in Pawnee Rock State Park, just north of [[Pawnee Rock, Kansas]], United States. Originally over {{convert|150|ft|m}} tall, railroad construction stripped it of some 15 to {{convert|20|ft|m}} in height for road bed material.<ref name=nomi/>\nA memorial monument, picnic area, and pergola have been constructed on the top.  From the top of the pergola is a view the [[Arkansas river]] valley and the route of the Santa Fe trail.\nToday it is a prominence rising {{convert|50|or|60|ft|m}} above the surrounding plains.  Matt Field, who traveled the Santa Fe Trail in 1840, later wrote, \"''Pawnee Rock springs like a huge wart from the carpeted green of the prairie.\"''<ref name=nomi>Pankratz, Richard D. Pawnee Rock, National Register of Historic Places Inventory \u2013 Nomination Form; National Park Service; Washington D.C.; December 7, 1970 pgs 7</ref> Traders, soldiers, and emigrants who stopped, carved their names into the brown [[sandstone]].  Some of these names are still visible among the graffiti of the more recent visitors.<ref name=nomi/>\n\nPawnee Rock was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] around 1970. The site is administrated by the [[Kansas Historical Society]] as the '''Pawnee Rock State Historic Site'''.\n\n==History==\nPawnee Rock was long a meeting place of the Comanche, Kiowa, Arapaho and Cheyenne Indians. Numerous battles were fought at Pawnee Rock between the tribes, and as a result, many bones have been found in the soil in the vicinity.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00unse_4 | title=Biographical History of Barton County, Kansas | publisher=Great Bend Tribune | year=1912 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00unse_4/page/145 145]}}</ref>\nPawnee Rock was for many years a place where [[Comanche]], [[Kiowa]], [[Arapahoe|Arapaho]], [[Cheyenne]], and [[Pawnee people|Pawnee]] tribes held their councils of war and peace.  Many Indian battles were fought nearby in the days before the white men came to Kansas.<ref name=nomi/>\n\nIt served as a lookout for travelers on the [[Santa Fe Trail]], as well as a rendezvous and ambush for the Indians.  As a camping spot it afforded some protection against hostile Indians. Many travelers and traders on the Santa Fe trail considered Pawnee Rock the most dangerous place on the Central Plains for encounters with the Indians.<ref name=nomi/>\nMany of the Plains tribes reportedly used it as an observation point from which they could track and swoop down upon buffalo herds and wagon trains. It was also a landmark for travelers, marking the half waypoint between Missouri and Santa Fe.  In 1848, James Birch, a soldier on his way to the Mexican War, wrote: \"Pawnee Rock was covered with names carved by the men who had passed it. It was so full that I could find no place for mine.\" .<ref name=kansapedia>http://www.kshs.org/kansapedia/topic/place; kansapedia; Pawnee Rock; Kansas Historical Society; December 1969; August 2013(downloaded September 16, 2015)</ref>\n\n[[File:Pawnee Rock P5310475.JPG|thumb|Pawnee Rock, approaching from the east along the old Santa Fe Trail. Pawnee Rock, KS]]Much of Pawnee Rock was destroyed in the 1870s by the railroad and by settlers for building stone. The remnant was acquired in 1908 by the Woman's Kansas Day Club. In 1909, was given to the State of Kansas as an historic site. On May 24, 1912, a stone monument was dedicated with great celebration before a crowd of some 8,000 onlookers. Pawnee Rock was listed in the National Register of Historic Places in 1970 and today operates as Pawnee Rock State Historic Site.<ref name=kansapedia/><ref name=Arnold>Arnold, Anna E.; A History of Kansas; The State of Kansas, State Printing Plant; Topeka; 1914</ref>\n\n==Naming Pawnee Rock==\n[[File:Pawnee Rock P5310477.JPG|thumb|Pawnee Rock, Pawnee Rock, KS]]Many stories have been told to explain how Pawnee Rock got its name. One source for the name comes from the belief that was sacred ground for the [[Pawnee Indians]] who held tribal councils on its flat top. Another from a great battle in which a small band of Pawnees were destroyed by a force of [[Kiowas]], [[Cheyennes]], and [[Arapahos]]. Both come from Pawnee lore. Among the [[frontiersman|plainsmen]] it is said that the Rock got its name in 1826.  [[Kit Carson]] was on his first trip west and only seventeen. He was working his passage on a wagon train which near the Rock. While on guard duty, he shot his own mule, thinking it was an attacking Pawnee. His associates commemorated his experience with the name, Pawnee Rock.<ref name=kansapedia/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n[[File:Waysides P5310507.JPG|thumb|Interpretive Trail around the rim of Pawnee Rock, Pawnee Rock State Park]]\n*Biographical History of Barton County, Kansas; Tribune Publishing Co.; Great Bend, Kansas; 1912 p 145\n*Blackmar, Frank W.; Kansas, A cyclopedia of State History, V. 2; Chicago Standard Publishing Col; 1912; pp 455\u2013457\n*Porter, Clyde & Mae Reed and John E. Sunder; Matt Field on the Santa Fe Trail; University of Oklahoma Press; Norman, Oklahoma; 1960\n*Survey of Historic Sites and Structures in Kansas; Kansas State Historical Society; Topeka, Kansas; 1957\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pawnee Rock State Park}}\n* [http://www.kshs.org/places/pawneerock/ Pawnee Rock] Kansas State Historical Society.\n* [http://www.santafetrailresearch.com/ Santa Fe Trail Research]\n\n[[Category:Protected areas of Barton County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Santa Fe Trail]]\n[[Category:Geography of Kansas]]\n[[Category:Kansas state historic sites]]\n[[Category:Natural features on the National Register of Historic Places in Kansas]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Barton County, Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =Pawnee Rock\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = Pawnee Rock 2013-09-26 14-17-58.jpg\n| caption = Monument at Pawnee Rock\n| nearest_city= [[Pawnee Rock, Kansas]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|38|16|19.57|N|98|58|53.33|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin=Kansas\n| area =\n| architect= \n| architecture= \n| added = December 29, 1970\n| governing_body = State\n| refnum=70000247<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pawnee Rock''', one of the most famous and beautiful landmarks on the [[Santa Fe Trail]], is located in Pawnee Rock State Park, just north of [[Pawnee Rock, Kansas]], United States. Originally over {{convert|150|ft|m}} tall, railroad construction stripped it of some 15 to {{convert|20|ft|m}} in height for road bed material.<ref name=nomi/>\nA memorial monument, picnic area, and pergola have been constructed on the top.  From the top of the pergola is a view the [[Arkansas river]] valley and the route of the Santa Fe trail.\nToday it is a prominence rising {{convert|50|or|60|ft|m}} above the surrounding plains.  Matt Field, who traveled the Santa Fe Trail in 1840, later wrote, \"''Pawnee Rock springs like a huge wart from the carpeted green of the prairie.\"''<ref name=nomi>Pankratz, Richard D. Pawnee Rock, National Register of Historic Places Inventory \u2013 Nomination Form; National Park Service; Washington D.C.; December 7, 1970 pgs 7</ref> Traders, soldiers, and emigrants who stopped, carved their names into the brown [[sandstone]].  Some of these names are still visible among the graffiti of the more recent visitors.<ref name=nomi/>\n\nPawnee Rock was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] around 1970. The site is administrated by the [[Kansas Historical Society]] as the '''Pawnee Rock State Historic Site'''.\n\n==History==\nPawnee Rock was long a meeting place of the Comanche, Kiowa, Arapaho and Cheyenne Indians. Numerous battles were fought at Pawnee Rock between the tribes, and as a result, many bones have been found in the soil in the vicinity.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00unse_4 | title=Biographical History of Barton County, Kansas | publisher=Great Bend Tribune | year=1912 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00unse_4/page/145 145]}}</ref>\nPawnee Rock was for many years a place where [[Comanche]], [[Kiowa]], [[Arapahoe|Arapaho]], [[Cheyenne]], and [[Pawnee people|Pawnee]] tribes held their councils of war and peace.  Many Indian battles were fought nearby in the days before the white men came to Kansas.<ref name=nomi/>\n\nIt served as a lookout for travelers on the [[Santa Fe Trail]], as well as a rendezvous and ambush for the Indians.  As a camping spot it afforded some protection against hostile Indians. Many travelers and traders on the Santa Fe trail considered Pawnee Rock the most dangerous place on the Central Plains for encounters with the Indians.<ref name=nomi/>\nMany of the Plains tribes reportedly used it as an observation point from which they could track and swoop down upon buffalo herds and wagon trains. It was also a landmark for travelers, marking the half waypoint between Missouri and Santa Fe.  In 1848, James Birch, a soldier on his way to the Mexican War, wrote: \"Pawnee Rock was covered with names carved by the men who had passed it. It was so full that I could find no place for mine.\" .<ref name=kansapedia>http://www.kshs.org/kansapedia/topic/place; kansapedia; Pawnee Rock; Kansas Historical Society; December 1969; August 2013(downloaded September 16, 2015)</ref>\n\n[[File:Pawnee Rock P5310475.JPG|thumb|Pawnee Rock, approaching from the east along the old Santa Fe Trail. Pawnee Rock, KS]]Much of Pawnee Rock was destroyed in the 1870s by the railroad and by settlers for building stone. The remnant was acquired in 1908 by the Woman's Kansas Day Club. In 1909, was given to the State of Kansas as an historic site. On May 24, 1912, a stone monument was dedicated with great celebration before a crowd of some 8,000 onlookers. Pawnee Rock was listed in the National Register of Historic Places in 1970 and today operates as Pawnee Rock State Historic Site.<ref name=kansapedia/><ref name=Arnold>Arnold, Anna E.; A History of Kansas; The State of Kansas, State Printing Plant; Topeka; 1914</ref>\n\n==Naming Pawnee Rock==\n[[File:Pawnee Rock P5310477.JPG|thumb|Pawnee Rock, Pawnee Rock, KS]]Many stories have been told to explain how Pawnee Rock got its name. One source for the name comes from the belief that was sacred ground for the [[Pawnee Indians]] who held tribal councils on its flat top. Another from a great battle in which a small band of Pawnees were destroyed by a force of [[Kiowas]], [[Cheyennes]], and [[Arapahos]]. Both come from Pawnee lore. Among the [[frontiersman|plainsmen]] it is said that the Rock got its name in 1826.  [[Kit Carson]] was on his first trip west and only seventeen. He was working his passage on a wagon train which near the Rock. While on guard duty, he shot his own mule, thinking it was an attacking Pawnee. His associates commemorated his experience with the name, Pawnee Rock.<ref name=kansapedia/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n[[File:Waysides P5310507.JPG|thumb|Interpretive Trail around the rim of Pawnee Rock, Pawnee Rock State Park]]\n*Biographical History of Barton County, Kansas; Tribune Publishing Co.; Great Bend, Kansas; 1912 p 145\n*Blackmar, Frank W.; Kansas, A cyclopedia of State History, V. 2; Chicago Standard Publishing Col; 1912; pp 455\u2013457\n*Porter, Clyde & Mae Reed and John E. Sunder; Matt Field on the Santa Fe Trail; University of Oklahoma Press; Norman, Oklahoma; 1960\n*Survey of Historic Sites and Structures in Kansas; Kansas State Historical Society; Topeka, Kansas; 1957\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pawnee Rock State Park}}\n* [http://www.kshs.org/places/pawneerock/ Pawnee Rock] Kansas State Historical Society.\n* [http://www.santafetrailresearch.com/ Santa Fe Trail Research]\n\n[[Category:Protected areas of Barton County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Santa Fe Trail]]\n[[Category:Geography of Kansas]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Kansas state historic sites]]\n[[Category:Natural features on the National Register of Historic Places in Kansas]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Barton County, Kansas]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pawnee_Rock"}
{"title_page": "Mexcala elegans", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{taxobox\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum  = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Arachnid]]a\n| ordo = [[spider|Araneae]]\n| familia = [[Salticidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Mexcala]]''\n| species = ''M. elegans''\n| binomial = ''Mexcala elegans''\n| binomial_authority = [[George and Elizabeth Peckham|Peckham & Peckham]], 1903<ref>New species of the family Attidae from South Africa, with notes on the distribution of the genera found in the Ethiopian region. GW Peckham, EG Peckham - Transactions of the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences \u2026, 1903</ref>\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = \n| range_map = \n}}\n\n'''''Mexcala elegans''''' is a species of [[spider]]s in the jumping spider family, [[Salticidae]]. It is found in [[Southern Africa]]. It is preying on ants.<ref>Trophic strategy of ant-eating Mexcala elegans (Araneae: Salticidae): looking for evidence of evolution of prey-specialization. Stano Pek\u00e1r and Charles Haddad, Journal of Arachnology, 39(1), pages 133-138, 2011, {{doi|10.1636/Hi10-56.1}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* [http://www.jumping-spiders.com/index_wiki.php?id=2816 ''Mexcala elegans''] at jumping-spiders.com\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2419979}}\n\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Africa]]\n[[Category:Arthropods of Southern Africa]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1903]]\n\n\n{{salticidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{taxobox\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum  = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Arachnid]]a\n| ordo = [[spider|Araneae]]\n| familia = [[Salticidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Mexcala]]''\n| species = ''M. elegans''\n| binomial = ''Mexcala elegans''\n| binomial_authority = [[George and Elizabeth Peckham|Peckham & Peckham]], 1903<ref>New species of the family Attidae from South Africa, with notes on the distribution of the genera found in the Ethiopian region. GW Peckham, EG Peckham - Transactions of the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences \u2026, 1903</ref>\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = \n| range_map = \n}}\n\n'''''Mexcala elegans''''' is a species of [[spider]]s in the [[Salticidae]] family (jumping spiders). It is found in [[Southern Africa]]. It is preying on ants.<ref>Trophic strategy of ant-eating Mexcala elegans (Araneae: Salticidae): looking for evidence of evolution of prey-specialization. Stano Pek\u00e1r and Charles Haddad, Journal of Arachnology, 39(1), pages 133-138, 2011, {{doi|10.1636/Hi10-56.1}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* [http://www.jumping-spiders.com/index_wiki.php?id=2816 ''Mexcala elegans''] at jumping-spiders.com\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2419979}}\n\n[[Category:Salticidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Africa]]\n[[Category:Arthropods of Southern Africa]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1903]]\n\n\n{{salticidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexcala_elegans"}
{"title_page": "Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s 500 Greatest Albums of All Time}}\n<!-- For copyright reasons, DO NOT COPY ANY PORTION OF THE LIST HERE. If you want to see the list, use the external link. Feel free to mention where individual albums ranked in the articles about them.-->\n[[File:500greatestalbumsofalltime.JPG|right|thumb|''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s \"500 Greatest Albums of All Time\" magazine cover]]\n\"'''The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time'''\" is a 2003 special issue of American magazine ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and a related book published in 2005.<ref name=\"RS500\">{{cite book\n| editor-last=Levy\n| editor-first=Joe\n| editor2-last=Van Zandt\n| editor2-first=Steven\n| editor2-link=Steven Van Zandt\n|title=Rolling Stone 500 Greatest Albums of All Time\n|origyear=2005\n|edition=3rd\n|year=2006\n|publisher=Turnaround\n|location=London\n|isbn=1-932958-61-4\n|oclc=70672814\n|ref=RS500\n}}\n<br />'''Related news articles:'''\n*{{cite news\n|date=December 11, 2003\n|title=The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time\n| newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]]\n| issue = 937\n| pages=83&ndash;178\n|publisher=Straight Arrow\n|issn=0035-791X\n|oclc=1787396\n}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/\n|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time\n|accessdate=2010-07-01\n|publisher=Rolling Stone\n| work=rollingstone.com\n}}</ref> The lists were compiled based on votes from selected [[rock music]]ians, critics, and industry figures. The lists predominantly feature American and British music from the 1960s and the 1970s, topped by [[the Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', with a top 10 that featured four entries from the Beatles (Nos. 1, 3, 5 and 10), two from [[Bob Dylan]] (No. 4 and 9), and one each from [[the Beach Boys]] (No. 2), [[Marvin Gaye]] (No. 6), the [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] (No. 7) and [[the Clash]] (No. 8).\n\nIn 2012, ''Rolling Stone'' published a revised edition of the list drawing on the original and a later survey of albums up until the early 2000s.<ref name=\"rs500list\">{{cite web|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531|date=May 31, 2012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> It was made available in \"bookazine\" format on newsstands in the US from April 27 to July 25. The new list contained 38 albums not present in the previous one, 16 of them released after 2003.\n\n==Background==\nThe first version of the list, published as a magazine in November 2003, was based on the votes of 273 rock musicians, critics, and industry figures, each of whom submitted a weighted list of 50 albums. The accounting firm [[Ernst & Young]] devised a point system to weigh votes for 1,600 submitted titles. The list includes a few compilations, and \"greatest hits\" collections.<ref name=\"cite-2\">[https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2003-11-16-rolling-stone-list_x.htm \"It's Certainly a Thrill: Sgt. Pepper Is Best Album\"], ''USA Today'', November 17, 2003.</ref>\n\nThe following authors contributed to the citations made of each album:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Pat Blashill\n* [[Anthony DeCurtis]]\n* Ben Edmonds\n* Gavin Edwards\n* [[Jenny Eliscu]]\n* [[David Fricke]]\n* [[Mark Kemp]]\n* [[Greg Kot]]\n* Joe Levy\n* Parke Puterbaugh\n* [[Austin Scaggs]]\n* Karen Schoemer\n* Bud Scoppa\n* [[Rob Sheffield]]\n* David Thigpen\n* Barry Walters\n* Tammy Mustafa\n{{div col end}}\n\nAn amended list was released in book form in 2005, with an introduction written by [[Steven Van Zandt]]. As the editor's foreword explains, some compilation albums were removed, and [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson's]] ''[[The Complete Recordings (Robert Johnson album)|The Complete Recordings]]'' was substituted for both of his ''[[King of the Delta Blues Singers]]'' volumes, making room for a total of eight new entries on the list. ''The Complete Recordings'' would be reinstated to the list in the 2012 edition.\n\n==List statistics==\n<!-- For copyright reasons, DO NOT COPY ANY PORTION OF THE LIST HERE. If you want to see the list, use the external link. Feel free to mention where individual albums ranked in the articles about them.-->\n\n===Top ten===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:0.95em; line-height:1.5em;\"\n |-\n ! Number !! Artist !! Album\n|- \n|1 || [[The Beatles]] || ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''\n|- \n|2 || [[The Beach Boys]] ||  ''[[Pet Sounds]]''\n|- \n|3 || [[The Beatles]] ||  ''[[Revolver (Beatles album)|Revolver]]''\n|- \n|4 || [[Bob Dylan]] ||  ''[[Highway 61 Revisited]]''\n|- \n|5 || [[The Beatles]] ||  ''[[Rubber Soul]]''\n|- \n|6 || [[Marvin Gaye]] ||  ''[[What's Going On (Marvin Gaye album)|What\u2019s Going On]]''\n|- \n|7 || [[The Rolling Stones]] ||  ''[[Exile on Main Street]]''\n|- \n|8 || [[The Clash]] ||  ''[[London Calling]]''\n|- \n|9 || [[Bob Dylan]] ||  ''[[Blonde on Blonde]]''\n|- \n|10 || [[The Beatles]] ||  ''[[The Beatles (album)|The Beatles]]''\n |}\n\n===Number of albums from each decade===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:0.95em; line-height:1.5em;\"\n |-\n ! Decade !! Number of albums !! Percentage\n |-\n | 1950s || 10 || 2.0%\n |-\n | 1960s || 105 || 21.0%\n |-\n | 1970s || 186 || 37.2%\n |-\n | 1980s || 84 || 16.8%\n |-\n | 1990s || 73 || 14.6%\n |-\n | 2000s || 40 || 8.0%\n |-\n | 2010s || 2 || 0.4%\n |}\n\n===Artists with the most albums===\n\n'''11 albums'''\n* [[Bob Dylan]] (one credited to Bob Dylan and [[the Band]]; two in the top 10 including the No. 9 and No. 4 spots)\n\n'''10 albums'''\n* [[The Beatles]] (four in the top 10 including the No. 10, No. 5, No. 3, and No. 1 spots)\n* [[The Rolling Stones]] (one in the top 10 at the No. 7 spot)\n\n'''8 albums'''\n* [[Bruce Springsteen]]\n\n'''7 albums'''\n* [[The Who]]\n\n'''6 albums'''\n* [[David Bowie]]\n* [[Elton John]]\n\n''' 5 albums'''\n* [[Led Zeppelin]]\n* [[Bob Marley and the Wailers]]\n* [[Radiohead]]\n* [[U2]]\n* [[Neil Young]] (two credited to Neil Young and [[Crazy Horse (band)|Crazy Horse]])\n\n'''4 albums'''\n* [[James Brown]]\n* [[The Byrds]]\n* [[Elvis Costello]] (three credited with [[the Attractions]])\n* [[Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Pink Floyd]]\n* [[The Police]]\n* [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]\n* [[Otis Redding]] \n* [[Roxy Music]]\n* [[Sly and the Family Stone]]\n* [[The Smiths]]\n* [[Talking Heads]]\n* [[Stevie Wonder]]\n* [[The Velvet Underground]] (one album credited with [[Nico]])\n\n'''3 albums'''\n* [[The Band]] (one credited to Bob Dylan and The Band)\n* [[The Beach Boys]] (one in the top 10 at the No. 2 spot)\n* [[Big Star]]\n* [[Black Sabbath]]\n* [[Jackson Browne]]\n* [[Ray Charles]]\n* [[The Clash]] (one in the top 10 at the No. 8 spot)\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] (two with [[Funkadelic]], one with [[Parliament (band)|Parliament]])\n* [[Cream (band)|Cream]]\n* [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]] (in 2003 edition)\n* [[Miles Davis]]\n* [[The Doors]]\n* [[Nick Drake]] (in 2003 edition)\n* [[Eminem]] (in 2003 edition)\n* [[Marvin Gaye]] (one in the top 10 at the No. 6 spot)\n* [[Al Green]]\n* [[The Jimi Hendrix Experience]]\n* [[Michael Jackson]]\n* [[The Kinks]]\n* [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n* [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n* [[Randy Newman]]\n* [[Elvis Presley]]\n* [[Public Enemy (group)|Public Enemy]] (in 2003 edition)\n* [[R.E.M.]]\n* [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] (in 2012 edition)\n* [[Simon & Garfunkel]]\n* [[Steely Dan]]\n* [[The Stooges]]\n* [[Tom Waits]]\n* [[Muddy Waters]] \n* [[Kanye West]] (in 2012 edition)\n* [[Jay Z]]\n\n==Reception==\nWriting in ''[[USA Today]]'' newspaper, [[Edna Gundersen]] described the list as predictable and \"weighted toward testosterone-fueled vintage rock\". The ''Rolling Stone'' 500 has also been criticised for being male-dominated, outmoded and almost entirely Anglo-American in focus.<ref>Biron, Dean. 2011. Towards a Popular Music Criticism of Replenishment. ''Popular Music & Society'', 34/5: 661\u2013682.</ref><ref>Schmutz, Vaughan. 2005. Retrospective Critical Consecration in Popular Music: Rolling Stone's Greatest Albums of All Time. ''American Behavioral Scientist'', 48/11: 1510\u20131523.</ref> Jonny Sharp, a contributor to [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|''NME''{{'}}s own 500 greatest albums list]], described the ''Rolling Stone'' list as a \"soulless, canon-centric [list] of the same tired old titles,\" noting: \"looking at their 500, when the only album in their top 10 less than 40 years old is ''[[London Calling]]'', I think I prefer the ''NME'''s less critically-correct approach.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharp |first1=Johnny |title=Mission Impossible: My 'NME 500 Greatest Albums' Voting Hell |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/13683-nme-greatest-albums-list-johnny-sharp-cigarettes |website=The Quietus |accessdate=January 1, 2020 |date=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the publicity surrounding the list, rock critic [[Jim DeRogatis]], a former ''Rolling Stone'' editor, published ''Kill Your Idols: A New Generation of Rock Writers Reconsiders the Classics'' in 2004. This featured a number of generally younger critics arguing against the high evaluation of various \"great\" albums, some of which had been included in the list, including DeRogatis taking on ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', which had been ''Rolling Stone''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s top choice.<ref>({{ISBN|1-56980-276-9}})</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|''NME'''s The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]], a similar list\n* [[All Time Top 1000 Albums]], a similar list\n* [[Rolling Stone's 100 Greatest Songwriters of All Time|The 100 Greatest Songwriters of All Time]], also from ''Rolling Stone'' magazine\n* [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]], also from ''Rolling Stone'' magazine\n* [[Rolling Stone's 100 Greatest Artists of All Time|The 100 Greatest Artists of All Time]], also from ''Rolling Stone'' magazine\n* [[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]], a similar list, ordered by time period\n* [[List of greatest hits albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--A link to the list is specifically allowed in [[WP:ELYES]] under both ELYES#2 and ELYES#3 -->\n*[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531 500 Greatest Albums of All Time], ''Rolling Stone'' \n<!-- Note that this list is not identical to the list in the book -->\n<!-- For copyright reasons, DO NOT COPY THE LIST HERE. If you want to see the full list, use the external link. Feel free to mention where individual albums ranked in the articles about them.-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:500 Greatest Albums Of All Time}}\n[[Category:Lists of albums]]\n[[Category:Rolling Stone articles]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s 500 Greatest Albums of All Time}}\n<!-- For copyright reasons, DO NOT COPY ANY PORTION OF THE LIST HERE. If you want to see the list, use the external link. Feel free to mention where individual albums ranked in the articles about them.-->\n[[File:500greatestalbumsofalltime.JPG|right|thumb|''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s \"500 Greatest Albums of All Time\" magazine cover]]\n\"'''The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time'''\" is a 2003 special issue of American magazine ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and a related book published in 2005.<ref name=\"RS500\">{{cite book\n| editor-last=Levy\n| editor-first=Joe\n| editor2-last=Van Zandt\n| editor2-first=Steven\n| editor2-link=Steven Van Zandt\n|title=Rolling Stone 500 Greatest Albums of All Time\n|origyear=2005\n|edition=3rd\n|year=2006\n|publisher=Turnaround\n|location=London\n|isbn=1-932958-61-4\n|oclc=70672814\n|ref=RS500\n}}\n<br />'''Related news articles:'''\n*{{cite news\n|date=December 11, 2003\n|title=The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time\n| newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]]\n| issue = 937\n| pages=83&ndash;178\n|publisher=Straight Arrow\n|issn=0035-791X\n|oclc=1787396\n}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/\n|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time\n|accessdate=2010-07-01\n|publisher=Rolling Stone\n| work=rollingstone.com\n}}</ref> The lists were compiled based on votes from selected [[rock music]]ians, critics, and industry figures. The lists predominantly feature American and British music from the 1960s and the 1970s, topped by [[the Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', with a top 10 that featured four entries from the Beatles (Nos. 1, 3, 5 and 10), two from [[Bob Dylan]] (No. 4 and 9), and one each from [[the Beach Boys]] (No. 2), [[Marvin Gaye]] (No. 6), the [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] (No. 7) and [[the Clash]] (No. 8).\n\nIn 2012, ''Rolling Stone'' published a revised edition of the list drawing on the original and a later survey of albums up until the early 2000s.<ref name=\"rs500list\">{{cite web|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531|date=May 31, 2012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> It was made available in \"bookazine\" format on newsstands in the US from April 27 to July 25. The new list contained 38 albums not present in the previous one, 16 of them released after 2003.\n\n==Background==\nThe first version of the list, published as a magazine in November 2003, was based on the votes of 273 rock musicians, critics, and industry figures, each of whom submitted a weighted list of 50 albums. The accounting firm [[Ernst & Young]] devised a point system to weigh votes for 1,600 submitted titles. The list includes a few compilations, and \"greatest hits\" collections.<ref name=\"cite-2\">[https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2003-11-16-rolling-stone-list_x.htm \"It's Certainly a Thrill: Sgt. Pepper Is Best Album\"], ''USA Today'', November 17, 2003.</ref>\n\nThe following authors contributed to the citations made of each album:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Pat Blashill\n* [[Anthony DeCurtis]]\n* Ben Edmonds\n* Gavin Edwards\n* [[Jenny Eliscu]]\n* [[David Fricke]]\n* [[Mark Kemp]]\n* [[Greg Kot]]\n* Joe Levy\n* Parke Puterbaugh\n* [[Austin Scaggs]]\n* Karen Schoemer\n* Bud Scoppa\n* [[Rob Sheffield]]\n* David Thigpen\n* Barry Walters\n* Tammy Mustafa\n{{div col end}}\n\nAn amended list was released in book form in 2005, with an introduction written by [[Steven Van Zandt]]. As the editor's foreword explains, some compilation albums were removed, and [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson's]] ''[[The Complete Recordings (Robert Johnson album)|The Complete Recordings]]'' was substituted for both of his ''[[King of the Delta Blues Singers]]'' volumes, making room for a total of eight new entries on the list. ''The Complete Recordings'' would be reinstated to the list in the 2012 edition.\n\n==List statistics==\n<!-- For copyright reasons, DO NOT COPY ANY PORTION OF THE LIST HERE. If you want to see the list, use the external link. Feel free to mention where individual albums ranked in the articles about them.-->\n\n===Number of albums from each decade===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:0.95em; line-height:1.5em;\"\n |-\n ! Decade !! Number of albums !! Percentage\n |-\n | 1950s || 10 || 2.0%\n |-\n | 1960s || 105 || 21.0%\n |-\n | 1970s || 186 || 37.2%\n |-\n | 1980s || 84 || 16.8%\n |-\n | 1990s || 73 || 14.6%\n |-\n | 2000s || 40 || 8.0%\n |-\n | 2010s || 2 || 0.4%\n |}\n\n===Artists with the most albums===\n\n'''11 albums'''\n* [[Bob Dylan]] (one credited to Bob Dylan and [[the Band]]; two in the top 10 including the No. 9 and No. 4 spots)\n\n'''10 albums'''\n* [[The Beatles]] (four in the top 10 including the No. 10, No. 5, No. 3, and No. 1 spots)\n* [[The Rolling Stones]] (one in the top 10 at the No. 7 spot)\n\n'''8 albums'''\n* [[